<SECOND>AM-Gulf-Hostages,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Condemned, Calls for U.S. Restraint</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> on Wednesday denounced both the Israeli kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem cleric and the killing of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Col. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>. The official Saudi press agency quoted `` a responsible source'' as saying <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION> `` always condemns and denounces terrorist acts of all forms and of whatever methods ... These are despicable, inhuman acts.'' Arab media criticized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for abducting <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Karim </PERSON> <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON> from south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> Friday and urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to show restraint amid reports of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fleet movements in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. The Dubai-based <ORGANIZATION> Al-Bayan </ORGANIZATION> wrote in an editorial: `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has flung the doors of hell wide open.'' `` What is the objective behind the Israeli act which can only be classified as organized state terrorism?'' asked <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhabi </PERSON>'s state-run <ORGANIZATION> Al-Ittihad </ORGANIZATION> daily The hard-line newspaper Al-Khaleej, in neighboring <LOCATION> Sharjah </LOCATION> emirate, said `` the Zionist terrorist operation in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and its repercussions must be attributed to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in the region and the full and unconditional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bias toward <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' The <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> newspaper Al-Rai Al-Aam cautioned the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> against a military response to <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' purported hanging. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not possess many effective means for a speedy revenge of the hanging of a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> colonel by a group operating in a country with usurped sovereignty such as <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` An effective military action is impossible in a country overburdened with rocket launchers, artillery, tanks, bombs, booby-trapped cars and suicide squads, which could be mobilized in any reaction to an American retaliatory strike,'' it wrote. <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>'s leading Al-Watan newspaper said `` blame should be pinned on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as it is the instrument of violence in the region.'' Al-Watan and other <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> newspapers, urged self-restraint in the crisis. The newspapers noted that an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> committee announced an impasse in efforts to end <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war. The <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Raya </ORGANIZATION> said that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> could exploit the situation `` to direct a major blow against <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'' that could lead to its `` partition into small states after internationalization of its crisis.'' <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> voiced `` surprise and outrage'' at claims of <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' death but blamed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for abducting <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON> and refusing to free him <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> offered to exchange <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON> and Shiite Moslem prisoners it holds for three <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> servicemen and all 16 foreign hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ally and at peace with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, urged `` all parties concerned, whether regional or international, to exercise extreme self-restraint.''
