<HEAD>`Cheers,' `13 East' Lead NBC to 58th Consecutive Ratings Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> might have flopped with its nurse drama `` Nightingales,'' but its summer nurse comedy `` 13 East'' finished in the Top 10, helping the network win another Nielsen ratings derby victory. For the week ended July 30, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Cheers'' landed in first place for the fourth time in five weeks, narrowly topping <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Roseanne. `` Cheers'' had a rating of 17.5, only one-tenth of a point ahead of `` Roseanne.'' Last week they tied for first place at 17.4. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> easily won the week for its 58th straight victory in the <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> survey. The only surprise in the Top 10 was the appearance of lightly regarded `` 13 East,'' which finished 10th. Other than CBS' `` 60 Minutes'' and `` Murder, She Wrote,'' all the shows in the Top 10 were comedies. The ratings are certainly proof of the resurgence of the situation comedy, which was all but written off a few years ago. Prime-time soap operas like `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>'' and `` Dynasty'' dominated the ratings until the appearance of `` The Cosby Show'' in 1984. In the 1983-84 season the only comedy in the Top 10 was <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` Kate & amp; <PERSON> Allie </PERSON>.'' Comedy also dominated the second 10 highest-rated shows this past week with seven entries. Here are the Top 10: <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Cheers,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Roseanne,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Cosby Show,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` A Different World,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Dear <PERSON> John </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Golden Girls'' and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` 60 Minutes'' tied, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> `` Murder, She Wrote,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Wonder Years'' and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` 13 East <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> continued its summer surge in the ratings. `` Married ... With Children'' was in 29th place, `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Most Wanted'' was tied for 34th and `` Totally Hidden Video'' was tied for 39th place. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> was first with an average of 10.8, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> was second with 8.9 and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> was third with 8.7. The averages since the fall season began on Sept. 19 were: <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> 14.8, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> 11.9 and CBS 11.8. The ratings is the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with television. The share is the percentage of sets in use. The <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> summer show, `` Knight and <PERSON> Daye </PERSON>,'' did not fare that well in the ratings. It was in 37th place. The lowest-rated show on the three networks was <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` American Nuclear.'' Here are the bottom five: CBS' `` Tour of Duty,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frankie </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Trans-Antarctica Expedition'' and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` American Nuclear <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> had the highest-rated evening news show. The ratings: CBS 9.0, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> 8.8 and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> 8.6.
