<FIRST>u a AM-CourthouseHostage     08-02 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Courthouse Hostage,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Holding Hostage in Courtroom Kills Her, Then Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An ex-sheriff's deputy held his former girlfriend hostage in a courtroom for nearly seven hours Tuesday, then killed himself and her, authorities said. Officials and bystanders heard two muffled shots at 9:45 p.m. from the courtroom where <PERSON> Manny </PERSON> <PERSON> Cabano </PERSON> seized <PERSON> Juanita </PERSON> <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON>, a county clerk who had obtained a restraining order against Cabano the day before. Paramedics and sheriff's authorities then rushed in and found Cabano dead, with a gunshot wound to the head, and Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON> critically wounded. Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON> was taken to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> <PERSON> Hospital </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, where she died at 10:17 p.m. while undergoing emergency surgery, said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, night administrator. Both victims were in their 40s. Cabano used a .44 - caliber pistol he'd taken to the courtroom in the suicide-murder, said <LOCATION> Tarrant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cabano </PERSON> had also seized a .38 - caliber pistol from the justice of the peace in whose courtroom Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON> The gunman apparently went to Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON>'s home and opened her mail, finding court papers relating to the restraining order, before storming the courtroom, sheriff's officials said. The standoff began when <PERSON> Cabano </PERSON> grabbed the woman in Justice of the Peace <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON>'s first-floor courtroom at the <LOCATION> Tarrant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Courthouse </LOCATION> at about 3 p.m. Police negotiated with <PERSON> Cabano </PERSON>, sometimes through Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON>, via telephone during the standoff. Wise said talks with Cabano were improving about 8 p.m. and authorities thought the situation would end without bloodshed. `` Our hopes were building,'' he said. But then Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON> came on the line and `` she requested that she talk to her boys. That's always a bad sign.'' Wise did n't say whether Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON> was able to speak to her children. Police special weapons and tactics units were dispatched to the scene but left about 5 p.m., when the Sheriff's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said they would take over, said <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> police spokesman <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>. `` Judge <PERSON> Ashmore </PERSON> said he worked with the man and knew him. The sheriff said he worked with him and knew him,'' <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> said. A sheriff's department dispatcher who did not wish to be identified said <PERSON> Cabano </PERSON> `` worked here as a deputy years and years ago. He then became a bail bondsman until he went bankrupt about a year ago.'' Four of Ms. <PERSON> Hermosilla </PERSON>'s five children, some in their teens, rushed to the courthouse about 5 p.m., but were taken away by several of her co-workers. Police blocked off the area and evacuated about 300 people in the courthouse and the City Administration Building across the street.
