<TEXT>
 Pepper, a liberal champion of the elderly and poor, drew no opposition in 1988. He died May 30 at age 88, and his death left the Republicans with a 10-8 majority in the state's congressional delegation. The district includes the retirement communities of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, predominantly black neighborhoods such as <LOCATION> Liberty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, heavily <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> neighborhoods and affluent <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>. The elections office said the district's 100,198 registered Democrats comprised 16,028 Hispanics, 32,183 blacks and 51,987 non-Latin whites. The 71,620 registered Republicans comprised 46,738 Hispanics, 23,656 non-Latin whites, and 1,226 blacks. But the figures for Hispanics are low, because the office counts only those who were born in Hispanic nations. Unofficial estimates that include second-generation Hispanics run to about half of the registered voters. Ms. <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON>, an educator and conservative married to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehtinen </PERSON>, led candidates in fund-raising with more than $ 200,000 reported as of July 20. She avoided joint appearances with <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, a businessman and fervent supporter of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> adviser who endorsed <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, whose former husband is <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, an ex-mayor of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and one of her top political advisers, was criticized in the campaign's final week for negative mailings aimed at Ms. Pepper and <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>. She was endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZ