<HEAD>Leading Newspaper Chain Ends 40-Year Snub of East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Since East <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> was founded 40 years ago, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s largest publishing chain has snubbed its socialist sibling by placing quotation marks around every reference to the state. But starting today, <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> newspapers and magazines will end the practice that has irked authorities in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> officials said. The quotation marks have cost the publishing empire journalistic accreditation in the neighboring socialist state and readership among much of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s left-leaning populace. But far from conceding defeat in the ideological battle, the publishers contend the war against the division of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> continues. `` The hope for reunification is unshaken,'' <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Schell </PERSON>, editor-in-chief of the conservative daily <ORGANIZATION> Die </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welt </ORGANIZATION> wrote today. But, in light of changes in East-West relations, the barriers to improving the flow of information between the political blocs must fall, <PERSON> Schell </PERSON> said. The giant <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> publishing network includes <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s largest-circulation daily, Hamburg-based <ORGANIZATION> Bild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeitung </ORGANIZATION>, which sells nearly 5 million copies daily It also includes the influential <PERSON> Berliner </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgenpost </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>'s Die Welt. Despite <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>'s broad audience, its journalists have been denied accreditation to work in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> on the grounds that the company's editorial policies are insulting to the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> government. A spokesman for the East German <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the government had no immediate comment on <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>'s reversal. <PERSON> Schell </PERSON> hinted in his editorial that the newspaper considered the dropped quotation marks a step toward gaining permission to report from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Referring to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> as `` DDR,'' the German abbreviation for <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Demokratische </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republik </ORGANIZATION>, was the protest of the publishing chain's founder, <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>, who died nearly four years ago. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s division after World War II weighed heavily on <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>, who moved his prospering business from his native <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> in 1967. After construction of the Berlin Wall in 1961, he put up a lighted readerboard to flash news from the West across the barrier. <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> also issued political and moral guidelines for the publications in 1967, and the first and foremost called for the reunification of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. From the 1949 founding of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> publications refused to acknowledge the socialist government and the quotation marks demonstrated their disdain. Die Welt administrative chief <PERSON> Jens </PERSON> <PERSON> Lueddeke </PERSON> said other West German publications also initially declined to acknowledge East German statehood, using similar quote marks or skeptical references to the government. But most dropped the practice after <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> recognized the east in 1970. <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> editors concede now that the quotation marks have now lost their meaning and in some cases simply confuse readers. Circulation of <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>'s main dailies has fallen by as much as 10 percent over the past few years, and many attribute the drop to shifts within the West German populace toward detente with nations of the Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>. `` The number of people who can recall adult life in a unified <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is a minority,'' <ORGANIZATION> Die </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welt </ORGANIZATION> editor <PERSON> Schell </PERSON> wrote. `` With this step we come to grips with the developments in East and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, in particular the reform efforts in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Schell </PERSON> said.
