<FIRST>r a PM-Judge-Conflict     08-02 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge-Conflict,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Reprimanded Over Conflict of Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge who was reprimanded for ruling on two <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> cases while owning <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> stock said he will institute safeguards to prevent it from happening again. A judicial panel determined that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> violated the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Judicial Code of Ethics by ruling in the cases, according to documents obtained Tuesday by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The code requires judges to disqualify themselves from any case in which they have a personal or financial interest. In a letter, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON>, chief judge of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, admonished <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> to `` increase your diligence in searching out any future possible conflicts'' but said no other action would be taken. `` Because the violation, unintended as it appears, gives an appearance of impropriety to the actions, we express our concern that they occurred,'' said <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON>, who oversees the <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> district where <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> presides. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> could have faced suspension or a recommendation that he be impeached, but <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> said those penalties would have been too harsh. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s rulings in the cases where he had holdings were reported by the AP on May 30. That report triggered the <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> review. The <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> is made up of the 11 active appeals judges in the <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> and four district judges from the <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION>, which covers <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. Upon being notified of the conflict, <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> publicly dismissed himself from the cases, an action that allows interested parties to reopen the cases. In a letter responding to the reprimand, <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> said he `` joined in the council's concern'' about the conflicts and `` instituted additional procedures and safeguards designed to prevent reoccurrence.'' <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> wrote he reviewed documents in both cases and `` I simply never connected up the defendant in each case with my investment. The responsibility and blame must rest solely on my shoulders.'' The AP discovered the conflicts by reviewing <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s annual financial disclosure statements and cross-referencing his stock holdings with his case files. The <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> review showed <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> has reported each year since 1985 that he has held between $ 15,000 and $ 50,000 in <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> stock. He presided over unrelated cases involving <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 and 1989. In both cases, he ruled in favor of GE. In the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, lawyers are required to file a certificate identifying all interests in the case. Judges must then review that certificate and compare it against their financial records to make sure they do not have an interest. In one of the two <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> cases, <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> said a certificate of interest was not filed by either the defendant or plaintiff. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, 64, was appointed to the bench in 1983 by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. His 1988 disclosure statement showed net investments between $ 648,030 and $ 1,740,000, generally in blue-chip stocks. His investments returned between $ 37,147 and $ 112,116 in 1988, including between $ 1,001 and $ 2,500 in GE dividends.
