<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Cleanup,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Outlines Plan to Clean up Atomic Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report on the government's nuclear weapons program describes a pattern of shoddy waste management and hazardous conditions with contamination of ground water or soil at many plants. The findings were included in a detailed assessment Tuesday on what it will take to clean up the nuclear weapons plants after decades of environmental neglect by plant operators. Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the first phase of the cleanup effort will cost $ 19.5 billion over the next five years with the overall cleanup likely to take at least 30 years. Overall cost estimates range from $ 90 billion to as much as $ 150 billion. The department's report listed numerous cases where shoddy handling of hazardous waste has contaminated ground water, posing various degrees of risk to surrounding communities. For example, according to the report: _ At the <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservation </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, `` surface and ground water contamination'' was blamed on abandoned waste storage tanks Some public surface water was found to be contaminated and further `` potential health risks exist.'' _ Soil and ground water was found contaminated at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> uranium processing plant near <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, where wastes are buried in unlined pits and lagoons Some of the contaminated wastewater has been discharged into streams. _ Uranium dust has contaminated water at the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> where spent nuclear fuel is recycled The report also warned of an `` immediate risk to employees through exposure to contaminated drinking water'' and said radiation exposure `` is a potential health risk'' to nearby property. _ Ground water also was cited at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in eastern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, where particular concern was noted because of the facility's proximity to the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> _ Among other priorities was reducing ground water contamination at the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and digging up barrels of liquid chemical waste at the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Test Site north of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> The report said ground water contaminants must be reduced at other federal nuclear facilities including the <LOCATION> Welden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> nuclear site in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>; the <LOCATION> Fernald </LOCATION> uranium processing plant in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; the Rocky Flats plutonium processing plant in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>; and the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alamos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. At <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alamos </LOCATION>, `` untreated liquid ... were sometimes discharged -LRB- into -RRB- canyons'' and radioactive wastes stored in various pits, trenches and shafts. As yet, the health risk of those actions `` can not be quantified,'' the report said. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> outlined the department's proposed cleanup effort in a speech Tuesday to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. He acknowledged `` the cost will be high'' and said even an optimistic timetable `` passes much of the burden to the next generation.'' The plan, which must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, calls for spending $ 2.4 billion next fiscal year. After that the annual bill is expected to steadily increase, peaking at more than $ 4 billion in both fiscal 1994 and 1995. The money would be used to clean up pollution where federal and state safety laws are violated, repair faulty equipment and develop new procedures and technology for future waste disposal, the department said. Most of the $ 19.5 billion will be used at 17 nuclear weapons plants in a dozen states as well as other nuclear facilities, most of which are inactive but continue to have hazardous waste problems. Among the sites considered most contaminated and getting the largest share of the cleanup money are: the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear complex in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, $ 4 billion; the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> facility near <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, $ 3.4 billion; the Oak Ridge Reservation complex in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, more than $ 2.7 billion; and the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, nearly $ 2.2 billion. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> officials <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON> criticized the plan, saying it `` provides for tradeoffs among compliance-related activities'' rather than a commitment to doing everything necessary to clean up the plants.
