<HEAD>House Subcommittee Chairman Says Agriculture Department Overreacted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Democratic chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> agriculture subcommittee describes the government's cancellation of some farm export projects as an overreaction, saying the program has been handled like a covert operation. `` It's almost operated like a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> operation,'' Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, D-Kan., said about the Export Enhancement Program `` I do n't want a stealth EEP.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, citing congressional leaks of sensitive information, said Tuesday that all projects approved but not announced under the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> have been canceled. `` A list of proposals that had been approved but not announced was made public by members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> yesterday -LRB- Monday -RRB- in a hearing. This information is market sensitive and was not authorized for release,'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON>, undersecretary for the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programs </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement. The export subsidy program has operated since 1985 to make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities competitive in targeted markets where foreign competitors _ especially the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> _ intrude with subsidized sales of their own. About 65 countries, including the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, have been designated for subsidized sales. Under the program, private exporters can sell <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities at lower prices to meet foreign competition and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> agriculture subcommittee Monday that the program has succeeded in boosting farm exports. In response to questions by subcommittee members, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> gave the panel a list of export subsidy proposals, some of which had not been announced. The list, which was classified, could enable foreign competitors to seek out the intended buyers of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods overseas and offer better deals, an official said. `` If information is released prior to the announcement of a decision, then the effectiveness of the program dissipates and the ultimate cost is borne by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmers by making it more difficult to compete in markets abroad,'' <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, chairman of the subcommittee, said in an interview that `` the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> voluntarily handed over the document to us. It became a public document.'' `` He is overreacting,'' <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON>. `` He's also inexperienced. But he is an honest, decent guy.'' <PERSON> Glickman </PERSON>, who said he planned to meet Friday with <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON>, sent a letter acknowledging that the incident was `` unfortunate'' and `` should n't have happended.'' Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, said the incident began when he asked <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON> if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was interested in buying soybean oil from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON> said he did n't know and asked the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, which led to the distribution of the sheets that included rejected projects. `` Obviously he -LRB- <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON> -RRB- does n't want this list out,'' <PERSON> Nagle </PERSON> said. `` They do n't want to admit they have n't been taking advantage of sales opportunities and have been rejecting programs.'' <PERSON> Nagle </PERSON> said the papers showed rejections to the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> for 200,000 tons of wheat, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> for 700,000 tons of wheat, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> for 500,000 tons of wheat and to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for 16,000 tons of rice. But Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, R-Mo., an agriculture committee member who was not at Monday's hearing, blamed <PERSON> Nagle </PERSON> and said the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had no choice but to cancel the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> projects `` It is hard to quarrel with what they have done because it could have adverse effects on the market,'' he said. `` It is incumbent on the members to be a little more sensitive to tossing this information around.''
