<HEAD>After the Speeches, Underbrush Still Remains</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: To CORRECT that ASEAN has six members, SUB 25th graf, `And
the ... of co-existence.' Picks up 26th, `Outside nations ...' ^By MORT
ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign ministers hoping to clear a path to peace in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> went home after a ringing round of speeches, leaving deputies to hack through almost impenetrable underbrush. Even if four disparate <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> factions reach an accord, allowing internationally supervised steps toward reconstruction, good intention must stand the test of political reality. `` A lot of delegates express optimism, but I do n't think very many of them are optimistic,'' a Japanese official said before a month of committee work began Tuesday. The crucial obstacle is what to do about the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, no mere negotiating point to any Cambodian who left his family on the killing fields. Front-page cartoons in the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monde </ORGANIZATION> keep fresh the memory of <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>'s regime of the 1970s, in which at least 300,000 people were executed or starved in class purges. Tuesday's drawing showed one Cambodian telling others: `` I propose we forget our little differences.'' They sat at a table engulfed by a vast sea of skulls. <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Khieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Samphan </PERSON> sat impassively in the hall, taking his turn at the rostrum to denounce subsequent Vietnamese crimes in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> as equal to <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s. Speaker after speaker rejected any <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> role in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s long-term future, but aides acknowledged privately it was not likely the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> would go away. Even <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> endorsed <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> participation in a transitory coalition, regarding that as a necessary evil to remove <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> from the scene. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s role was another imponderable. Vietnamese authorities pledged to evacuate their last troops by Sept. 27, whatever the 19-nation <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> conference decided in month-long deliberations. `` Will the Vietnamese really get out, even if they remove their troops?'' reflected <PERSON> Lek </PERSON> <PERSON> Hor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> historian who helps edit the London-based Index on Censorship. `` I do n't believe it. We have jungles, sanctuaries.'' Other expert observers disagreed with <ORGANIZATION> Lek </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s lingering presence would be noted, endangering its basic purpose of improving its international image and attracting more aid. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Co </PERSON> <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> assured goodwill, mugging for reporters in a surreal counterpoint to the grim business at hand. He said his Chinese colleague was cordial, modifying <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s harsh tone toward <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> `` We shook hands,'' he said. `` Did we look at each other and go like this?'' He closed his eyes and stuck out his tongue. `` No, no.'' Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> occupied a pivotal role at the conference, as he has since his neutralist government crumbled two decades ago after the Vietnam War spilled across his borders. Flitting between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, he has rallied support for his embattled nation, held together by a rich ancient culture that has absorbed and then shrugged off foreign intrusion throughout history. Still, his popularity is not boundless. Many Cambodians remember his reign as tainted by profligate relatives of the colorful prince who, they say, played the saxophone while <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> burned. Some Cambodian experts see a likely compromise, if any is forged, will be a symbolic role for <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> under a government sympathetic to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> with the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> making war at the edges. As the conference shifted into grinding low gear, Western and Cambodian analysts agreed that one of the few concrete results was a backhand byproduct: In the past few months, <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> prime minister who was widely spurned as a puppet of <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, has been tacitly legitimatized as leader of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. He is in a position to hold power while waiting for support to wane for <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> and for <LOCATION> Son </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sann </LOCATION>, a pro-Western resistance leader in tenuous control of his forces. Despite the obstacles, most of the world is anxious to press for some sort of settlement. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> see it as a costly, dangerous flashpoint in a world with enough problems. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> wants to rebuild <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> but can not without a stable internal framework. And the six members of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> have been trying for a decade to get <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to go home and allow the Cambodians to find some level of co-existence. Outside nations hope a thaw in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> will melt away settlements of 300,000 refugees along the Thai border, not only a human tragedy but also a political tinderbox. Beyond the internal issues at the heart of the Cambodian problem, nations differ over the international structure to supervise the peace. Some insist that Cambodians should resolve their own problems at their own pace. Canadian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, among others, argued that the international effort has to be part of a comprehensive settlement, including agreement among the Cambodians. `` There has to be a peace to keep,'' he said. He added what many Cambodian experts considered to be a understatement: This will be the most complex peacekeeping operation since the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
