<HEAD>Hungary Sees Risks, Unrest in Push for Free-Market Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> says it is risking social unrest, rising unemployment and a possible backlash from the conservative right in its push toward a free-market economy. The government, in a memo Tuesday to a 24-nation conference on aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, said it is determined to change its state-controlled economy `` even if it initially causes social conflicts.'' <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> warned, however, of widespread opposition if its campaign resulted in a sharp and sustained fall in the standard of living of the country's 11 million people. It urged more than 130 officials attending the meeting at the headquarters of the European Community for financial aid. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s foreign debt is about $ 18 billion, the highest per capita in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> The memo said the government was seeking as much as $ 3 billion in new Western assistance from 1990 to 1992. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other key world leaders called for the meeting to draw up a Western aid package that would encourage democratic change and economic reforms in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. They also urged emergency food shipments for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. At the one-day talks, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pledged an additional $ 50 million in food aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, beginning Oct. 1, to help ease the shortages caused by that government's moves toward a free-market economy. `` We're trying to help carry them through this period,'' <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamman </PERSON>, deputy assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State for European Affairs, told reporters. <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> also promised food aid. The European Community, the 12-nation trading bloc, earlier agreed to send $ 120 million worth of meat, grains and other products to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Shortly after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s trip last month to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> announced it would send $ 9 million in food from surplus stocks. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on Tuesday ended price controls and meat rationing as part of the current economic reforms. There was concern the abrupt lifting of price controls might send the country into turmoil. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, a founding member of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>, has been in the forefront of economic reforms in the Communist bloc since the 1960s. The push has recently accelerated. The government's memo said the key goal was for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to become `` an equal member of the community of the developed democratic nations.'' To do so, it wants to create a market economy `` based on the equality of the different forms of ownership'' and integrated in the world economy with a currency that can be traded internationally. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s currency, like those of other <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc nations, does not circulate in world currency markets. `` Parallel with our efforts aimed at creation of the market economy, economic policy must also be radically changed,'' the memo said. The reforms, it said, require tight monetary and budget policies that can lead to poor economic growth and higher inflation. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> said its balance of payments _ a summing up of international trade payments _ was expected to `` deteriorate'' in 1989. Moreover, it forecast a higher jobless rate due partly to shutdowns of money-losing companies. `` Although unemployment is not yet considerable, its rate is gradually growing,'' it said, cautioning it could lead `` to serious problems in certain regions.'' It invited the nations attending the aid conference to meet in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> next month to take a closer look at <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s situation. Nations at the meeting were the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> members of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. Others present were the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>.
