<FIRST>r w PM-DrugStrategy     08-02 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Strategy,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett's Drug Strategy Short on Specifics, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug czar <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s national drug strategy calls for increased law enforcement but is short on specifics, according to administration officials who have seen it. While the program focuses on cocaine, particularly crack, it has `` virtually nothing'' on heroin, dangerous prescription drugs that are diverted to illegal use or hallucinogens, said one source. `` There's only one sentence on all of that,'' the source said Tuesday. The strategy report to the Cabinet, required by the 1988 anti-drug law that created the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategy </ORGANIZATION>, strongly reflects public comments made by <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> since he took office five months ago. The final report is due Sept. 5. `` It reads like one of his speeches,'' said one source. Another source said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> wrote the strategy himself after gathering information from government agencies and drug experts. All the sources spoke on condition of anonymity. The strategy calls for an all-out effort to eradicate domestic marijuana crops and to wipe out money-laundering operations, but it says nothing about domestic methamphetamine labs, one source said. However, the source said there were few specific goals _ such as the number of drug-treatment beds the nation should have by 1991 _ in the draft submitted Monday. The only goals included were that drug-related admissions to emergency rooms and the drug use found by the National Household Survey on Drug Abuse should be reduced by 10 percent in two years and by 50 percent in 10 years, according to one of the sources. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> warned last week that the strategy would contain `` some carrots and some sticks. `` We will expect states to do certain things if they want federal funds,'' he said then. `` We will expect educational institutions to finally do certain things if they want education funds.'' In the most recent draft, those threats take the form of a possible loss of highway funds for states that fail to revoke driver's licenses from those convicted of drug offenses, and a possible loss of federal education funds from schools that fail to have Education Department approved drug-prevention programs and policies, a source said. Threats in an earlier draft to revoke criminal justice funds were eliminated, the source said. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Judiciary Chairman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who spent eight years pushing for creation of the job, said during <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s confirmation hearing that he expected the strategy to include detailed goals One source said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> planned to meet with senators in the next few days, possibly to reduce expectations. The strategy seen by the sources did not include matters such as international operations and interdiction efforts, which are included in a separate, classified document being reviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The non-classified strategy, under review by the <ORGANIZATION> Domestic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, reflects <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s oft-stated contention that the drug war must be aggressively fought on all fronts _ enforcement, prevention and treatment. `` No single strategy, pursued alone or to the detriment of other possible and valuable initiatives, can work to contain or reduce drug use,'' the strategy says. But what that means in terms of money was not immediately clear. The draft strategy circulated Monday included no budget figures. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in June that he expected to seek more money for drug treatment and probably more for prevention. He said last week that the escalating cost of the drug war may eventually lead to the need for a tax increase. The strategy stresses a need to rid inner cities of illegal drugs. `` A paramount target of law-enforcement activity, especially at the local level, must be the disruption of those street markets for drugs in which retail demand and supply finally meet in a combustible mix.'' It includes proposed anti-drug legislation for states that closely resembles outlines <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> provided two weeks ago to a gathering of state legislators, according to one source. The policies <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> urged on the state legislators ranged from hiring more police, judges and prosecutors and building more prisons, to imposing civil fines of up to $ 10,000 for those convicted of possessing small amounts of drugs.
</TEXT>
