<HEAD>Congress Warned About High-Definition TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is being warned not to bet the farm on high-definition television. Despite what its proponents say about the dazzling new technology, HDTV wo n't play a significant role in a growing electronics market in the next 20 years, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report Tuesday. The report, which may take some of the wind out of the <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> sails in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said: _ HDTV advocates have made `` very optimistic'' forecasts about the market size and easy availability of the next generation of video _ Even under the rosiest of scenarios, HDTV sales will be small relative to other electronic equipment markets _ It is questionable how quickly _ or if _ finicky consumers will accept <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION>, even though it promises 35mm motion picture quality images, particularly if there are intermediate and cheaper types of advanced TV receivers available _ The total world market for electronic equipment grew by $ 54 billion in 1988 to reach $ 461 billion, and the world market for <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> receivers and VCRs is forecast to be less than $ 30 billion by 2010 _ HDTV will spur only marginal production of sophisticated memory chips, which are widely used in other applications even now `` It seems counterintuitive to suggest that such a small market that may exist in the future is a more important driver of economies of scale, technology and competitive success than is the growth in the present market.'' the report said. `` It would be a case of the tail wagging the dog.'' But the report, written by <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webre </PERSON>, said government support of HDTV might be justified because of increased employment, national prestige or scientific advancement. The report was introduced at a hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which is considering a possible government role in fostering the growth of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> high-definition TV industry. Proponents say a quick government decision is vital in overcoming the Japanese and European lead in the HDTV arena. Committee Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> needs to pre-empt foreign competition so HDTV wo n't become another U.S.-invented product that is sold back to Americans from overseas. Despite the report, the HDTV juggernaut rolled along Tuesday on several congressional fronts. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> gave voice vote approval to a $ 305 million authorization bill for the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> new </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in fiscal 1990 that includes $ 37.5 million for federal <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> research and seed money for private HDTV consortia. The bill was amended to allow foreign companies to participate in the <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> research consortia and a provision for $ 50 million in loan guarantees was dropped. Also, a House Science, Space and Technology subcommittee approved an amendment to the technology authorization bill to provide $ 100 million annually for three years for creating public-private consortia for HDTV development. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> McCloskey </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, applauded the <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> report, saying it would help shift the discussion of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitiveness away from just <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> to `` the need to find solutions for major economy-wide problems of primary importance to national competitiveness.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the report was narrowly focused on <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION>'s potential use in home TV receivers. HDTV, he said, would be a far more important technology driver in engineering work stations and high-end personal computers and for development of better manufacturing techniques. The association has proposed a package of federal support for <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> that would include $ 1 billion in loans and loan guarantees for manufacturing facilities and $ 300 million over three years to expand the $ 30 million already allocated to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Projects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> for HDTV research. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Benitez </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy assistant secretary for science and electronics, reiterated the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's proposal to spur HDTV through lower capital gains taxes, a permanent <ORGANIZATION> R </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; D tax credit and possible antitrust exemption for joint industry ventures
