<HEAD>Bush's Clean-Air Bill Best Hope for Breaking Stalemate: Industry
Coalition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s clean-air bill could cost businesses and consumers money but it remains the best hope for breaking a decade-long stalemate, a coalition of the nation's major industries says. `` There is no gift here _ for consumers, workers or businesses,'' coalition administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said Tuesday in answer to environmental groups that contend the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal is a sellout to industry. Representatives of the petroleum, chemical and auto industries, all members of the <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Working </ORGANIZATION> group, offered a mixed review of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan at a news conference. <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said the legislation would dramatically control acid rain, tighten auto and truck emission standards, force some cities to adopt an alternative motor fuels program and cut ozone emissions and airborne toxic chemicals. But some of the measures, <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said, would go too far in slashing industry profits, hurting competitiveness and costing consumers money when pollution control costs are passed on. The industry representatives criticized two cornerstones of the legislation: use of alternative fuels for some motor vehicles sold in severely polluted cities, and a cap on sulfur-dioxide emissions that would prevent utilities from expanding when demand for electricity is rising. Sulfur dioxide is the main component of acid rain, which has destroyed trees and lakes in the northeastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Despite the criticism, <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan should be `` the basic legislative text from which a final bill will be drawn.'' It `` addresses serious issues such as ozone ... and toxic air pollution,'' he said. `` And the president has made a serious effort to consider costs and build flexibility into the bill.'' The bill, <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said, is a much better alternative than competing bills backed by environmental groups. Those bills would give industry far fewer choices in devising ways to improve air quality. <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> and other industry representatives say <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s original annual cost estimate of $ 14 billion to $ 19 billion would be far too low and would cause layoffs because of expense to industry. He would n't predict how many jobs would be lost or give industry's estimate of the cost. The provisions that upset the industry group the most have been cited again and again by administration officials as cornerstones of the legislation. The alternative fuels plan would require that in areas with severe ozone pollution, at least nine cities, vehicles with clean-burning fuel must be sold according to the following schedule: 500,000 in the 1995 model year; 750,000 in the 1996 model year; and 1 million in each of the model years from 1997 through 2004. `` We're suggesting the mandate should not be there'' because automakers are n't certain the technology is perfected or that consumers would accept the cars, <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, a lobbyist with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said his oil industry trade group believes the proposal to be `` a big mistake,'' saying `` there should be a level playing field in which all fuels should be able to compete.'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has most-often mentioned methanol as the likely alternative fuel, a product made from natural gas that likely would come from <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He contended the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> appeared to be biased against giving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> petroleum companies the chance to produce a cleaner-burning gasoline. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan also would reduce sulfur-dioxide emissions by 10 million tons by the end of 2000, based on 1980 levels. But the measure also would `` cap'' emissions at the reduced level, thus restricting growth of utilities unless they could further reduce their emissions from existing plants. The cap on such emissions, <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said, `` is unnecessarily restrictive, limits economic growth, and makes it difficult to build new factories and power plants.''
