<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drug Testing,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate and House Have Different Approaches to Random Drug Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Both the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> have bills to impose random drug testing on transportation workers, but the measures still have most of the differences that kept them from being combined into a single law a year ago. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved a bill Tuesday that would require random and other testing of workers with safety-related jobs on planes, trains, trucks and buses, while the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Monday passed a measure affecting only railroads. Similar bills passed both chambers last session, but lawmakers failed to come up with a single law. Sen. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., a sponsor of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version, said the committee's bill was the `` best way to prevent the lethal consequences of transportation substance abuse. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has jurisdiction over all modes of transportation, while the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that produced the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill only covers railroads. Unlike the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approach, <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill would give workers the incentive to seek rehabilitation before they are caught while the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> measure would encourage workers to wait until they are caught. Both bills authorize employers to conduct drug tests before hiring, on reasonable suspicion and after certain accidents, as well as at random. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> legislation would require airline crews, railroad crews and truck and bus drivers to submit to a variety of drug and alcohol tests. Rehabilitation programs would be set up by employers for workers who voluntarily seek help, but the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill offers no guarantee of rehabilitation or continued employment for a worker caught by the tests or involved in a drug-related accident. The House bill would require testing only for railroad workers, and would mandate employers to set up rehabilitation programs for workers caught under the influence of drugs or alcohol on the job. The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> already has ordered a wide range of drug tests, including random tests for railroad crews, but they have been challenged in the courts. The tests do n't cover alcohol abuse. If the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure is passed, a conference committee would have to work out the differences in the two bills before a law could be sent to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his signature.
</TEXT>
