<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Stocks Up Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell against the Japanese yen for the third consecutive day today, while the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s main index rose marginally. The dollar closed at 136.20 yen, down 0.45 yen from Tuesday's 136.65-yen finish It opened at 135.58 yen and moved between 135.50 yen and 136.30 yen. The dollar now has declined 3.25 yen in three days. <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> dealer <PERSON> Yoshitsugu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanada </PERSON> said market players in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> were mainly making position adjustments today in the absence of market-affecting news. `` The market's basic sentiment has been toward a weaker dollar because of the falling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates, but Japanese investors were trying to buy whenever the dollar fell,'' he said. `` When investors found out that the dollar would n't fall further today, some of them started to buy it back, which helped the currency end higher than its opening rate,'' <PERSON> Hanada </PERSON> added. But because of a slowdown in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy, the dollar seemed unlikely to rise again, he said, adding: `` Friday's -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- jobless rate report will be another indicator.'' On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained in early trading but ended up only 0.88 points, or 0.003 percent, higher, closing at 34,899.334. It surpassed the 35,000 mark for the first time at the end of morning trading. But <PERSON> Kazuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nomura </PERSON>, a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said investors started selling to take profits as soon as the afternoon session began, and the index fell back. `` Market players avoided buying to prevent prices from rising too fast,'' he added. Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 800 million shares, up from Tuesday's 700 million. Among gainers were steel, electric power company and chemical issues.
