<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0818,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Mandy Patinkin in Concert' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS four grafs with other reviews; no PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> never does anything halfway. If you need proof, the evidence is on display at <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> Theater where he has opened in a dazzling one-man show called `` <PERSON> Mandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> in Concert: Dress Casual. There's nothing casual about <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> except maybe his clothes _ red T-shirt, gray sneakers and baggy, black pants. The intense performer, best known to theater audiences as <PERSON> Che </PERSON> <PERSON> Guevara </PERSON> in `` Evita'' and <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Seurat </PERSON> in `` Sunday in the Park with <PERSON> George </PERSON>,'' is one of those unique artists who can make an audience cheer. At the <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, he scorches the stage with a virtuosic performance that is as exhausting as it is exhilarating. What makes his show so special? <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> does n't just stand there and sing. He takes over each song as if it were a story, and he were telling it directly to you. There's a simplicity in his communication that is disarming, particularly when he is sweetly singing an old standard like `` Pennies from Heaven'' or <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>'s `` <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>.'' But he's not afraid of a little histrionics either, like his almost over-the-edge, down-on-one-knee version of <PERSON> Jolson </PERSON>'s `` My Mammy'' or `` On the <PERSON> Atchison </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>'' performed at full throttle. Although there is a heavy dose of theater songs, <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON>'s wide-ranging repertoire is astonishing His precise diction and exact phrasing make him a natural singer of <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON> songs. And he does n't disappoint, coming up with two numbers from `` Into the <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>,'' as well as a heartfelt rendition of the title song from `` Anyone Can Whistle'' and a hilarious version of `` Buddy's Blues'' from `` Follies. His grouping of songs is equally effective. Not many performers would open with `` <PERSON> Doodle </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo </PERSON>,'' move right into `` When the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bob-Bob-Bobbin </ORGANIZATION>' Along'' and then finish with `` Tchaikowsky,'' a tongue-twisting recitation of Russian composers from `` Lady in the Dark'' that <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> made famous. Somehow it works. The show also includes a medley of seven songs from `` Pal <PERSON> Joey </PERSON>'' that seems like a mini-version of the <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> musical, as well as an impassioned `` Soliloquy'' from `` Carousel.'' Both shows sound like ideal vehicles for the singer if he decides to return to the musical theater. In the `` Carousel'' number, <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> bounds around the stage and even does a few chin ups on a backstage bar while he sings. There are several comic highlights including a wacky version of the <PERSON> Ella </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> standard `` A-Tisket A-Tasket'' that sounds like it came out of the television police show `` Dragnet'' and a rare <PERSON> Kander </PERSON> and Ebb song, `` Coffee in a Cardboard Cup,'' done with all the sound effects of a typical greasy spoon restaurant. There should be a special mention for piano wizard <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON>'s partner during the evening. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> is not just an accompanist. He anticipates the singer's needs and provides the support that <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> needs as he does his dangerous high-wire balancing act. One final note. No microphones are used during the show. It's a relevation and a relief to hear <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON>'s unique voice without the tinny interference of modern technology. `` <PERSON> Mandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> in Concert'' truly is `` live'' theater at its best. In other reviews: <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> called <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON>'s show the `` most exciting ... in ages.'' `` The range of what he does and the imagination and power with which he does it are enough for you to imagine he could singlehandedly revive the American musical theater,'' <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Clive </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> called <PERSON> Patinkin </PERSON> the greatest entertainer on Broadway today and described the concert as `` dazzling fun.'' While he can bring tears to your eyes, <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> said, `` most of the time you are just happy to be in the same room with him.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> described the show as `` audacious, often brilliant, but also a touch wacky.'' `` Instead of a bland, all-American confidence, he radiates a fierce, neurotic intelligence,'' <PERSON> Holden </PERSON> said.
