<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s main opposition group claimed today that President-elect <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> secretly sent his brother to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> to `` closely supervise'' the killing of Lt. Col. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> has been quoted by the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> as denying in a meeting with visiting Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> had any `` relation to the tragedy.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION>, or People's Holy Warriors, said in a statement that <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> exerts direct control of the radical Shiite Moslem groups believed to be holding Western hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The group said <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> sent his brother, <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON>, `` secretly to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> a few days ago in order to closely supervise the terrorist acts of the regime's proxies in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, including the execution of the American hostage, Col. <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>.'' The opposition's statement said <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> heads the Iranian foreign ministry's `` <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'' set up to coordinate the kidnappers' activities. The statement was sent by telex to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, where the group has its headquarters. A Shiite Moslem group calling itself the Organization of the Oppressed on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> claimed it hanged the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> on Monday in retaliation for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s abduction Friday of a Shiite Moslem cleric in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The group released a videotape that purported to show <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON> hanging from a makeshift gallows. There was no indication when it was filmed. Prior reports indicated that <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>, who led a 75-member <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> truce monitoring force in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, may have been killed by his captors last year. Moslem fundamentalist groups loyal to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> are believed to be holding most of the 16 western hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. They are thought to be linked to <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, an Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem group seeking to dominate the 1.2-million strong Shiite community in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, the country's largest sect The <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> statement alleged that several <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> officials sent from <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> were told to `` extend their stay in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> for another two weeks on the orders of President-elect <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> in order to carry out the execution of <LOCATION> Col </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> denies it has anything to do with hostage-taking, while <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has sought to distance itself from the reported hanging and threats to execute other western hostages held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who was voted president by a landslide majority in Friday's election, is believed anxious to erase <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s image as a sponsor of international terrorism. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> said Monday before <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' death was announced the threat against him `` has nothing to do with us However, we condemn any kind of kidnapping or death threat.'' But on Sunday, Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON> warned that Islamic groups around the world would retaliate for the aduction of the cleric, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul-Karim </PERSON> <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> statement said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> used its embassy in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, as a headquarters for <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> activities in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> is a close ally of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The statement said Iranian Revolutionary Guards based in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> were responsible for `` military training of terrorists, operational planning, interrogations and other intelligence operations by the regime's proxy terrorist groups in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' About 4,000 Revolutionary Guards are currently believed based in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa valley in eastern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s 1979 fundamentalist revolution in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> helped spawn several Shiite terrorist groups in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Revolutionary Guards, sent into <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> during the 1982 Israeli invasion, helped organize <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>.
