<FIRST>r a PM-LiquidAir     08-02 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Liquid Air,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Use Liquid To Help Premature Baby Breathe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new respiration technique that uses a liquid to deliver oxygen to a patient's lungs could save premature babies and affect the abortion debate, researchers said. In May, a baby born after 28 weeks of gestation and within an hour or two of death from lung damage was kept alive 19 hours when doctors filled the infant's lungs with perfluorocarbon, an oxygen-carrying liquid, said Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> physiologist and pediatrician who led the team. He and his colleagues are on call to attempt the procedure again when a candidate becomes available, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. The baby girl, born two months premature and weighing just under 2 pounds, was the first human to undergo the procedure, according to Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, a pediatric surgeon at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisico </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> was not involved in the research in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. If the procedure could be shown to shorten the time a fetus is dependent on its mother, the technology could affect the abortion debate in the country, said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. In its controversial decision July 3, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled states may require doctors to determine through various tests whether a fetus at least 20 weeks old is capable of surviving outside the womb. Many states prohibit aborting a viable fetus, but the court's 1973 decision making abortion legal drew the viability line at 24 weeks. Generally, premature babies delivered 23 to 24 weeks from conception stand a chance of surviving without major disabilities, researchers said. If the liquid ventilation technique is successful, it could push that time period back to 20 weeks, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. However, it is still unclear whether organs other than the lungs would be developed enough to sustain life at 20 weeks, he said. Aside from premature babies, the procedure holds promise for any kind of situation where a patient's lungs can not be ventilated with gas, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, a chemist at <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> who first discovered the technique, said perfluorocarbon acts as a liquid Teflon to gently separate parts of the lung that stick together after a collapse in a premature baby. In adults, the body produces surfactant, which prevents the inside of a lung from sticking to itself. But in premature babies who have not yet developed surfactant or in babies who lack the material, normal ventilation runs the risk of bursting a lung or damaging it, he said. The infant, whose lungs had been damaged by two weeks of conventional ventilation and had partially collapsed, was close to death May 10 when the experiment was performed, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. About a half ounce of perfluorocarbon, a liquid that carries oxygen, was poured into the baby's lungs through her trachea, he said. About another quarter ounce of the liquid was allowed to flow in and out of her lungs, bringing fresh oxygen, for 15 minutes, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
