<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-CFCs     08-02 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-CFCs,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan to Ban Chloroflourocarbons from Its Vehicles by 1993</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said today that it plans to make its car air conditioners and manufacturing processes free of chlorofluorocarbons, the gases blamed for destroying the Earth's protective ozone layer, by 1993 <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> became the first of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s major automakers _ which are heavy users of chlorofluorocarbons -LRB- CFCs -RRB- _ to announce a total ban on the gases. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Shingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> said the company, helped by air-conditioning makers such as <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Calsonic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, is developing new car air conditioners that use a new substance to replace CFC-12. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> has used some 1,150 tons of CFC-12 a year as coolants, he said, and a total of 1,500 tons of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s a year for all purposes, accounting for 1.2 percent of total <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the spokesman said, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> already has stopped using CFC-11 in the making of automobile bumpers and will do so in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> by the end of next year. By the end of 1993, he said, the company plans to replace CFC-113 with water for cleansing automobile parts. He said this will require the company to develop additional processes to dry parts after washing. CFC-113 dries instantly. `` But it depends on the feasibility of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> alternatives,'' <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> said. `` If we can get stable supplies of new substitutes, our goal is certainly attainable.'' <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashimoto </PERSON> said, `` Although we've been considering environmental issues, we have n't reached the stage to announce anything concrete.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s move would `` prompt <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> to consider the issue more seriously and swiftly.'' An official of the freon countermeasure division in the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> called such moves by the private sector `` very welcome.'' Companies that have to use additional machines and substances in the process of cutting <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use can obtain tax reductions, said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity. In <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 38 countries agreed in 1987 to reduce production and use of the gases. Under the Montreal Protocol, participating countries must freeze their CFC consumption this year at the 1986 level and reduce consumption to 5 percent of the 1986 level by the end of 1999.
