<HEAD>In Acceptance Speech, Kiszczak Tries to Enlist Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a text of the acceptance speech by Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> after his election as prime minister. The speech was monitored on Polish television and translated by The Associated Press: I would like to thank you for entrusting me with the honorable mission of forming the government of the Polish People's Republic. The confidence which I enjoyed in the support for my candidacy I treat as ... an obligation. I will do whatever is in my might not to fail this confidence. With attention, I approach those deputies who voted against my candidacy. Their opinion inclines me toward an active search for ways and means of gaining a broader parliamentary and social understanding and approval for the activities of the government which I intend to form. I face, and naturally the high chamber -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- faces, the question of the shape of the new Cabinet, its program and philosophy of functioning. I state with regret that so far, the concept of creating a `` grand coalition'' government has not been accepted. I think that a government of such a construction would be most appropriate today for overseeing the course of issues of the country. That is why in forming the Cabinet on as broad a basis as possible, I will not give up efforts to attract to it representatives of opposition circles with a hope that in the future a grand coalition government will be possible. I opt for a government of the `` roundtable.'' I do not refer here only to the symbol of agreement and national reconciliation, but most of all to its substantial content and ways of shaping the process of dialogue. A vision of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s development has been outlined in the roundtable accords -LRB- reached between Solidarity and Communist authorities in April -RRB-, corresponding with social aspirations and expectations The new government should work with all its effort toward realizing this vision, especially as far as the shape of the new economic order and political reforms are concerned. As co-chairman of the roundtable, I feel morally and politically obliged to guarantee the concluded agreement of Poles. I will thus do everything so that the directions of the government's work might correspond with the supreme reasons of state and the nation. The seriousness of the internal situation, especially in the economic sphere, imposes the necessity of quick action. I would thus like to ask the high chamber if I could present the program of action and makeup of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> within the next two weeks. Thank you.
