pickup. ^By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament today elected the interior minister, Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, as prime minister in a victory for the long-ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, whose power has been eroding. In his acceptance speech, <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> pledged to try to bring members of the Solidarity-led opposition into his new Cabinet. He asked Solidarity to reverse its position that it will not accept joint responsibility for governing <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Although it has rejected joining a coalition government, Solidarity has not ruled out allowing members to serve in the Cabinet. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, the nation's top law enforcement officer, was elected by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s lower house, the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION>, by a vote of 237 to 173 with 10 abstentions. The required majority was 211 votes. As interior minister, <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> implemented the 1981 martial law crackdown that suppressed the free trade union movement, but he also helped initiate this year's campaign that made Solidarity legal again. The vote for prime minister had been postponed Tuesday when some deputies in the communist-allied <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> sought a government dominated by lawmakers of the Solidarity independent trade union. But after urgent arm-twisting Tuesday night by their party leadership and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> officials, most <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members ended up voting for <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, the handpicked candidate of Communist President <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>. `` Looks like they were frightened,'' said Solidarity member <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON> following the vote. Solidarity's floor leader in the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION>, <PERS