<TEXT>
 July 28 The <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> -RRB- Sun on the crash of Flight 232: Capt. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>, the pilot of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet that crashed July 19 in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, says there is no hero in the horrifying accident. The 185 people who survived the crash of the DC-10 may disagree. In his first news conference since the crash, <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> said he heard a loud noise and began shutting down -LRB- the plane's tail engine -RRB- ... A short time later, he said, the crew realized the plane had lost all its hydraulic fluid. When he asked another crew member what the flying procedure for those circumstances would be, he learned there was none. So the crew had to develop one as it tried to guide the stricken aircraft to the <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> airport. The plane crashed landed just short of the runway, flipped and broke apart. <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> reminded reporters and others of the 111 people who died in the crash and the importance of determining the cause and trying to avoid such disasters in the future. He modestly said the four crew members just `` did their job.'' He should also remember that in doing so, they saved 185 lives.
