 July 27 The <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> -RRB- News on the crash of Flight 232: <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> captain, is a reminder that ordinarily able people are capable of extraordinary competency and courage. This was an indomitable man at the press conference at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, a man you'd guess has n't yet counted his cuts and bruises, and used a wheelchair only to humor his doctor. The mid-air crisis that crippled Captain <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>' jumbo jetliner held him and his crew in tortured suspension for nearly an hour. The challenge to stay aloft, to reach an airport, to attempt a safe landing, was beyond the imagining of most of us. He did it with mental toughness, methodically, calmly, with knowing trust in his own ability and intuition. And he made it all work until seconds before touch down, when lack of precise control, or perhaps a runway crosswind, dropped one wing into the ground. The aircraft cartwheeled and the fore and aft section disintegrated among trailing flames. But 185 of Captain <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>' passengers survived. Air safety authorities labeled it a heroic and miraculous piloting job. His own matter-of-fact declaration that there was no hero, only people doing their jobs, fit him becomingly. Not many people are capable, but he gives the impression that many more could be.
