<HEAD>Police Kill Suspected Guerrilla in Namibia, Capture Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police today shot and killed a black man during a raid on his house and said the Soviet-made arms they found there indicate that <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas are smuggling arms into <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. Kierie du Rand, chief inspector of the South African-ruled territory, said the suspected guerrilla, <PERSON> Petrus </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, was shot in the northern border town of <LOCATION> Rundu </LOCATION> when he brandished a pistol while trying to escape after his arrest. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Rand </PERSON> said police found Soviet-made explosives, a detonator and a hand grenade in <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>'s home in the town 180 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION>. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> contingent monitoring <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s transition to independence could not be located to accompany the police patrol on its mission, <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Rand </PERSON> said He said the incident proves <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas are crossing the border from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, where their bases are, to establish arms caches in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and that <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> troops are unable to monitor the situation. Under a multinational agreement linked to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> independence plan, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas are to remain at bases at least 100 miles inside <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> or return to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> as unarmed civilians. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> have accused the South African-led territorial police of harassing and intimidating the movement's supporters. More than 5,000 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military and police personnel have been deployed in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to supervise the campaign leading to pre-independence elections in November. <LOCATION> SWAPO </LOCATION>, which began a bush war against <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African rule in 1966, is favored to get the most votes in the election.
