<HEAD>Rulers Let PEN Club Restart in Prague</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to ADD background on the PEN organization
and background on PEN group in Soviet Union. Pickup graf 14 pvs, `Klima
said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> rulers have allowed the domestic branch of the <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> writers' club to reopen, and its board will include banned and officially-sanctioned authors, participants said today. <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Klima </PERSON>, a dissident writer, said he and about 20 colleagues gathered Tuesday in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and elected a new club governing committee. He said both he and banned playwright <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> are included in the panel. <PERSON> Klima </PERSON> himself was banned after the 1968 reforms known as the `` Prague Spring'' were crushed by a Soviet-led invasion. The Czech branch of the international writers' club became dormant around 1971 in the wake of broad purges of party members, including many writers. Police detained <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> for about three hours Tuesday but released him in time to allow him to appear at the end of the meeting, <PERSON> Klima </PERSON> and another participant said. Two members of the human rights group Charter 77, <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanturkova </PERSON> and <PERSON> Milan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simecka </PERSON>, were summoned to police for questioning to coincide with Tuesday's meeting, thus preventing their attendance, <PERSON> Klima </PERSON> said. However, the official news agency, <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION>, signaled authorities' approval of the <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> club project by briefly reporting that it was being formed again <PERSON> Klima </PERSON> said 10 writers were elected to the club's governing committee, or board of directors: six dissident or non-conformist writers and four older, officially-backed writers. The <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> report did not discuss the board's makeup. One of the official writers, <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Mucha </PERSON>, was elected chairman in what <PERSON> Klima </PERSON> described as a compromise between the official and banned writers. The efforts to restart the PEN club are the first such joint initiative in Czech literature in almost 20 years. <PERSON> Klima </PERSON> said he saw it as `` a very good sign'' that the club was permitted to resume activity. He said he hopes it can negotiate with authorities on publishing previously banned books and lifting curbs on banned writers. Over the past year, authorities have made small shifts toward liberalizing the arts. Books by <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kafka </PERSON> have appeared for only the second time in 20 years, and a number of previously banned films, plays and rock bands were allowed to be seen. Writers such as <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, however, have remained banned because of their refusal to renounce political activities, according to officials. In May, the 60-chapter international PEN association voted unanimously to admit a Russian chapter, ending a long quarrel with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Soviet participation in the 10,000-member group has been an issue ever since PEN _ an acronym for Poets, Playwrights, Editors, Essayists and Novelists _ turned down an application by the Soviet state in 1924. PEN, which champions freedom of speech for writers, had kept out the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> because of its persecution of writers and other intellectuals. <PERSON> Klima </PERSON> said the Czech club will hold its first annual meeting next year.
</TEXT>
