<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> will be sworn in as the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>'s fifth president on Thursday, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio reported Wednesday. The broadcast said <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s credentials will be presented in a ceremony to <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, the incumbent president who took over as the country's spiritual leader after <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death June 3. Although <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>'s second four-year term does n't expire until October, he had been expected to step down sooner. The state-run radio report, monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, did not say whether Thursday's ceremony meant that <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> would start his duties as president immediately. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, the 54-year-old speaker of parliament, won a landslide victory in Friday's presidential elections, capturing 94.5 percent of the vote. Constitutional reforms approved in a referendum alongside the election give him considerably enlarged powers by scrapping Prime Minister <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON>'s post. Earlier this week, <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> told <PERSON> Musavi </PERSON> to continue his duties as prime minister until a new cabinet is set up by <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> is considered a pragmatist who would like to ease tight governmental control of the economy, and resume ties with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. The presidential elections, originally due to be held Aug. 18, were moved up about three weeks to hasten the transfer of power after <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death. <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>'s decision to step down as president before the end of his term appeared aimed at allowing <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> move quickly to start reforming