 <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> wo n't appeal a $ 399 award to Mayor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendler </PERSON> who complained he was n't allowed to smoke on a flight. `` We'd basically just like to forget about it,'' <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said Tuesday. `` It would be more trouble and more expensive than it's worth to go through the appeal process.'' <PERSON> Hendler </PERSON> sued <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> after his March flight from <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, was declared non-smoking just before takeoff to accommodate two passengers. In small claims court in <LOCATION> Pasco </LOCATION> last month, <PERSON> Hendler </PERSON> was awarded the ticket price of $ 376 and $ 23 for court costs. <PERSON> Hendler </PERSON> originally sought three times the ticket price. Delta does not fear <PERSON> Hendler </PERSON>'s victory will inspire similar lawsuits, and does not plan to change its policies, <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> said. Federal law says airlines must provide `` a sufficient number of seats in the no-smoking sections of the aircraft for all persons who wish to be seated there, and expansion of no-smoking areas to meet demand.'' About 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s seats typically are for smokers, <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> said. The carrier occasionally cancels smoking sections, but <PERSON> Hendler </PERSON> was the first to sue, <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hendler </PERSON> said that if the airline reserves seats for smokers, it should honor that commitment. `` The principle is breach of contract. That is the basis of the suit,'' he said.
