<HEAD>Study Raises New Concern About Estrogen-Breast Cancer Link</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Women who try to reduce their risk of fractures and heart disease by taking estrogen supplements for many years after menopause may slightly increase their chances of breast cancer, a study concludes. Some experts said doctors may have to consider the possibility of cancer when weighing the risks and benefits of putting women on estrogen after menopause. However, they caution that the evidence of a cancer link is still weak. `` In my opinion, the data are not conclusive enough to warrant any immediate change in the way we approach hormone replacement,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett-Connor </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. The study, based on 23,244 Swedish women, found that users had a 10 percent overall increase in their risk of breast cancer after six years of taking the hormone. However, the risk varied, depending on the kind of estrogen that women used. Those who took estradiol, the most commonly used variety in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, had nearly double the usual risk of breast cancer. But the researchers found no increased risk among the relatively small numbers who used conjugated estrogens, which are most frequently prescribed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Doctors often prescribe estrogen in combination with the hormone progestin in the belief that this will minimize any increase in the risk of uterine cancer, which also is associated with estrogen use. However, the Swedish study raised the possibility that this combination may actually heighten the risk of breast cancer. Women in the study who had used the combination for more than six years had four times the usual risk of breast cancer, but the number of women studied was too small to be statistically meaningful. `` This article raises concern about the new regimens,'' noted Dr. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Sloan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Epidemiology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Combination therapy is becoming increasingly popular and recommended.'' The study, like other research, found no danger from brief use of estrogen to relieve hot flashes and other symptoms during menopause. The study was directed by Dr. <PERSON> Leif </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergkvist </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Uppsala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, and published in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine. Evidence of a link between estrogen and breast cancer is conflicting. More than 20 studies have found no sign of an association, but a few others suggest there may be a link. Estrogen is widely prescribed to older women to reduce their risk of heart disease and to stop osteoporosis, which leads to broken bones. Some doctors recommended that women take the hormone for the rest of their lives. `` This is an important public health question,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hennekens </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brigham </LOCATION> and Women's Hospital in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` The breast cancer finding, if confirmed, would certainly be something that the physician would have to weigh in deciding whether to give estrogen.''
</TEXT>
