pvs, `Hurricane warnings ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical Storm Dean developed into a hurricane with winds of 78 mph today as it surged westward toward the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. At noon EDT, the second hurricane of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> season was centered near 17.5 degrees north latitude and 59.5 degrees west longitude, or 425 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, rushing westward across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> at 20 mph. Hurricane warnings were posted for the Lesser Antilles from <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>. A hurricane watch was in effect for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION>. `` It's very warm water. There's not anything in the atmosphere to cause it to break up, so basically it looks good for further development,'' said meteorologist <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. `` Right now, it's away from any land area, but it could affect the easternmost islands of the Lesser Antilles within the next 6 to 12 hours. Rainfall of 5-10 inches and tides 3 to 5 feet above normal were possible. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> could be in danger in three or four days from <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, which is called a <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> storm because it formed off the west coast of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` When we see a hurricane like that we realize that it has the potential to move all the way across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and threaten the southeastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said hurricane center forecaster <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chantal </PERSON>, the first hurricane of the season, was downgraded to a tropical depression Tuesday night after hitting <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> High </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, midway between <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arthur </LOCATION>. It was blamed for at least two deaths. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> began Monday as the fifth tropical depression of the season. It became a named storm Monday night when its winds reached 39 mph. Tropical storms become hurricanes when their top sustained winds hit 74 mph. Three other depressions have grown into named storms since the season began June 1.
