<HEAD>US Was Investigating Von Karajan's Nazi Past, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Austrian conductor <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> was under investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> over allegations of involvement in Nazi persecution, but the case against him was dropped when he died last month, a government lawyer said Wednesday. Had he lived, `` there might have been a question of the watchlist'' _ putting the famed musician on a list of people banned from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for their <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> pasts _ said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigations </ORGANIZATION>. Among the allegations were that von <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> might have worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> security police and had a role in ridding German orchestras of Jews and other `` non-Aryans,'' said <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>. The investigation was begun several months ago, before von <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> died in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> on July 16 at the age of 81, <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. `` We were looking at what his role in Nazi persecution might have been,'' said <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>. `` I do n't know where the investigation would have led, but there might have been a question of the watchlist.'' Thousands of people have been placed on the list, including Austrian President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>. The office investigated him in 1986 and reached a finding that played a role in Nazi persecution during World War II while he served as an intelligence officer. <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> joined the fledgling <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1933 in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and then rejoined in 1934 when he moved to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. Under the sponsorship of <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> <PERSON> Goering </PERSON>, the field marshal who founded the Gestapo, <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON>'s career flourished. `` He was the cultural showpiece of the most horrendous regime ever. At the time they were throwing people in the ovens he was holding concerts,'' <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. To say von <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> was just an artist `` is a revisionist view of history,'' <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. For two years after the war ended in 1945 von <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> was banned from performing by the Allied powers who occupied <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, because of his collaboration with the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. His first tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1954, at the head of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Philharmonic which he conducted for 34 years, was greeted by widespread protests. <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> was a frequent visitor to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the last time in February, <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. `` There were many questions about him that deserved answers,'' but with his death the case has been closed, he said.
