<SECOND>AM-Drug Treaty,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Urges Approval of International Drug Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> urged a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel Wednesday to ratify an international anti-drug trafficking treaty. The pact will `` provide us with enhanced law enforcement tools and can lead to substantial advances in our international cooperative efforts'' to counter the illegal drug market, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The attorney general signed the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illicit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances on behalf of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last December in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. The treaty includes a provision under which `` all the nations signing the convention have agreed to exchange evidence of criminal conduct and to extradite accused traffickers so that safe havens are no longer so readily available,'' he said. However, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> noted in response to questions from Chairman <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, that the treaty does not obligate countries to extradite their own nationals wanted on drug-related charges in other countries. `` The convention in and of itself is not going to provide a remedy to the extradition problem of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>,'' where the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> several years ago declared unconstitutional its extradition treaty with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that allowed drug traffickers to remain there when they were wanted on charges in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said. In addition, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, Jr., D-Del., that the treaty would allow the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to withhold investigative information from governments it perceives to be corrupt, even if they have signed the document `` I think we would have no hesitation about doing that ...,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. `` Our obligation to our own citizens would transcend'' the treaty requirement to share information. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the president would decide whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should seek extradition of someone overseas wanted on drug charges here when the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> does n't want that to occur. `` I have not had such a case arise,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>. `` The obvious instinct of a prosecutor ... is to prosecute. However, all of us recognize the prosecutions may have to be foregone for national security reasons.'' <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitsky </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for international narcotics matters, attended the hearing but did not comment. Panamanian Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted by two federal grand juries on drug-trafficking charges in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> last year, before <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> became attorney general. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reportedly offered to drop the criminal charges against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> if he would step down from power in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The treaty calls for extradition of accused drug traffickers and the exchange of law enforcement information. It also seeks to lift `` the veil of bank secrecy'' to help uncover money-laundering operations, requires supervision of the manufacturing and sale of chemicals used in the production of illegal drugs, mandates that commercial carriers ensure their cargos are free of drugs, and reaffirms the need for aggressive efforts in crop eradication and demand reduction, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. The agreement requires each signatory to pass laws outlawing drug trafficking and money laudering while enabling the countries to seize drug profits, but the laws of each country would take precedence. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> noted that all legislation by each country is `` subject to their constitutional principles and basic concepts of their legal systems.'' The treaty, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said, `` will assist in the eradication of drugs and drug-producing laboratories, and in preventing the transportation of precursor chemicals from this nation and others to the drug-producing countries for use in drug production. `` The convention will also help to hinder the importation of drugs into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and prevent the transfer of the profits of the illegal drug trade back to the drug cartels,'' he said.
