<HEAD>Wildfires Threaten Idaho Hamlets, Burn 215,000 Acres in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB FICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flames pushed within 300 yards of the rustic <ORGANIZATION> Sourdough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lodge </ORGANIZATION> and theatened two <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> hamlets Wednesday, but cooler weather was turning the tide against some of the wildfires buring in five western states. `` It all depends on the wind,'' said Sourdough owner <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahern </PERSON>, who refused to leave his inn outside <PERSON> Lowman </PERSON>. `` If we do n't get any wind, we could walk away from this thing heads high. If the wind changes, my friend, this is going to be one big black hole.'' Wildfires have consumed more than 215,000 acres _ or 335 square miles _ of timber, brush and grassland in the West since the middle of last week, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, the government's wildfire command post. Most were ignited by lightning. Big fires continued to burn Wednesday in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, while smaller blazes were fought in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, moist, cool air slowed the flames' advance. `` Those conditions really help suppression,'' <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lynette </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. `` But then its supposed to get hotter again by the weekend so we've got to get something done before then.'' More than 15,000 firefighters were on the lines throughout the West, and reinforcements continued to arrive from outside the region and from the military. Fifteen buses carrying 500 soldiers left the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> on Wesdnesday to join the battle in eastern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. The soldiers, who got a crash course in fire safety, were to be joined by 500 more troops Thursday, said Capt. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>, spokesman for the fort south of <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, where 94,000 acres of timber and range have burned, crews had to concentrate on protecting structures scattered throughout the <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Payette </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Nez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Perce </LOCATION> national forests rather than on containing the flames. `` They save the structures first and fight the fires second,'' Ms. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. Air tankers were dumping flame-retardant chemicals at a rate of one-quarter of a million gallons of retardant a day on the most stubborn of the blazes. <PERSON> Lowman </PERSON>, population 15, was largely leveled by flames over the weekend, and shifting winds Wednesday renewed the threat to cabins scattered near the town 70 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ahern </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Sourdough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lodge </ORGANIZATION> was one of the few to ignore the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> advice to leave. Fire crews poured so much soap-like foam on the building that it took on a mid-winter snowy look. Even the tops of the surrounding firs were white. The fire was so hot it melted asphalt on the highway, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> 21, east and west of <PERSON> Lowman </PERSON>. Fire also neared the small mining town of <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION>, 120 miles north of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, where 16 of the 36 residents fled and the rest prepared to move to an open area if the threat increased. Hundreds of firefighters ringed the town with 1,000 feet of hose, putting sprinklers on each building as wind sent the fire racing to within a mile of the buildings. The situation Wednesday elsewhere in the West: _ In eastern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, where 85,000 acres have been blackened, cool weather gave firefighters hope they could turn back several big timber and range blazes, said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. Several smaller blazes were contained, and the spread of the bigger fires around the towns of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and Enterprise had stopped, she said. _ In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, a brush fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> that has blackened 8,200 acres destroyed a house and a mobile home was 50 percent contained Wednesday. More than 1,300 firefighters supperted by air tankers and helicopters struggled in sporadic wind and tough terrain to contain the blaze 90 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> foothills in central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, 3,000-acre fire burned out of control in grass and brush, but did n't pose a theat to structures. _ In <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, firefighters were close to containing an 800-acre grass and timber fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Custer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. About 300 firefighters were working to cut lines around the blaze in the southeastern corner of the state. _ In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, firefighters were mopping up the 850-acre Lodgepole fire in the North Cascades near the Canadian border.
