<HEAD>Homeless Looking Out for Themselves as Spiked Wine Threat Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Homeless people have formed a `` neighborhood watch'' to protect themselves from the threat posed by wine bottles spiked with glass shards that someone has been leaving around town. Thirty-two spiked bottles have been found in the last month at various places where the homeless are known to go. No one has been hurt, police said Wednesday. `` People in suburban neighborhoods have these neighborhood watches because they're worried about crime. ... Well, homeless people are victims of crimes too,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, who camps near downtown, said. `` Somebody may take a belt of this wine and get hurt real bad. So some of us are walking the streets every night and keeping our eyes open.'' He said the homeless are not the only ones in danger. A group of children recently found six bottles in a park. Some advocates for the homeless contend that the police did not respond quickly enough. `` If this had been a case of adulterated food in grocery stores, you would have had a serious response immediately,'' said <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Haggstrom </PERSON>, coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barbara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeless </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>. Police say they are aggressively investigating and have assigned a detective to the case full-time. Although police did not begin posting flyers warning the homeless until July 20, the department issued a press release July 1, after the first bottle was found. `` We're finding these bottles in a relatively large geographical area, so it's not an easy case,'' Sgt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Glaus </PERSON> said. `` And it's not like food tampering inside a store where you can track down manufacturing and distribution methods. With the wine bottles, it appears as if the glass has been put inside the bottles after they were purchased.''
