<HEAD>Sultan's Heir Officially Attains Adulthood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and local royalty welcomed the 15-year-old future ruler of this tiny oil-rich nation into the adult world Wednesday by sprinkling scented water on his hands. Cannons fired in salute and thousands of Bruneians watched on TV to watch the ritual for Prince <PERSON> Al-Muhtadee </PERSON> <PERSON> Billah </PERSON>, the son of Sultan <PERSON> Hassanal </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolkia </PERSON>. Leaders from <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, as well as 3,000 other VIPs, including members of the royal family, government dignitaries and foreign diplomats, were invited to the two-hour ceremony in the throne hall of the sultan's 1,778-room palace The pomp and pageantry, a combination of Islamic ritual and Malay culture, were actually a commemoration of Prince <PERSON> Billah </PERSON>'s circumcision, a momentous event in the life of Malay Moslems Even though the prince, eldest son of the 43-year-old sultan, was circumcised a few years ago, the ceremonies were dubbed `` berkhatan'' _ Malay for circumcision. `` Coming of age is a more appropriate term,'' an official said, but tradition dictates that such ceremonies be called berkhatan. A weeklong festival for the occasion began Sunday with the beating of gongs and playing of pipes and other ethnic musical instruments at the main gate to the 300-acre palace grounds. The streets of the capital were decorated with multicolored lights and yellow <LOCATION> Bruneian </LOCATION> flags fluttering from the top of virtually every building. Until Wednesday, however, the ceremonies had consisted of solemn prayers, chants of religious hymns and nightly poetry readings at the palace. A few hours before Wednesday's rites, the sultan, cited by the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> as the world's wealthiest man, threw an elaborate dinner at the cavernous royal banquet hall, whose arches are covered with 22-carat gold tiles. His guest list was headed by President <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and Prime Ministers <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON> <PERSON> Choonhavan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. In declaring the sultan the world's richest individual, <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> said that as its absolute ruler, he has <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>'s oil income and foreign exchange reserves of about $ 30 billion `` effectively at his disposal.'' After all guests were seated, about 100 men and boys marched up the middle of the hall, bearing Prince <PERSON> Billah </PERSON>'s regalia. They included spears, swords, shields, rifles, pennants, candles, drums, brass vases and urns. Behind them walked the young prince, in a green costume gleaming with gold embroidery. Light from 12 giant chandeliers _ each with 600 bulbs _ reflected off the gems on his headdress. The normally shy boy appeared nervous. Just before Moslem priests began chanting praise to Allah, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Billah </PERSON> rose from his cushioned throne-like chair, set under a gold-colored canopy. Apparently realizing the miscue, he quickly sat back, his head bowed slightly. As the chanting began, the boy's parents, the leaders and other guests came forward one by one and sprinkled scented water on his hands, resting on a cushion on his lap. Outside, cannons boomed. Prince <PERSON> Billah </PERSON> is the third of the sultan's six children by <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Saleha </PERSON>, his first wife, but the elder of two boys. The sultan has a son and two daughters by his second wife, <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON>. On Thursday, the prince will undergo a cleansing ceremony in the privacy of his apartments. Officials say the equivalent of this rite for commoners is a swim in a river. After that, 25,000 children and other residents are expected to line the streets of <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Seri </PERSON> <PERSON> Begawan </PERSON> to cheer <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Billah </PERSON> as he rides past on a float. Ceremonies at the palace are to continue through Sunday.
