<FIRST>r a AM-TransplantDrugs     08-02 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transplant Drugs,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drugs Promising For Transplanted Organs, Says Researcher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An experimental drug that stimulates rather than suppresses the immune system offers new hope in preventing rejection of transplanted human organs, a researcher says. `` The central dogma has been that if you stimulate the immune system, that's bad,'' Dr. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immunology </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview. `` We're developing a new dogma that says it's possible to use the immune system as an ally.'' Results of his research, which includes successful testing in rodents, were delivered Wednesday to delegates to the triennial <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Immunology in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> is testing lectins, proteins derived from plant tissue. He said lectins promote the growth of certain white blood cells called T-supressors. While the action of the T-supressors is not clear, they apparently restrain another type of white blood cell, T-killers, that attack foreign tissue, including transplanted organs. In experiments at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION>, transplanted hearts in rats remained free of rejection for more than two years with no side effects. The rats received 50 days of lectin treatment, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said in the telephone interview, before his <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> speech. Tests on humans are still years away, he said. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said the lectins and two other experimental drugs will require extensive further testing, but may someday reduce the need for large doses of cyclosporine, a potent drug now used to prevent transplant rejection by depressing the immune system. `` If our initial hopes are proven, we are nearing a fundamental turning point in being able to keep transplant patients healthier and alive longer,'' he said. Since human organ transplants began with kidneys about 35 years ago, doctors have been unable to prevent the rejection of transplanted organs without compromising the immune system. Cyclosporine, derived from a soil fungus, helps prevent rejection by restraining the formation of white blood cells that attack transplanted organs. But the daily oral doses can lead to kidney failure and high blood pressure. Two other transplant experts _ Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> and Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Corry </PERSON>, chairman of surgery at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> and president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharing </ORGANIZATION> _ said the use of lectins is virtually untested elsewhere. <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> said <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' idea of boosting the immune system to prevent organ rejection is a departure from current thinking on the problem. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said tests at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION> found lectins and two other drugs, FK-506 and RPM, were effective in preventing rejection of transplanted hearts in rodents. Like cyclosporine, he said, FK-506 and RPM are derived from fungus and work by depressing the immune system, but they are more powerful. FK-506, developed several years ago by a Japanese company, was nearly 20 times more potent than cyclosporine in rodent testing, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. Heart transplants in rats treated for two weeks with FK-506 survived eight times longer, some longer than a year, than recipients treated with cyclosporine, even though the FK-506 dose was only one-fifth that of cyclosporine, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> said his testing of FK-506 indicated that while it may be powerful, it was too early to predict its potential. <PERSON> Corry </PERSON> said the hope is that FK-506 would be less toxic but more effective than cyclosporin.
</TEXT>
