<HEAD>Truckers Say Refrigerated Food Trucks Also Carry Garbage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Truckers testifying behind a screen to conceal their identities told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel Wednesday that they carried garbage in the same refrigerated trucks used for food hauls, a legal practice a lawmaker called `` more than disgusting.'' `` Would you serve potato salad from your cat's litter box?'' <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> food science professor <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Kroger </PERSON> rhetorically asked a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee during an all-day hearing. The investigations subcommittee released correspondence showing that <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Geo </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hormel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and other food manufacturers had taken steps in the last two months to ensure that their products were not placed in the same trailers that hauled waste to landfills. None of the food firms said it knew of such a practice, but all said they wanted to safeguard against it. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said an investigation had found no contaminated food. The vice president and driver for a small, family-owned trucking firm specializing in hauling meat products from the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> to the East told the subcommittee food-garbage hauling appeared widespread. `` Of the ten largest carriers in my area that haul refrigerated food products to the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, six of them I know have loaded it -LRB- garbage -RRB-,'' he said. A woman trucker told the panel her firm hauled two loads of garbage on return trips by food trucks to the Midwest. She said she refused other loads because `` I just did n't want to put it in the trucks.'' Both truckers who testified were hidden by a partition on three sides because they did not want their identities made public, according to the committee, which also would not divulge their home states. Part of the problem is that trucks making trips East can not afford to return to the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> empty, the male trucker said. He said garbage is `` a dream commodity'' to return home with because `` you're not responsible for anything. How could you destroy it?'' Still, he said he felt there could be sanitary problems, even though his trucks are steam-cleaned. `` I'm not a bacteriologist,'' he said. He said his meat-hauling trucks used to carry bales of waste to a landfill near <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, but stopped in June at the request of customers. The <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in an inquiry last month confirmed the practice of food trucks carrying garbage, according to testimony. In one instance, a food truck emptied at an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> landfill `` emanated powerful garbage odors'' despite just being washed, said <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaillard </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION>'s Office of Compliance and Consumer Assistance. Before the garbage haul, the truck had carried avocadoes from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <PERSON