<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors are amazed at the quick recovery of a 73-year-old American nun who was seriously wounded when she was shot in the head during an apparent robbery attempt in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> six weeks ago. Sister <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanislaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON>, a member of the Sisters of Charity of the Incarnate Word, will be moved to a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> convent this week to continue her recuperation, doctors at <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. `` I think the outcome approaches miracle stage when one considers she was shot in the head at close range with a large-caliber handgun,'' <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrish </PERSON>, the nun's neurosurgeon, said. ` Sister <PERSON> Stan </PERSON>,' as she is called, was hit by a .38 - caliber bullet June 21 as she and two other nuns rode in a pickup truck in <LOCATION> Zaragoza </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> The sisters are unsure of the motive for the attack, but speculate the gunman, one of several men in a pickup truck, wanted to rob the nuns, who had just been to a bank. Sister <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON> worked in the town 10 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in an orphanage for children whose parents have been killed in the nine-year civil war between leftist guerrillas and the government. The bullet shattered her cheekbone. After initial treatment in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, she was flown to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, where her religious order is based. Doctors operated June 26 to remove a bullet fragment lodged in her brain and to relieve swelling in her brain. A second operation was performed July 8 to reattach the retina in her left eye. `` There appears to have been some damage to her optic nerve and we're not sure how much