<HEAD>Official: Communists Could Enact Own Multiparty Law Without Opposition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior communist official indicated Wednesday that his party could enact its own legislation on political reform if talks founder with the opposition, but a communist negotiator urged patience. The comment by Deputy Justice Minister <PERSON> Geza </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> came hours after members of the opposition accused the ruling communists of dragging their feet in negotiations that broke down last week. The negotiations broke down over the wording of a new constitution, a new party law, party finances and the office of a new president with wide powers. The first multiparty elections in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> since the 1948 communist takeover are slated to be held next year. <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> indicated legislative measures already drawn up by the communists, but tabled for review in talks with the opposition, could be considered in Parliament without discussion if the negotiations remain inconclusive. `` If there is no suitable progress made, we will simply take those items of draft legislation and put them back on the table again in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Kilenyi </PERSON> criticized the Opposition Round Table, which includes nine opposition groups, for what he called their inflexibility. But <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> secretary <PERSON> Gyerogy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fejti </PERSON>, a leading communist negotiator, said he still seeks an agreement. `` It does not help the achievement of a compromise if differing views are made public too early,'' <PERSON> Fejti </PERSON> said. `` Compromise requires an atmosphere of patience and calm.'' <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, a top reformer on the Executive Political Committee -LRB- Politburo -RRB-, has promised an agreement regardless of how long it takes. At an earlier news conference, <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kis </PERSON> of the League of Free Democrats alleged the Hungarian Socialist Workers -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Party `` is trying to suggest to the nation that the choice is between that party and chaos.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Toelgyessy </PERSON> of the League of Free Democrats said the communists want to retain in the constitution the paragraph on the working class as the leading social force in the nation `` and other such holdovers from the present constitution based on the Stalinist model.'' He said the communists want `` to use the constitutional state as a smokescreen and continue business as usual under the same management.'' The opposition groups disagree on the need to have a law on parties, contending that the existing law on association is sufficient and only a law on party financing and operation is needed. A major obstacle in the talks is whether the wealth of the communist party should be distributed to other groups. On July 27, the communists, who had been amenable to discussing the issue, reversed their position. They said the party acquired its assets legally and that distribution of the money is an internal party affair. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Fejti </PERSON> sidestepped a question on his party's financial holdings There is also disagreement on who may field candidates in first multi-party elections next year and how many signatures will be required to get on the ballot and where and how such signatures may be collected.
