<HEAD>6th Fleet Flagship Cancels Soviet Port Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The flagship of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 6th Fleet canceled a ceremonial visit to a Soviet port, and it and other warships were put `` at the beck and call'' of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday in case they're needed in the hostage situation, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The aircraft carrier <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and eight escort ships also cut short a port call in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, other officials said, but the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> refused to reveal the carrier's destination or the reason for the battle group's early departure. Military officials, speaking privately, emphasized that the ship movements were not `` bellicose'' actions and noted that the forces in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> area remain at the normal peace-time level. But the announcements highlighted the type of `` show-the-flag'' movements designed to give the impression that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces are ready to act if the president decides to use them. `` We're positioning ourselves at the beck and call of the president,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official familiar with the tactics. `` These are not necessarily bellicose moves _ but we want to be ready in case we are needed. ... These are prudent measures,'' the official said. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official stressed that `` extensive on-scene diplomatic efforts'' are under way, and that emphasis is not being placed on a possible military strike. `` We are just giving the president what he might need,'' the official said. But, the official also pointed out, in case a strike is ordered, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships are ready with their long-range guns, aircraft and missiles, even if they remain some distance from a possible target. `` You do n't have to be near the shore to do what may be necessary,'' the official said. In a statement, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced that the USS Belknap, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> flagship in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, canceled a four-day call at the port of <LOCATION> Sevastapol </LOCATION>. Two other ships, the USS <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kauffman </LOCATION>, were slated to keep to the scheduled visit, set for Aug. 4-8. The <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON>, a guided missile cruiser with fleet commander Vice Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> aboard, had been scheduled to call at the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> port as part of a long-planned exchange worked out between the superpowers. Three Soviet ships just departed <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, after conducting the first such visit to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> port in 14 years. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and his ship `` are required elsewhere and will not be able to visit <LOCATION> Sevastopol </LOCATION>,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> statement said. The statement made no mention of the reported execution of Lt. Col. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>, or of threats by Shiite Moslem factions to execute another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hostage. The cancellation of the <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON>'s visit allows <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> to remain in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> in case his services are needed there, said other officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. On Tuesday, the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft carrier in the <ORGANIZATION> 6th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>, the USS Coral Sea, had left <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, `` several hours earlier'' than planned, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sources said. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, following normal policy, refused to divulge the destination of any of the carriers or their battle groups. One official pointed out that if the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is headed in the direction of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, it will take nearly a week for the carrier to cross the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. Overall, there are between 20 to 25 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> at this time, with approximately 20 others in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> region, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The battleship <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, which is not allowed to use its 16-inch guns pending the outcome of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> inquiry into the April explosion in one of its three turrets, ended its port call in <LOCATION> Marseilles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, and is in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, the sources said. The ship has a variety of weapons, including cruise missiles, that could be used if necessary, sources said. Also on permanent station in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> is a three-ship amphibious landing group composed of 2,400 Marines, officials said. `` This is very typical of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> official. `` There is nothing unique about our deployment there. It's our normal peace-time position,'' he said. The official added that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s duty is to provide a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence around the world and the ship movements allow routine patrols as well as for training. `` We have to train as if we were at war, and you ca n't do that in port,'' he said.
