<HEAD>HHS Head Says Methadone Programs Not Perfect, But Helpful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Health Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday that while methadone programs are `` not ideal,'' they are better than doing nothing to help heroin addicts quit their habit and avoid AIDS. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, testifying before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Narcotics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, defended his department's proposal to make methadone available to more addicts to prevent needle-sharing and help curb the spread of AIDS. `` This is not ideal,'' he said in response to two studies critical of the plan. `` But this, we feel, is better than nothing for those individuals.'' He emphasized that the program proposed in March would be an `` interim step'' that would allow heroin addicts to receive methadone while they wait for an opening in a comprehensive methadone treatment program. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, in separate studies presented to the committee, questioned the wisdom of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>' plan. They cited continued drug abuse by many patients in treatment and illegal diversion of the methadone. Under the <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> proposal, heroin addicts unable to get into a comprehensive treatment program would be able to receive methadone daily at outpatient clinics and from mobile medical units. The synthetic narcotic would not be provided for take-home use and addicts would be counseled on avoiding AIDS. Heroin addicts often share needles and, in doing so, can spread or contract the AIDS virus. Methadone, which is used to help relieve an addict's craving for heroin and is less addictive, is taken by mouth, eliminating the risk from needles. About 100,000 people were undergoing methadone treatment last year; the government estimates there are about 500,000 heroin addicts nationwide. Preliminary results of the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study of 15 methadone programs in five states indicate that as many as 47 percent of patients in treatment for more than six months at one clinic continued to use drugs. Forty percent of patients at another clinic used cocaine. `` Results of our work indicate that most clinics have not been able to deal effectively with the drug problems of many of their patients,'' <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shikles </PERSON>, director of national and public health issues for the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said in testimony submitted to the panel. `` It is unclear how effective the interim maintenance program would be in reducing the spread of AIDS,'' she said. `` <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> believes that additional information is needed before the program is allowed to be implemented nationwide.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> reviewed methadone clinics serving more than 3,300 patients in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Most clinic officials <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> investigators interviewed did not support the <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> plan allowing interim methadone maintenance programs, she said. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haislip </PERSON>, deputy administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diversion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, said an investigation conducted in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> metropolitan area between Aug. 21 and Sept. 16, 1988, found `` there is significant selling of take-home dosages of methadone.'' <PERSON> Haislip </PERSON> said many of the programs monitored by <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> have lax safeguards and `` routinely ignore'' test results that show patients are using other drugs rather than take taking their methadone. `` There is little incentive for individuals to become drug-free because their steady supply of methadone provides them with a constant source of illicit income with which to purchase other drugs, primarily cocaine,'' he said.
