<FIRST>r i AM-GarciaMarquez     08-02 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Garcia Marquez,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garcia Marquez Awarded Prize For Contributing To Latin Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The unity and freedom of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is a `` dream within a dream'' that must soon become reality, author <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> said Wednesday as he accepted an award for his contributions to the fulfillment of that dream. `` In his prose, <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> presents the various facets of the vision of a single <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Olloqui </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Serfin </ORGANIZATION>, told 300 people at the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> presidential residence. President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> presented the Serfin Prize to the Nobel prize-winning author but made no remarks. The prize carries no monetary award, a bank official said. <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> grappled with the problem of Latin unity in his latest book, `` The General in his Labyrinth,'' a controversial novel cast as a deathbed narrative by <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolivar </PERSON>, a hero of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s independence from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Bolivar's goal was not just independence but the creation of a united <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> federation to compete with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. That vision dissolved into the separate nations, including <ORGANIZATION> Bolivar </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Greater </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, now <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. The book has created a literary controversy because it deals with a sensitive subject and because of its demythologizing portrayal of the man known as `` the Liberator'' as a foul-mouthed libertine. In his brief remarks, <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> began by recounting a story by Italian author <PERSON> Italo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvino </PERSON> in which an emperor of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> asks a painter to portray a crab. The painter replies that it will take five years and he'll need a house with 12 servants. When the five years are up, he asks for another five years. When the emperor comes back again, the painter rises, snatches up his brush and in an instant paints the most beautiful crab ever seen. `` In this story from ancient <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> you can see a crude representation of artistic creation, the most incomprehensible and enslaving of human passions,'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> said. The 20th century, which has `` unleashed the furies of the atom as a servant of death, and seen a flag planted on the windless wastes of the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>,'' might be just another of man's many lost centuries if if were not for a dream. `` Let us dream aloud, then. Let us dream that a fundamental change has started in the world, that the craziest concentration of power in the history of mankind is ending because the dogmas that sustained the two sides are breaking down, and we are headed for a new millenium dominated by the freedom of creative thought.'' Inside those dreams, <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquz </PERSON> said, lies <PERSON> Bolivar </PERSON>'s dream, the dream of a united <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, `` finally part of the torrent of history, made up of our invincible culture, our inspired nightmares, our crazy magic, of the disasters that revive us, and the irresistible power of the imagination. `` Mr. President, ladies and gentlemen, Latin Americans all, I think it is time for us to draw the crab.''
