<FIRST>u w AM-FarmExpenses     08-02 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Expenses,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cost of Farming Continues to Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cost of running the nation's farms rose 7.5 percent to $ 118.4 billion in 1988, with farmers paying the bulk of their money for basics such as feed, stock and machinery, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. Despite the increase, the figure falls short of the record $ 131.8 billion farmers spent in 1981, just before the general financial crunch that stalled expansion in the agricultural sector. In 1987, farmers spent $ 110.1 billion for the buildings, feed, livestock, rent, labor, seeds and plants, fuels, equipment and other components of raising livestock and crops. Average expenditures per farm last year were $ 54,956, an increase of $ 4,165 from 1987. The increase outstripped the nation's overall inflation rate, which was 4.4 percent last year. Farms with annual sales of more than $ 100,000 averaged $ 271,481 in expenditures and accounted for 68 percent of the total expenses. They spent most of their money on services, feed, labor, livestock and poultry, farm machinery, interest and fertilizer. Farms with sales of $ 40,000 to $ 100,000 had expenses averaging $ 75,371 and contributed 16 percent of the total. Their main expenses were services, feed and machinery. Small farms, those with sales under $ 40,000, averaged expenses of $ 15,464 and accounted for 15 percent of the total. Feed, farm services and farm machinery were the leading expenses. Feed was the highest single cost item at $ 17.9 billion dollars in 1988, accounting for 15.1 percent of total costs. The previous year, feed cost $ 14.9 billion dollars and accounted for 13.5 percent of expenses, the highest single expense item that year as well. The livestock and poultry that devour that feed cost $ 13.6 billion, accounting for 11.5 percent of the total. Last year, the cattle, swine and poultry, including stud services, cost $ 10.7 billion, accounting for 9.7 percent of the total. The machinery to do the farm work cost $ 11.5 billion, for 9.7 percent of total expenses, up from $ 10.9 billion. A composite category _ farm services, including rent, _ was the largest one, $ 24.6 billion, accounting for 21 percent of the nation's production expenses. That's up from $ 24 billion in 1987. That category includes cash and share rent, vet supplies and services, marketing and storage expenses, insurance, utilities, leasing and transportation. The only expenses to drop were interest payments, which decreased 3.7 percent to $ 8.37 billion, and building and fencing, which dropped 10.3 percent to $ 2.23 billion. The analysis dealt only with production expenditures and did not include figures for net income or profits. Annual spending by farmers reached its nadir this decade in 1986, when many massively cut back their capital investments during a time of plummeting land values and rising debt burdens.
</TEXT>
