<HEAD>Red Cross Launches Campaign To Prevent Child Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> launched a national campaign Wednesday aimed at preventing child deaths from choking, suffocation and drowning. The Infant and Child CPR Campaign encourages parents, grandparents, baby sitters and other care-givers to learn how to handle breathing emergencies in infants and children. Actress <PERSON> Lynda </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, who has an 18-month-old boy, lent her name to the campaign. `` There's a lot a parent can do before the ambulance arrives,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnside </PERSON>, director of health services for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. The Heimlich maneuver, however, is not among them. That method of using abdominal thrusts to dislodge obstructions in the breathing passages works on choking adults but does more harm than good when used on a baby, <PERSON> Burnside </PERSON> said. A choking baby needs to be held in a certain way and be given a series of blows to the back and thrusts to the chest to restore breathing, he said. The technique taught in the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Infant </ORGANIZATION> and Child CPR course was highlighted in a segment of the CBS daytime drama `` The Young and the Restless'' Wednesday when a choking emergency occurred to a young child. Besides choking emergencies, the seven-hour <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> course teaches mouth-to-mouth rescue breathing, cardiopulmonary resuscitation and injury prevention. Thousands of children who die from choking, suffocation and drowning could be saved if more adults knew how to respond to the emergencies, <PERSON> Burnside </PERSON> said. Choking and suffocation are leading causes of accidental deaths in children under 1 year old, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Injury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Among children ages 1-4, drowning is the second leading cause of accidental deaths after motor vehicle accidents.
