<SECOND>AM-Child Abuse,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Many Teachers Feel More Training Needed on Child Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elementary-school teachers are underreporting child-abuse cases because they are n't adequately trained to recognize or deal with them, according to a study released Wednesday. Fifty-seven percent of the more than 2.1 million reports of child abuse and neglect in 1986 involved school-age children, but only 16.3 percent of all reports filed with child-protective agencies originated with school personnel, said the study by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION>. `` The results of the survey point out a major problem in our efforts to prevent child abuse,'' said committee Executive Director <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON>. All states require teachers to report instances of child abuse, Ms. <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said. But the committee's survey found that only 50 percent of the 480 elementary-school teachers polled had received any training in the identification, reporting and prevention of such cases, she said. Most who said they received such training said it was inadequate. The teachers surveyed taught first grade through sixth grade in 39 school districts nationwide, Ms. <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said. The Chicago-based committee, described as a national, volunteer-based organization, tried to assess teachers' knowledge, attitudes and beliefs about child abuse, as well as their opinions on reporting child abuse and on prevention programs. Seventy-two percent of the teachers surveyed said they suspected that at least one of their students had been abused or neglected, and 90 percent said they had reported such cases, Ms. <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said. However, reports commonly went to other school personnel, such as a principal, social worker or nurse. Only about 20 percent of the teachers said they reported abuse directly to child-protective agencies, as required by most states' laws. Only 57 percent of those polled said their districts had clearly defined polices on reporting suspicions of child abuse. Twenty-four percent did n't know if their districts had such policies, although 95 percent of the nation's districts say they have clearly set guidelines for teachers to follow, Ms. <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said. `` Not only are many teachers unaware of the existence of those school policies, but many do not seem to understand the policies that do exist,'' she said. According to the survey, teachers are concerned about the legal ramifications of reporting child abuse even though most states grant immunity from lawsuits to teachers who report child-abuse suspicions in good faith, Ms. <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> said her organization believes administrators need to `` dramatically expand the education they provide their teachers so that ... teachers can feel much more comfortable and much more competent in their ability to identify and report child abuse.'' The survey also asked teachers about corporal punishment and found that 57 percent felt it should be eliminated. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> to Abolish Corporal Punishment in Schools, said the drive to stop corporal punishment received a big boost this year, with eight states banning the practice. `` For the first time in the history of our country's education system, more than half of the school children in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> now attend schools that have prohibited hitting, slapping, punching, hair-pulling, paddling or other firms of corporal punishment by educators,'' <PERSON> Fathman </PERSON> said.
