<FIRST>u w AM-RiceMarket     08-02 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rice Market,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coals to Newcastle? Try Rice to China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is forecast to become a net importer of rice for the first time in recent history, helping create a record worldwide trade in rice in 1989, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The report, `` Rice: Situation and Outlook Yearbook,'' says <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> are fueling this year's record demand, with trade forecast at 13.4 million metric tons. The previous record was 13.1 million metric tons set in 1981, the report said. Although the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will increase its exports 10 percent this year to 2.5 million metric tons, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> will be the big winner, exporting a record 5.5 million metric tons. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share of the export, 19 percent, and the Thai share, 41 percent, will be the same as last year, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has already bought 950,000 tons from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, which has been exporting rice at `` an extraordinary pace'' since August 1988, the report said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is expected to buy 1.2 million tons of rice this year from all sources, the report said. That is triple the amount bought the previous year. The report said `` it is unclear how or if the current turmoil in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will affect its short-term rice trade.'' `` There have been few reports of exports in the first half of 1989, and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is forecast to export only 300,000 tons by the end of the year, less than half the amount it exported in 1988,'' the report said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> will also account for about a 5 percent drop in the 1990 market when their crops improve and stocks are replenished. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> account for over 50 percent of the world's rice production. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> imports rice to feed its urban populations. In the forecast for 1990 contained in the report, the department cites reports that farmers will keep more rice on the farm because of the government system of paying farmers with IOUs that can not be redeemed immediately. <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> is forecast to import 400,000 tons and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> will likely take in 500,000 tons, the report says. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> are expecting record crops in the crop year 1989-1990. <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> are the main rice-growing states. The main <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> customers are <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Low stocks and strong import demand caused world prices to soar starting in January. They reached $ 8.91 per hundredweight in July, after having fallen to $ 5.90 in December 1988. Recent prices were at their lowest in 1986-1987, when abundant world prices kept them down as far as $ 3.78 a hundredweight. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmers are planting 2.8 million acres in rice this year, 5 percent less than a year ago, the department estimates. Yields are unlikely to show improvement, meaning a drop in production, the department says.
</TEXT>
