<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes On Takeoff, Six Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Emergency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A twin-engine plane crashed on takeoff Wednesday at <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>'s airport, getting barely aloft before tumbling to the ground and exploding in flames. Six people were killed, authorities said. The Beechcraft Queen Air BE-80 was bound for <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoefer </PERSON>, an air traffic controller at <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Regional Airport. The plane had climbed only about 10 feet off the ground when its right engine caught fire, witnesses said. The plane's right wing then slammed into the ground, spewing fuel as the aircraft cartwheeled several times, the witnesses reported. The plane, engulfed in flames, came to rest upside down and broken apart near the control tower. The fire prevented any rescue, witnesses said. `` There's not much you can do when that gas ignited,'' said off-duty <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilot <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, who saw the crash. Rescue crews left the victims' bodies in the wreckage until investigators from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> could examine it, said Fire Chief J.D. <PERSON> Jansen </PERSON>. `` As far as we can determine now we have six fatalities,'' said <PERSON> Jansen </PERSON>. Six people, including the pilot, were driven by van from the terminal and boarded the plane minutes before takeoff, said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradshaw </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Gray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the van's driver. The victims were not immediately identified. The plane was registered to Rainbow Properties of <LOCATION> Sarasota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Vedder </PERSON> <PERSON> Steed </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>.
