with Bush's efforts. Picks up 12th graf, `There are...' with minor editing
to TRIM. ^LaserPhotos NY31,32</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official went to southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> Wednesday to press the search for the body of a slain American hostage as a glimmer of hope came from the Shiite Moslem camp that a second hostage would be spared. The victim, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>, was on <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> duty when he was abducted. <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> sources said they expected kidnappers threatening the life of <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON>, 58, of <LOCATION> Norristown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, to spare him at <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s behest to avert a confrontation with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Pro-Iranian kidnappers said they hanged <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON> on Monday in retaliation for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s abduction Friday of a Lebanese Shiite cleric. The colonel was seized Feb. 17, 1988, near Tyre in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> said Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, at President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s request, would assist in efforts to have <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' body returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Wednesday he is `` leaving no stone unturned'' in trying to free American hostages but lacks hard information as he tries to deal with the crisis `` in a prudent way.'' He said he contacted many world leaders and `` We have had assurance after assurance ... they want to help.'' British officials in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> talked for 20 minutes about the crisis. A videotape the kidnappers provided shows a man, apparently <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>, hanging from a gallows. No body has been found and there is no way of knowing when the tape was made. Some reports have said <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON> was killed months ago. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said the USS Belknap, flagship of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 6th Fleet, and the fleet commander canceled a visit to <LOCATION> Sevastopol </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in case <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> needs them, but said a military strike was unlikely. The aircraft carrier <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> cut short a visit to <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, they said. <PERSON> Marrack </PERSON> <PERSON> Goulding </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> undersecretary-general for peacekeeping operations, flew to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in the Lebanese border town of <LOCATION> Naqoura </LOCATION> by helicopter from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. He met with Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Lars-Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Wahlgren </PERSON>, Swedish commander of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, and battalion commanders of the nine-nation force known as <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> to investigate <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' death and try to find his body. <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Timor </PERSON> <PERSON> Goksel </PERSON> said <PERSON> Goulding </PERSON> put off going to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> because of the fighting but would try to make the trip Thursday. Christian forces and a Syrian-led Moslem alliance have fought an artillery war in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> for five months. The undersecretary-general is scheduled to meet with Lebanese leaders in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Goksel </PERSON> would not identify them. `` There are no negotiations involved, although he has a secondary mission of trying to find out about other hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' the spokesman said. Sixteen Westerners are captives in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, including eight Americans. Held longest is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, kidnapped March 16, 1985. <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>, 44, commanded a 75-man observer team attached to the 5,800-member <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> force. <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON>'s captors, who call themselves the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday he would be killed unless <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> freed <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Karim </PERSON> <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON> by 6 p.m. the next day. Two hours after the Tuesday deadline, the kidnappers announced a `` non-extendable postponement'' of 48 hours. No specific hour on Thursday was mentioned as a new deadline. The statement cited a plea for mercy from <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON>'s Lebanese wife, <PERSON> Elham </PERSON>, and other `` friendly appeals and sincere behests.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON> said Wednesday: `` Even if it was a postponement for only one minute, it's better than nothing.'' <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> sources said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> might have stepped in to save <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON> because of the international uproar created by <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' death. An organization caling itself the Organization of the Oppressed on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> claimed to hold <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>. Nearly all the groups holding hostages are believed to be fronts for <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, a <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> movement in which <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON> is a spiritual leader. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has offered to exchange <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> prisoners for the foreign hostages and three of its soldiers held prisoner in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> rejected the deal. <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Arens </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> foreign minister, said Wednesday there was a `` good possibility'' hostages would be freed, but other officials said negotiations could be lengthy. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> sponsors <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, which also holds two of the three <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers. Israeli commandos abducted <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON>, 33, and two aides from his home in Jibchit, a south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> village. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> denies any connection with the hostages, but publicly endorsed the Oppressed on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> group when it claimed responsibility for <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' abduction. One Lebanese Shiite source said: `` The Iranians probably are bringing immense pressure on their Lebanese surrogates, seeking to defuse the crisis generated by <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>' murder. They can do without a showdown with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, just elected president of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, has sought improved relations with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> in the past in hopes of aid in rebuilding from eight years of war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Other Shiite sources said the emergence of <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s most powerful politician had meant a decline in the influence over <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> of a hard-line rival, Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON> Analysts say the hostages' fate may be dictated by the struggle between those known as pragmatists, led by <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, and hard-liners over the direction of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 10-year-old Islamic revolution. The first Shiite source noted that <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> is not known to have killed a hostage, but has issued death threats in the past. The Revolutionary Justice statement announcing the 48-hour postponement for <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON> was accompanied by a picture of another <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> hostage it holds, writer <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON>, 58. Statements from the group threatened both men's lives twice in 1988. <PERSON> Cicippio </PERSON> was acting comptroller of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beirut </ORGANIZATION> when he was abducted from its campus on Sept. 12, 1986.
