<FIRST>r w AM-CleanAir     08-02 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Discuss Clean Air Plan with Environmental Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top administration officials met Wednesday with environmental leaders to discuss criticisms of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s clean air plan, won praise for keeping an open White House door but received no blanket commitment of support. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his environmental advisory team invited the environmentalists to discuss the acid rain provision of the clean air package and promised later meetings on the airborne toxics and urban smog sections which have prompted the most criticism from environmental activists and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The Environmental Defense Fund, which has praised <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal to curb acid rain, will lobby for that aspect of the president's package on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Krupp </PERSON> said after the White House session He said the acid rain portion `` is stronger than anything being offered'' in competing legislation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He praised <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for `` taking leadership'' on the environment that represented a `` sea change'' from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. But <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said his organization still has reservations about the provisions, in part focusing on the way the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> calculated gaseous emissions that cause acid rain. The administration claims its plan will result in a 10 million-ton reduction in sulfur dioxide emissions from 1980 levels, but the <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION>'s calculations are it will be only 9 million tons since 1 million ton reduction has already been achieved. The meeting was the latest effort by the administration to take the offensive on its clean air bill after weeks of criticism from environmental groups and their congressional backers. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> dropped by the meeting only briefly, participants said. Environmental Protection Agency Assistant Administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said the meeting was called to `` continue the dialogue'' with environmental groups. However, he insisted the administration was not positioning to make changes in the bill it sent to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last month. `` We're talking about clarifying our position, their position. Sometimes there are interpretation questions that need to be raised where we say one thing and different people read it for different results. At this point it's an information discussion and not a negotiating session. The administration's bill stands as it is,'' he said. Last week, <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> accused Democrats in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of making `` unfair and totally biased attacks'' on the legislation and of falsely calling the proposal a sellout to industry. <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON> said the administration officials at the meeting were `` very upset by the criticism the bill has got from the environmental community and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. We responded with equal vehemence that we do n't think you've been unfairly attacked. We believe what we're saying is based on the facts.'' Administration officials have complained that the environmental critics are nitpicking the bill after the administration solicited their views and addressed many of their concerns in the package. `` They certainly would like us to be more positive than we have been. I would like to be more positive than we've been able to be,'' <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Pritchard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and