<HEAD>Justice Department May Crack Down on News Leakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials who leak information to news reporters about federal criminal investigations may be prosecuted for theft of government property under a new policy announced Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The department has decided to narrow a 11-year-old policy against prosecuting officials who leak information to inform the public, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON>, a deputy assistant attorney general in the criminal division, said in written testimony submitted to a congressional hearing. In some circumstances, reporters may be called to testify at grand juries to identify leakers, although a subpoena would not be issued without the approval of the attorney general, <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON> said. This aspect of the new policy, which was unveiled at a joint hearing of two House Judiciary subcommittees, means the change could have little practical effect on leak investigations. Attorneys general historically have been unwilling to subpoena reporters, who are usually the only source of evidence about who leaked them information. But the new policy drew expressions of concern from civil libertarians who said it could be used to undermine a reporters' First Amendment protection against revealing confidential sources of information `` Once the government is able to say ` we need this information because it's material to a criminal investigation,' that raises the question of whether or not the protection of a confidential source is diluted,'' said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> media lawyer and former legislative counsel to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think it would be a definite misuse of the statute. The statute was not designed with that in mind at all,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of one of the subcommittees `` It would be a very dangerous practice.'' The policy in force since 1978 stated that `` it is inappropriate to bring a prosecution'' under the theft of government property law if information is leaked to inform the public and was n't obtained by illegal means, such as wiretaps or trespassing, <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON> said in testimony prepared for the committee. The guideline, contained in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Attorneys Manual, was designed `` to protect ` whistleblowers' and also to protect members of the media from prosecution for receipt of stolen property.'' `` We have examined this policy and concluded it is too broad,' <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON> said. `` Accordingly it is no longer applicable to government employees who leak information obtained from a criminal investigation.'' `` Moreover, we will now consider prosecution of government employees under section 641 -LRB- the theft statute -RRB- in leak cases not arising out of criminal investigations if the employee's conduct also violated some other provision such as the Privacy Act,'' <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON> said in his prepared statement. Such a leak could come from an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> background investigation of someone under consideration for a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> position, such as former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, whose nomination to be defense secretary was killed amidst allegations of womanizing and drinking. Leaks of information from the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> background investigation of Tower drew criticism from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and expressions of consternation by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON> said the `` department is in the process of deciding whether the policy should be changed in other respects.'' <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, legislative counsel at the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>, called <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON>'s announcement `` rather disturbing. <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON>'s testimony was delivered at a hearing convened in the wake of congressional concern about leaks revealing a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation into financial irregularities in the office of Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, D-Pa. The investigation was disclosed during <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s ultimately successful campaign to become <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority whip. News reports of the Gray case prompted Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> to order a leak investigation.
