<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Luiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzaga </PERSON>, a singer and accordion player who almost singlehandedly popularized the lilting music of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s rural northeast, died Wednesday of pneumonia. He was 76. <ORGANIZATION> Gonzaga </ORGANIZATION> suffered from osteoporosis, a disease that weakens the bones, and had been hospitalized for more than a month in <LOCATION> Recife </LOCATION>, 1,500 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, hospital officials said by telephone. <PERSON> Gonzaga </PERSON> was born Dec. 13, 1912 in the remote town of <LOCATION> Exu </LOCATION>, in the heart of the arid `` sertao,'' or outback. His father taught him to play the accordion, a popular instrument in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s rural northeast, and at 12 he was performing regularly at local dances. In the 1940s he came to <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, where regional music then was virtually unknown. At first considered lowbrow, <ORGANIZATION> Gonzaga </ORGANIZATION> popularized the `` baiao'' and `` forro'' music. With his moon face and trademark leather hat, typical of northeastern bandits, <ORGANIZATION> Gonzaga </ORGANIZATION> became a nationally known figure. His music dealt almost exclusively with the hard life in the poor northeast. His greatest success was `` <LOCATION> Asa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Branca </LOCATION>,'' or `` White Wing,'' about a peasant regretfully fleeing the drought-stricken backlands but pledging to return when the rains came. <ORGANIZATION> Gonzaga </ORGANIZATION>'s body was to be taken back to Exu for burial on Friday.
