<HEAD>Washington Post Guild Members Approve Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday overwhelmingly ratified a new contract that will raise salaries at the newspaper by about $ 165 per week over the next five years. In addition to the salary hike, the new contract includes improvements in guild representation for the paper's 1,420 union members, according to <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Diuguid </PERSON>, a member of the bargaining committee. The contract was tentatively approved last Friday after all-night negotiations. In addition to newsroom workers, employees in the paper's accounting, advertising, circulation and data-processing departments are covered by the agreement The contract is the first between the paper and the guild in nearly three years. The previous pact expired in 1986, and newspaper officials declared that negotiations had reached an impasse a year later. To protest the slow pace in the contract talks, many Post reporters removed their bylines from stories on the two anniversaries of the breakdown in discussions. The new contract raises salaries between 4 percent and 6 percent a year, with lower-paid workers receiving a higher percentage increase along with improvements in minimum salary scales. The average salary for Post reporters is more than $ 52,000 per year.
