arrest shortly after the crackdown. If the link between <PERSON> Bao </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> could be established, communist authorities would be able to implicate <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> directly in the student movement, the Western diplomat said. So far, the charges against <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> have been relatively vague. The former chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> was officially purged after the June 4 crackdown and accused of supporting the movement and `` counterrevolutionary turmoil.'' More recently, the state-run media have accused him being responsible for high prices and widespread corruption. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s real involvement in the student movement is unclear. His sympathy for the movement was obvious when he went to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in mid-May and, with tears in his eyes, told the students that he had come to see them too late. The movement was supported by many intellectuals like <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Yizhi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiaqi </PERSON> who worked in think-tanks tied to <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>. But it is unknown whether they were functioning under <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s orders or acting on their own. The <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> activist said he looked on <PERSON> Chen </PERSON>'s escape as a major victory against the current crackdown on the movement. Thousands of students and other participants in the campaign for freedom have been arrested since the repression began in early June. The official media, which started out reporting every major new arrest with headlines, have stopped highlighting such activity. The apparent arrest of student leader <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> received no mention in the Chinese press.
