<HEAD>Piedmont Jet Lands Safely After Landing Gear Jams</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd to UPDATE with NTSB investigator saying
he doesn't know when chock was left in landing gear, other details. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, `Passengers praised...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos GBO2, XASB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM FOREMAN Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet dragged its left wing and engine down a runway during an emergency landing Wednesday after part of its landing gear jammed, but none of the 100 people aboard was injured. `` I've had worse landings on regular flights,'' said passenger <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudd </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. The left landing gear could not be lowered because of a wheel chock that had lodged in the landing gear bay, said <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> investigator <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>. He said he did not know how or when the rubber chock, which is used to hold planes in place on the ground, might have been wedged there. A <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokesman said wheel chocks are supposed to be left on the ground. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reported that investigators believe mechanics at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> might have accidentally left the chock in the plane's landing gear well. Passengers praised the crew and the pilot, whom <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> refused to identify. `` It was kind of like a roller-coaster, kind of fun,'' said Army Sgt. <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> McDorman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>. She said the passengers were calm and the landing `` was just as smooth as if he was on wheels. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-400 carried 94 passengers and six crew, including the pilot, said <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON>. Piedmont took delivery of the jetliner in December 1988 and has had no problems with it or with the 737-400 fleet in general, <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said. The plane was bound for <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, but was diverted to <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> has a maintenance hangar, after a cockpit light showed the landing gear was n't locked, <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said. The pilot `` circled for better than an hour in an attempt to get all the gear down,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>. The pilot got the nose wheel and right landing gear down, but not the left gear, <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. During maneuvers to shake loose the landing gear and use up fuel, the jetliner did a touch-and-go on one wheel _ contacting the runway before immediately taking off again. Finally, the plane was eased down to the ground near the beginning of the 10,000-foot runway. After the right main landing gear touched down, the left wing tilted slowly toward the ground, tapping it twice before the wing and its engine assembly dragged the runway. Emergency vehicles lined the runway after the airport was closed to other traffic. There was a brief flash of flame and smoke, apparently from a tire, and the plane slid in a straight line, coming to rest about a third of the way down the runway. Passengers slid down emergency chutes. Emergency crews sprayed foam on the wing and engine. <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said she was moved from her seat, which was located on an emergency exit so that someone stronger could handle the door once the plane landed. `` They had prepared us with this brace procedure,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said, crossing her arms over her head to demonstrate the instructions. `` I braced and braced.'' Some passengers were still shaking and soaked in sweat after they were bused to the terminal from the runway. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Roscoe </PERSON>, also of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, had but one comment when he emerged from the plane: `` Thank God.'' He said the pilot `` did a very beautiful job.'' `` I went to the pilot when we got off'' and flashed him a thumbs-up sign, said passenger <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kochan </PERSON> said the pilot looked at him, then pointed to the sky. `` I think the crew deserves a tremendous amount of praise,'' said <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. `` It shows a tremendous amount of professionalism.'' She said the pilot had flown 20 years for <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, which delivered the plane to <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> on Nov. 14, 1988, will not send a crash investigation team, said spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. On Saturday, the <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> name will disappear and all planes will bear <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> markings. <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> have been subsidiaries of <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> for two years.
