<HEAD>House Defeats Abortion Restrictions in Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS new 5th graf, The House, with vote on final passage expected
Thursday; ADDS three grafs after 13th graf pvs ``This is, with Dornan comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An emotionally divided <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday rejected an effort to tighten abortion restrictions in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, the first congressional test on the subject since a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling last month permitting states to impose new limits. On a surprising 219-206 vote that evoked hugs and hoots of cheer on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor by supporters of the right to abortion, the lawmakers rejected a proposal that would have banned all government spending on abortions in the capital. The vote was a reversal of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sentiment last year, when the legislators voted 222-186 to ban public spending on the procedures. Abortion activists said it was the first time since 1980 the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had refused to restrict government spending for abortion. The defeated provision, an amendment to a spending bill for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 that forms <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s municipal budget, was proposed by Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>. The prohibition would have included cases in which the mother's life is in danger or pregnancies resulting from rape or incest. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> recessed for the day and left the vote on final passage of the overall bill for Thursday. That left anti-abortion lawmakers one more chance to find votes and try to salvage their proposal, perhaps by defeating the entire spending measure. Defeat of the amendment left intact abortion provisions in the bill which are more liberal than current law. The bill would allow the district to spend its own funds for abortions and to use federal funds if the pregnancy was the result of rape or incest or if the mother's life was in danger. Current law, which expires Sept. 30, contains a ban on spending either federal or district funds unless the mother's life is threatened. Quoting the hospitalized Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., one of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s foremost abortion opponents, <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> said, `` This is not government intervention The government's first duty is to protect the weak from the strong.'' <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> and his supporters said they preferred to include an exception for mothers whose lives are threatened, but did not because it would have left their amendment vulnerable to being struck down for procedural reasons. Opponents to <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON>'s language warned that the roll call would supply a hit list of lawmakers for voters who support the freedom to choose abortions. `` All across the country, a newly energized pro-choice movement is going to say to supporters of amendments like this, ` If you are anti-choice, when we the voters go to the ballot box, we wo n't choose you,''' Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON>, D-Ore., said before the Jubilant pro-choice lawmakers readily conceded that they had not expected to win, but attributed the surprise victory to a new alarm among voters triggered by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s recent decision restricting women's constitutional right to abortion. After the vote, <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON> said: `` It was clear to members that this is an issue on which they're going to be held accountable. This vote was a dramatic turn, and it clearly reflects what's happening in the country. It's a sea change.'' The court's decision `` was really a wake-up call'' to abortion defenders, said Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, D-Colo. House members `` must be starting to hear from people back home. `` This is a barometer,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON>, D-Calif. `` The winds are blowing, and they're blowing in our direction. <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> blamed his defeat on the new attention the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling has brought to abortion, the election of several freshmen who favor liberalized abortion laws, and a reluctance by some lawmakers to vote for a measure containing no exception for endangered mothers. He noted that earlier Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had overwhelmingly approved a separate spending bill that barred the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> from providing any funds for abortions, except for instances when the woman's life is at stake. `` I'm not worried about losing anything else,'' he said. <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Smeal </PERSON>, president of the Fund for the <ORGANIZATION> Feminist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Majority </ORGANIZATION> and a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>, was elated. `` We're on a roll. Thirty-three votes switched since 1980. ... We've marched in the streets, surged in the polls and challenged both parties,'' Ms. <PERSON> Smeal </PERSON> said. On July 3, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> gave states greater powers to restrict abortions, allowing them to ban public employees or facilities from participating in abortions, even when patients are willing to pay for them.
