in their release. _ Voted 53-44 against a plan to spend $ 100 million for the effective deployment of 100 ground-based interceptor missiles in <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forks </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, by 1995 The interceptors, part of the Accidental Launch Protection System, would have been used against sudden terrorist missile attacks. _ Approved a series of `` burden-sharing'' amendments aimed at increasing the contributions to defense by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> _ Declined to vote on a proposal to restore former Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s $ 23,000 pension North has been convicted on three felony counts in the Iran-Contra affair, and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ordered its <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to hold hearings on the subject of his pension. The defense bill legislation contains $ 200 million for anti-satellite weapons in addition to unspecified amounts in the Star Wars budget. Sens. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, R-Vt., had proposed restrictions to bar such tests unless the administration could certify that the Soviets had engaged in tests of their own, had refused to bargain in good faith in limitations and had blocked international verification The efforts to block attempts to chip away at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s defense package were evident earlier this morning when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> avoided a vote on an amendment transferring $ 450 million from the administration's $ 4.9 billion request for the Star Wars anti-missile shield to the war on drugs. Instead, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved a compromise drafted by Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZA