<HEAD>Opposition Leader Detained For Questioning on Lawmaker's Trip North</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 graf to UPDATE with Kim released, says he's not
involved; picks up 4th pvs, `Government officials...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security agents detained opposition leader <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dae-jung </PERSON> on Wednesday and released him 22 hours later after questioning on whether he was involved in a lawmaker's secret trip to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Following his release Thursday, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> told a news conference that he was cleared of any suspicion. Clashes occurred Wednesday near the police station where he was held when about 100 <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> supporters were stopped by hundreds of riot police. Two of the protesters were injured. Investigators from the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> had questioned <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, and lawmaker <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> <PERSON> Dong-hwan </PERSON> after taking him from his party headquarters to the downtown police station. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> was also released, but there were no reports he spoke about his investigation. Government officials said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> was investigated to determine whether he was involved in an unauthorized trip to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Suh </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyung-won </PERSON>, a former party lawmaker jailed on charges of espionage and security violations. The government prohibits any unofficial contacts with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, who ran twice for the presidency, has denied any involvement in <PERSON> Suh </PERSON>'s trip and charged the government with political harassment. <PERSON> Suh </PERSON> was expelled from the party after his June 28 arrest on charges of espionage for al