<HEAD>Court Rules Rented Houses Can Be Destroyed, 13 Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled Wednesday that the army can destroy the homes of Palestinians suspected of anti-Israeli activities even if they are rented. The decision followed by just four days a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that said the army must give Palestinians an opportunity to appeal before destroying their homes. In the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, 13 Palestinians were shot and wounded in stone-throwing clashes with troops, hospitals reported. A Palestinian prisoner, <PERSON> Jihad </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Imadi </PERSON>, was seriously beaten by fellow inmates at <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Ketziot </LOCATION> detention center in the southern <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> desert, the army said. It said it was investigating the circumstances of the incident. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling came in response to a case brought by an Arab landlord in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Tulkarem </LOCATION>, the independent <ORGANIZATION> Itim </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. The landlord, <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumail </PERSON>, said he rented an apartment to <PERSON> Mustafa </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON>, who has been charged with throwing Molotov cocktails at an army vehicle and at the house of a Palestinian suspected of collaborating with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jumail </PERSON> said that even though he had no connection with <PERSON> Omar </PERSON>'s alleged activities, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had ordered his property destroyed <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamgar </PERSON>, the court president, ruled that if sanctions could not be taken against rental property, it would `` negate all the deterrent power that comes from the usage of the emergency defense regulations,'' <ORGANIZATION> Itim </ORGANIZATION> said. He said, however, that <PERSON> Jumail </PERSON>'s property should be sealed and not destroyed. Israeli forces have blown up or torn down at least 225 houses in the occupied territories since the start of the Palestinian uprising against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> rule 19 months ago. At least 527 Palestinians and 38 Israelis have died in the uprising. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and international human rights groups have called for an end to the practice, saying that it is carried out without due process of the law. In many cases, property is destroyed before the suspect is either charged or tried.
