<SECOND>AM-Lake Derail,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fuel Spill Hits Beaches; Governor Demands Railroad Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB ANEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITEFISH, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Diesel fuel spilled into <LOCATION> Whitefish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> by a train derailment began washing up on beaches and shores near this resort community Wednesday and residents complained that the cleanup effort was halfhearted. Gov. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> toured the site by helicopter and said <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> Northern Railroad would be held accountable for `` anything that's been adversely impacted that has a cost to it,'' as well as all cleanup costs. BN Vice President <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> said the railroad would pay all costs `` legally that we need to.'' BN continued to pump diesel oil remaining in tanker cars that landed in the lake, but said all leaks had been plugged by divers and no more oil was spilling. The railroad estimated 10,000 gallons had spilled since Monday's derailment. Twenty-nine cars of a 100-car train derailed Monday four miles north of <LOCATION> Whitefish </LOCATION> in northwestern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, and several cars, including the fuel-carrying tankers, went down a 100-foot embankment into <LOCATION> Whitefish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>. No injuries were reported. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> estimated the cost of the derailment alone at $ 557,000, but said he has no estimate on cleanup costs. A helicopter survey Wednesday revealed that about half the 3,350-acre lake was covered with the telltale rainbow sheen of a thin oil slick, and oil began washing ashore on the populated southern and eastern banks. `` It's awful,'' said <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Olafson </PERSON>, who lives on the eastern shore. `` We've been mopping all morning and the winds changed and now it's just come back in again.'' <PERSON> Olafson </PERSON> complained that there had been too little response to the spill. `` The way they react is just wrong,'' <PERSON> Olafson </PERSON> said. `` They're always looking for the cheap way out, and it ends up being more expensive. The governor said he was `` deeply saddened'' by the sight, noting he and his family have vacationed at the lake for years. The tank cars should be pulled out of the water sometime Thursday, said <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Melonas </PERSON>, BN's <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> spokesman. The derailment closed BN's main line from <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, forcing freight trains to be rerouted south, and <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> had to bus passengers from its Empire Builder train around the derailment area.
