<HEAD>Congressman Questions U.S. Travel Advisories In Wake Of Kenya Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressman Wednesday questioned how the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issues travel advisories, saying a warning should have been posted for <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> before a <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> woman became the latest tourist killed in a recent string of ambushes. `` While the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> did respond the following day by placing <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> on the travel advisory list, I must seriously question why this action was not taken earlier,'' Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., said in a letter to Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> Three German tourists were wounded in an ambush in April, two French tourists were killed by ivory poachers in early July and two Americans were beaten while riding horseback last week, <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> said. `` It is my understanding that incidents such as the above weigh heaviest in any decision to place a nation on the travel advisory list,'' the congressman said. `` American citizens deserve to be informed of any dangers they face as international travelers.'' An advisory for <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> was not issued until after <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferraro </PERSON>, 50, of <LOCATION> Bethany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, was shot to death last Thursday by two bandits armed with assault rifles who fired at a van carrying a <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> wildlife tour group. `` My saddness and concern stem from this tragic loss of life and the possibility that proper risk notification was not given,'' <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> said. The congressman requested a detailed explanation of the decision-making process for travel advisories and urged an `` in-depth review'' by the department of its procedures. A spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> referred to a March press release that read in part, `` Travel advisories which describe a potential for violence and physical danger usually reflect a trend or pattern of violence over a period of time in which the government of the country involved is unwilling or unable to afford normal protection.''
