<HEAD>Student Expelled for Leading University Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chinese student who helped stage a demonstration at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> last month has been expelled and refused his diploma, university officials said. A public announcement, posted on bulletin boards once festooned with the posters of the student-led pro-democracy movement, said <PERSON> Xiong </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayong </PERSON>, 22, had broken martial law regulations banning unauthorized gatherings. The notice, dated July 25, said <PERSON> Xiong </PERSON>, a fourth-year student of Chinese and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, had `` incited other students to cause trouble by breaking martial law restrictions.'' It also accused <PERSON> Xiong </PERSON> of being a `` known criminal'' who had stolen three bicycles this summer and caused a drunken brawl last year. With no diploma and an expulsion on his record, <PERSON> Xiong </PERSON> will have difficulty finding work. On July 23, from 300 to 400 students sang and beat pots and pans to mourn classmates killed June 3-4 when troops opened fire on student protesters and supporters. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has said 200-300 people died in the military assault, but Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death toll may have been as high as 3,000. The students said they held the July 23 demonstration because they felt oppressed by the ideological study classes they were forced to attend following the military crackdown. They were also protesting because some of them were refused permission to join the work units to which they were earlier assigned. Most college graduates in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are assigned jobs by the government. Most of the 32,000 graduates from 80 universities and colleges in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> this year have been accepted by their assigned units, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported Wednesday. The report said more than 1,000 graduates, however, had not found appropriate jobs, in part because some foreign companies, party schools, judicial departments, travel agencies and the military had dropped plans to accept more than 300 students. The report did not say whether the refusals were due to political considerations arising from participation in the pro-democracy demonstrations this spring, which were initiated and led by students from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> universities. It quoted <PERSON> Han </PERSON> <PERSON> Xueping </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Higher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, as saying that all graduates in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> had undergone three weeks of political study to review their thought and actions during the student protests.
