<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> started proceedings Wednesday to strip a former <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> of his citizenship because he failed to disclose that he was a Nazi concentration camp guard. A complaint was filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> against <PERSON> Jakob </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Denzinger </PERSON>, who became a naturalized citizen in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION> in 1972. <PERSON> Denzinger </PERSON>, 65, is believed to have left the country, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in a prepared statement. The government alleged that <PERSON> Denzinger </PERSON> guarded prisoners at slave labor sites, manned watchtowers and `` assisted in the persecution of those interned.'' According to the complaint, <PERSON> Denzinger </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, entered the Waffen SS in 1941 and was an armed guard at several concentration camps, including the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> death camp. To date, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship has been revoked from 30 World War II-era criminals, including 27 who have been deported, said the Office of Special Investigations, which builds the cases against suspected Nazi persecutors.
