<UNK>Moldavians Protest Stalin-Hitler Pact</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people gathered in <LOCATION> Kishinev </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moldavia </LOCATION>, Wednesday to condemn the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> annexation of their homeland in a secret pact between <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, an activist said. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Rozhgo </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Kishinev </LOCATION> that demonstrators demanded that the Soviet government declare the August 1939 pact to be null. A <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> legislative commission is thought to be within days of declaring void the agreement that divided Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> before World War II into Soviet and German spheres of influence. The <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> had denied for years that any such pact existed. Activists in the Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> have pushed for such a decision for more than two years. <PERSON> Rozhgo </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Moldavia </LOCATION> also came under Soviet control because of the pact. <PERSON> Rozhgo </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Moldavian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, said that between 2,000 and 3,000 people gathered in central <LOCATION> Kishinev </LOCATION> to mark Wednesday's 49th anniversary of the Moldavian Soviet republic. Soviet soldiers occupied the small republic bordering <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on June 28, 1940. <PERSON> Rozhgo </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> was told that members of <LOCATION> Vatra </LOCATION>, a group promoting Moldavian culture, were beaten by police when they tried to gather in <LOCATION> Bendery </LOCATION>, southeast of <LOCATION> Kishinev </LOCATION>. Demonstrations have swept the republic this year as ethnic Moldavians, who are closely related to Romanians, demand restoration of the Latin alphabet and their native language. The language was converted to Russian letters after the Soviet takeover. The republic's Supreme Soviet, or legislature, is to meet Aug. 28 to consider a law that would make Moldavian the official language.
