<FIRST>u w AM-DroughtRelief     08-02 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Relief,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Legislation to Aid Drought-Stricken Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a disaster assistance bill Wednesday to send $ 885 million in relief to farmers hit by drought and severe weather. The bill would make farmers eligible for federal aid if they have crop losses this year because of drought, flooding, freezing, hail, high winds or similar severe weather. The measure also provides for payments to livestock producers facing drought-related feed and water shortages for their herds. But the pricetag on the bill passed by voice vote in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is about $ 463 million less than the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has estimated would be the cost of a packaged approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill provides for different eligibility standards for various crops, but in all cases producers would receive payments designed to cover 65 percent of their lost income from crop losses. In most cases, the projected income levels will be based on federal crop subsidies or average market prices farmers would have received had they not suffered losses. `` The most important thing about this bill is that all farmers are being treated fairly,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` Those who suffer a significant loss will receive the same payment rate _ 65 percent of the applicable target price or loan rate.'' `` We will not discriminate against any farmer who needs help,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said. `` This legislation treats farmers fairly, whether they grow wheat, corn, hay or soybeans.'' Wheat and other crops have been damaged by the lingering drought across much of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and flooding has destroyed rice and cotton in the South. Senate Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., said winter wheat producers and other growers will be eligible for high-priority attention under provisions of the legislation `` This is not the best bill, nor is it the kind of relief winter wheat producers and other program crops deserve,'' he said. `` But it is far better than the budget-busting <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill which promised federal relief to every crop in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The House disaster relief bill required a minimum loss of 35 percent for any crop to receive assistance, with payments covering 65 percent of lost income. But unlike the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> measure called for 90 percent payments on crop losses of more than 75 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> dropped the higher payment level as a way of cutting the overall cost of the assistance package. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> also passed by voice vote rural development legislation designed to promote business investment and expansion in small towns. It also is aimed at improving schools and health care for residents. Proponents had said federal assistance was needed because the 61 million people living in rural areas face higher unemployment, more hospital closings and higher poverty levels than their urban counterparts. The rural economy also is more volatile because of its dependence on natural resources, supporters contended. The centerpiece of the package, called the `` rural partnership act,'' is a revolving loan fund program to provide $ 300 million in seed money over five years for new and expanding businesses. The federal money, which must be matched by money from local sources, would go for loans and loan guarantees to create new jobs. The revolving loan funds would be operated by states, local governor or economic development groupst to ensure local control of the lending, according to supportrs.
