<HEAD>Two Killed in Battle near San Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas based on <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Volcano </LOCATION> attacked an army post on the edge of the capital Tuesday night and at least one soldier and a civilian were killed in the fighting. Another soldier and two civilians were wounded in the battle that lasted two hours and kept many of the residents of the city's northwestern sector inside buildings or huddled behind walls or vehicles <PERSON> Gunsmoke </PERSON> settled over the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ramon </LOCATION> neighborhood where the fighting was heaviest. It was the fifth time in eight months that the army post in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ramon </LOCATION> has been attacked. An estimated 200 rebels are based on the volcano and its foothills nearly reach <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s city limits. Sgt. <PERSON> Ventura </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, who was in command of the detachment of 10 soldiers at the post, estimated the number of attackers at 60. He said the guerrillas threw packets of <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION> at the post. One explosion ripped a hole in the roof of the single-story cinderblock building that serves as post headquarters. Nearly 100 soldiers from the <PERSON> Belloso </PERSON> army brigade reinforced the post's unit about 20 minutes after the fighting began at dusk. Thousands of rounds from assault rifles and machine guns and sporadic detonations of rocket-propelled grenades and TNT bombs kept residents pinned down. `` All I want to do is get home,'' sobbed <PERSON> Leticia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, laying face down in a trench next to a reporter while bullets whizzed overhead. A helicopter circled at about 3,000 feet above the battle. Its gunner fired bursts of tracer rounds from time to time, though the action was beyond effective range of his M-60 machine gun. Leftist rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> have fought the U.S.-backed government for nearly 10 years. Attacks on military posts in and near the capital have increased during the past 10 months after three years in which <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> was almost free of combat. During the 10 months the rebels acquired hundreds of Soviet-designed Dragunov sniper rifles and an estimated 2,000 AK-47 assault rifles to augment their arsenal. The Dragunovs have an effective range of about 2,650 feet and have been used to damage several helicopters. The rifles have forced air force pilots to fly higher nd abandon more missions than at any time during the war.
