<HEAD>Fate of Possible Chinese Defectors Unknown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The opera ...' to CORRECT date opera company
flew back to Thursday, sted Sunday. </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight Chinese performers have been missing for a week since they left a group returning to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but immigration officials said Tuesday no one had contacted them on behalf of the entertainers. `` All I can tell you is they have n't walked into this office and applied for any relief,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ilchert </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Four other <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> citizens have chosen to defect in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> since the June 4 crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. If the eight entertainers who fled the <LOCATION> Kun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> company last week seek political asylum in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it would be the largest single defection of Chinese citizens since the 1950s. `` Everybody in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> wants to leave, so whoever has a chance to go out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, they will try to stay there,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Shia </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Kiangsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chekiang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit association that helps <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> immigrants. The performers left the 28-member opera over a two-day period last week while the company was in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> en route to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> following a series of performances in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We have had zero contact with them or with the consulate,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Latting </PERSON>. `` We would like to talk to them. We always want any defector to know that we are a wonderful umbrella for them. We can help them get to us or any other agency.'' The opera company flew back to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> on Thursday, according to Officer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>, coordinator of VIP travel at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. A spokesman for the Chinese consulate confirmed the eight performers did not leave with the company. `` They were influenced by people with ulterior motives,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaohua </PERSON>. Officals of the Chinese consulate in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> have blamed the disappearance on `` people with motives to bring damage to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' The missing entertainers include <PERSON> Hua </PERSON> <PERSON> Wen-Yi </PERSON>, a famous opera singer in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. Two other singers in the group, <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong-Shen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Zhan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ping-Ping </PERSON>, also are well known in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zhan </PERSON> is a famous television and film star as well as an opera performer. The others were identified as <PERSON> Qui </PERSON> <PERSON> Huan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi-Ping </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ma </PERSON> <PERSON> Xin-Bao </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chong </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Sei-Long </PERSON>. `` I think at this moment they fear making a wrong move _ whether they should seek political asylum or use other reasons to remain here,'' said Shia. `` I think they are going to wait until this incident is cooled off and then decide what options they should take,'' he said. Although accounts of the disappearances differ, Shia, who spoke with several opera members last Wednesday, gave this description: Two members left during a farewell dinner on July 25, two others left that evening, three group leaders early the next day, Wednesday, and one performer left Wednesday morning. <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wu </PERSON>, an attorney who specializes in immigration and who has represented defectors, said the performers have numerous legal options. Because they arrived in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> June 5, they are eligible for the emergency `` deferred departure status'' announced by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration in June. The policy offers a one-year blanket visa extension to all <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> citizens who were in the country on or before June 5. Alternatively, political asylum is `` tough for people to get who have n't really expressed any opinions'' against the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government, <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shia </PERSON> said if the performers were involved in the pro-democracy movement in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, they would not have been allowed to leave. Other options to remain in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> include permanent labor certification, temporary work authorization or permanent residency if a relative successfully petitions on behalf of a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> citizen.
