<FIRST>a i PM-Nepal'sChallenge Adv08   08-02 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nepal's Challenge, Adv 08,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs Aug. 8 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Already Poor, Nepal Tightens Belt After Trade Dispute with India</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Arguing with a big neighbor can be costly, as <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> is discovering four months after losing the first round of a trade dispute with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Already one of the world's poorest countries, landlocked and mountainous <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> faces difficult times unless it can come to terms with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> on transporting its exports and imports across <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> at previously favored rates. As a result of the dispute, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s deficit budget proposed for the fiscal year that started July 1 calls for expenditures to rise by 32 percent, compared to 8 percent the previous fiscal year. Gasoline prices have been raised by 48 percent. That reflects a threefold vulnerability of the Nepalese economy: steeper transit costs across <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the declining value of the Nepalese rupee, and fluctuating crude oil prices in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Nepalese optimists say the trade and transit crisis with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> will force <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> to develop its own infrastructure and become less reliant on others' largesse. Pessimists say any such period of adjustment will take several years and further sap the resources of the country. Although the Nepalese-Indian dispute was sparked by treaty terms on bilateral trade and <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s access to Indian transit facilities for third-country trade, many observers in the region see a deeper _ and to some a more sinister _ reason. They describe it as <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s growing power and ambitions as a major military, political and economic force in the region <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> rejects such contentions. <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s strength is in its majestic mountains and mystique that attract the tourists who provide about 20 percent of the country's foreign exchange earnings Another 20 percent comes from the export of carpets, a business dominated by Tibetan refugees who fled Chinese rule in their homeland across the border. Its chief weakness is poverty. <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s per capita annual income is $ 150. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund record only two other countries with equal or worse economic misery: <LOCATION> Bhutan </LOCATION>, where the per capita income also is $ 150, and <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, where it is $ 120. `` <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> can not remain an island of poverty any longer between the two countries in the region that are growing _ <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shailendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> <PERSON> Upadhyaya </PERSON> said in an interview. `` <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> also has to grow.'' Growth, he added, includes expanding ties beyond <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, with a population of 880 million, and <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, with 17 million people, had `` a special relationship'' between 1950 when the mountain kingdom emerged from hermit-like isolation and last March 23, when their trade and transit treaties lapsed. <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, seeking to lessen dependence on its big neighbor, has been steadily diversifying its trading partners over the past 15 years. But to import goods, it relied on preferential rights to use <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s seaports, railroads and highways. This year, <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> wanted to renew the two separate trade and transit treaties. But <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> insisted on a single treaty linking the two issues, saying it was unfair for <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> to expect generous transit privileges to import goods from other nations which often, as Foreign Minister <PERSON> Upadhyaya </PERSON> and other Nepalese officials acknowledged, end up getting smuggled back to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and sold at a profit. In 1975, 82 percent of <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s foreign trade was with <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. By April 1989, it had shrunk to 28 percent, according the fiscal 1988-89 economic survey issued in July by <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Birendra </PERSON>'s government The proposed 1989-90 budget, released at the same time, calls for expenditures of about $ 736 million, with a deficit of $ 81.8 million to be financed primarily by foreign and domestic borrowing. One of the biggest increases is in petroleum products, which <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> has started purchasing on the international market instead of buying from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, itself a net importer of oil. Petroleum and other Nepalese imports still pass through <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> closed 13 of the 15 authorized border transit points when the March treaties lapsed and hassles at the two remaining points still crop up periodically. For the Nepalese consumer, this has resulted in rationing and skyrocketing prices, although the gasoline shortage of last spring and early summer is starting to ease. Most Nepalese do n't have cars, but those who do are now paying the equivalen of $ 3.18 a gallon instead of $ 2.18 a gallon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Aug. 4</NOTE>
