<FIRST>a i PM-SovietTourists Adv11   08-02 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Tourists, Adv 11,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs Aug. 11 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Tourists in Israel Trade Caviar for Computers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet tourists, starved for consumer goods back home, are trading caviar for computers and using borrowed rubles to buy video cassette recorders. `` This video will pay for the trip,'' said <PERSON> Natalya </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> housewife in her 40s, clutching a VCR at Ben-Gurion International Airport. `` Everybody is buying videos. I wanted to bring another one for my son, but I did not have the money.'' As a result of a thaw in Soviet relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, thousands of Soviet Jews have been visiting relatives and friends in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. En route many stop in <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, to purchase electronic goods that can be resold in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> where a VCR can fetch the equivalent of 10 months' salary _ about 2,000 rubles, $ 3,140 at the official rate of exchange. <PERSON> Natalya </PERSON> and other travelers demanded anonymity because they feared reprisals for engaging in black market transactions. One recent flight from <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> carried 60 Soviet tourists with 26 VCRs and two double-deck radio-cassette players. One Georgian family was seen pushing a cart with three VCRs. The tourists are required to leave the VCRs and other goods at the airport to be picked up when they leave <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Some Soviet visitors, who include musicians and artists of Soviet touring groups, bring luxury items like caviar that are scarce in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to trade for personal computers and other electronic equipment. `` My refrigerator was packed with caviar tins,'' said <PERSON> Shmuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Weismel </PERSON>, an Israeli computer programmer in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> who recently hosted a Soviet theater troupe. He said the Soviets brought French perfume and caviar purchased on the black market back home and sold them here for several times the price. They then bought personal computers, which cost $ 2,000 to $ 4,000 in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. An additional $ 7,850 must be paid in customs taxes when they arrive back home. But once in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, a computer can be sold to a factory or a state-owned business for the equivalent of $ 78,500 to $ 110,000. Other Soviet visitors select one of a half-dozen Israeli firms offering a different way to buy electronics. `` We offer a transit deal,'' said <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterenhal </PERSON> of Tal-Hen & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Khanan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> in the Israeli coastal town of <LOCATION> Netanya </LOCATION>. `` Soviet tourists order tax-free products, which are delivered by our European branch directly to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' The firm, which advertizes in some of the seven Russian-language newspapers published in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, offers Soviet Jews radios, tape cassette players, VCRs, televisiion sets and personal computers. Attendants said not a day passes without a Soviet coming into the store `` to buy something, at least a radio.'' But the Soviet tourists also buy other things in short supply at home. <PERSON> Sonia </PERSON>, a retired biochemist from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, bought a $ 7.50 baroque freshwater-pearl necklace as a present for her daughter. `` In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, its costs 200 rubles -LRB- $ 314 -RRB-,'' or about an average month's salary, she said. While the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> does not allow the use of hard currency to import luxury items, it tolerates private imports. `` There is a tremendous demand for all kinds of goods that the government ca n't supply,'' said <PERSON> Galia </PERSON> <PERSON> Golan </PERSON>, a Soviet specialist at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. `` So they have always permitted the black market and the second economy to continue.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Aug. 11</NOTE>
