<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:AtlantaTransit Adv07   08-02 1027</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Atlanta Transit, Adv 07,1048</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Mon PMs, Aug. 7, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>After 10 Years, System Still Resisted in Some White Suburbs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note that 7th graf, `Atlantans may...' may offend some readers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten years after gleaming silver trains started rolling along the South's first rapid-transit system, a 1,582-mile network of 150 bus routes and two rail lines with 29 stations carries a quarter-million passengers a day. The <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> has been hailed for its safety and cleanliness. <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION> celebrated its trains' 10th birthday with a free-ride day on July 4 that drew a record 435,000 passengers. A revitalized Underground <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> draws up to 100,000 extra passengers a week, many of them first-time riders. But <PERSON> MARTA </PERSON> has a problem: It increasingly goes where much of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> is n't. When <PERSON> MARTA </PERSON> was launched in 1971, the three suburban counties that refused it _ Cobb to the northwest, <PERSON> Gwinnett </PERSON> to the northeast and <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> to the south _ were largely rural, and it was hard to imagine subway cars rolling past farms and forests. Those three counties now hold nearly 900,000 people, three-fourths the number in the two central counties, <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> and DeKalb, where <PERSON> MARTA </PERSON> runs. Despite suburban traffic that is getting worse and suburban jobs that go begging because car-less workers ca n't reach them, opposition to expanding the system remains. Joining would almost surely mean higher taxes, and suburban politicians have been loathe to submit to decision-makers in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. But the chief reason given by many opponents is the fear <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION> will bring crime to their tranquil neighborhoods. That feeling is widely seen as racism. <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION>'s passengers reflect central <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, which is predominantly black. Atlantans may not like to discuss it, but few have n't heard the acronym explained as: `` Moving Africans Rapidly Through <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>.'' `` The people you hear opposing <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> and Gwinnett ... they've been pretty open about it. They do n't want black people coming into their areas,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, a civil rights leader and a member of <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION>'s board since 1975. `` It's blind prejudice and fear. `` We feel its in everyone's interest to have a regional transit agency providing all the service,'' said General Manager <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON>. `` It makes sense, it's much more cost-effective, unencumbered by the problems of numerous political jurisdictions. I think that position ultimately will prevail.'' `` I think <PERSON> MARTA </PERSON>'s future is contingent on that,'' said <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>. `` Its maximum potential will never be realized until we go north to <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION> and south to <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>. ... We at least need five counties.'' End-of-the-line stops on <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION>'s cross-shaped rail system do a booming business as thousands of <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION> residents drive across the county line and hop on the train. Some luxury hotels in <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> have even sent vans to ferry workers across the <LOCATION> Chattahoochee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which marks the county line. But MARTA trains and buses are n't going to cross that bridge anytime soon. `` They're pretty much against it, at least in my end of the county,'' said <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> McGill </PERSON>. `` A number of the people who have moved into the south end are transplants from <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, and a lot of them feel like <PERSON> MARTA </PERSON> ran them out of town.'' `` Without being obvious, people say that ease of transportation would bring in ` the undesirables' and crime,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Gwinnett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, who has advocated at least a trial run of <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION> buses. Even talking about <PERSON> MARTA </PERSON> can be tricky in the suburbs. A discussion group with <ORGANIZATION> Cobb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> leaders in 1980 had a `` code name so folks would n't know about it,'' <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON> said. But more and more, suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> may be coming to the conclusion that something must be done. A one-mile trip down a major thoroughfare in <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> or Gwinnett can take more than a half-hour, and residents of those counties named traffic as their No. 1 problem in a recent <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Journal-Constitution poll. The poll found between 54 percent and 60 percent of <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> county residents favored MARTA trains in their communities, although only in <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> were a majority willing to pay the 1 percent sales tax that <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> residents pay for <PERSON> MARTA </PERSON>. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> last month launched its own five-route bus system. Ten thousand people used it the first week, more than twice the volume expected for the first three weeks, forcing officials to drop a radio advertising campaign for fear they would n't be able to meet the demand. The busiest <ORGANIZATION> Cobb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> route is one dropping commuters at a midtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> MARTA subway station. Ultimately, the service plans 10 routes, including three more <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> express runs. Riders get free transfers to <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION> under a deal that allows <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION> riders to hop on <LOCATION> Cobb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s buses. The system, costing the county an estimated $ 2 million a year, makes more sense than giving <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION> an estimated $ 65 million a year in local sales taxes, said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Aronoff </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> CCT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. `` It does n't look like it would make sense to provide more than we provide. ... <ORGANIZATION> MARTA </ORGANIZATION>'s the best system in the country, but it does n't have all the answers.'' `` In my judgment, they're fooling themselves,'' <PERSON> Gregor </PERSON> said. `` Ten bus routes are n't going to even dent, are n't going to put an infinitesimal impact, on their traffic congestion. And starting a bus system that brings four routes in the city of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> ai n't going to do it. <LOCATION> Clayton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> has no public transportation. Gwinnett, which has none either, will vote next year on some sort of mass transit referendum. Mrs. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> hopes it will once and for all answer questions like what the county wants and will pay for. `` I hope they'll use reason and understanding, rather than ... illogical rationale,'' she said, pointing out that the county's 330,000 population will more than double in the next 20 years `` The sheer mathematics of it says we have got to come up with some method of handling all those people. `` It's inevitable. It's time to fish or cut bait.''
</TEXT>
