<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv03   08-02 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 03,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Aug. 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Statistical Sleight of Hand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It takes a mighty aggregation of man, machine and fossil - fuel power to move the gross national product a fraction of a point, but in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> it can be done by researchers using only calculator power They do it again and again, month after month, revising important economic measurements, some of which might have been, when first announced, the basis for decisions regarding business and economic policy. Revisions are a regular occurrence in statistics, produced mainly by access to additional information or changes in methodology. In some instances they are expected; in some, they are not. In either event, they can dismay. Several years ago, for example, rising retail sales were reported month after month, giving the impression of a boom. But, when viewed after a year, sales had risen only moderately. The reason: The monthly increases were based not on original figures but on later revisions. Repeatedly, those revisions were downward, meaning increases for the following months were from a base lower than originally stated. Some important revisions recently were made in estimates of gross national product, perhaps the broadest of all economic measurements and one that often guides the direction of fiscal and monetary policy. This revision raised the growth of real GNP for 1987 to 3.7 percent from 3.4 percent, a difference of $ 6.7 billion, and for 1988 to 4.4 percent from 3.9 percent, a difference of $ 28.3 billion. Those are n't puny numbers, even in an economy where the value of a billion shrinks by the day. In fact, they are momentous figures when you consider that overheating vs. recession was one of the biggest economic concerns in each of those years, and that the GNP measurement was one of the primary indicators. Whatever, decisions must be made in a critical time frame too immediate to wait for revisions. Battles are fought with the weapons on hand, not with arsenals promised. Gen. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> launched an invasion of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after reading weather reports later found to be faulty. Later, President <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> steered economic policy although, in review, the economic data he relied upon was less than perfect. Statistical faults are accepted, the attitude seeming to be that nothing better is available. If poor decisions are made, so be it. If good news comes in the revision, enjoy it and hope it wo n't be revised out later. Good news did indeed come in the July revisions. For one thing, they made the trade deficit appear less ominous, in one swipe erasing more than $ 25 billion from the negative 1988 numbers. In 1988, it is now believed that the deficit, stated in 1982 dollars, was $ 74.9 billion, not $ 100.2 billion. The main reason for the revisions, it now appears, is that the `` exporting'' of education and tourism was undercounted. Well, not quite; in the language of the fraternity, each was `` enhanced,'' but the net impact is the same no matter what language is used. So big was the enhancement that one economist, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, issued a comment in a language seldom heard from economists. `` Wow,'' he said. How significant is it, he asked? Plenty, he said, explaining that the trade picture in goods and services is simply that much better, `` and the case for foreign investor panic about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imbalances is all but over.'' Economists are known to disagree, of course; not all are saying `` wow.'' Some will claim the improvement would have been more meaningful if it involved the export of pig iron rather than education. Not Barbera. `` As we see it, it is better to have state-of-the-art schools vs. state-of-the-art steel mills,'' he declares. Besides, the dollars count no matter how they are earned, or when they are added to the accounts, or even if it takes some recalculations to discover them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs., Aug. 3.</NOTE>
</DOC>
