<HEAD>Colombians Pushing Their Flowers To Counter Drug Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This land of drug cartels and violence is also the land of beautiful flowers, and those who grow them are about to launch an advertising campaign to get Americans and Canadians to buy more of them. `` We counter the violence of drugs with the beauty of our flowers as a real image representing <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> more than anything else,'' said <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Uribe </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Colombian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flowers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Years of sustained efforts to produce popular flower types _ particularly carnations and chrysanthemums, in addition to the exotic specimens native to <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> _ have earned <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> a respectable second place after the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> among flower-exporting nations. Flowers represented $ 205 million last year in export revenues, more than double the amount of 1980. Next year could be another all-time record for Colombian growers and dealers if their goal of $ 260 million in exports is met. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s 8 percent to 10 percent share of the international market over recent years, surpassing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, reflects the drive of its flourishing non-traditional export industry. All this despite all sorts of difficulties, including embarassing actions by drug traffickers who often smuggle cocaine with shipments of flowers. Last year a cargo plane of Avianca, the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> national airline, was seized in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> after the police found cocaine concealed in the soil of a flower shipment. Fined $ 3 million, <ORGANIZATION> Avianca </ORGANIZATION> halted its overseas cargo operations and Colombian florists had to look for other airlines to ship their flowers _ at much higher rates. Flower shipments now are subject to stricter controls at the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> airport in an effort to detect hidden drugs. Flowers, <PERSON> Uribe </PERSON> said, are `` innocent victims of drug traffickers.'' Flower cultivators, like any other businessmen, are constantly adapting to the mood of customers. `` Flowers are like clothes: colors and taste for them change,'' <PERSON> Uribe </PERSON> said. `` And we have to follow the customers' whims.'' Flowers began as a tiny portion of Colombian exports in the mid-1960s, when they accounted for less than $ 100,000 annually. Colombian florists feel confident that their business will be rosier if the $ 8 million advertising campaign to persuade Americans and Canadians to buy more flowers is successful. Studies by <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> florists associations indicate Americans and Canadians buy flowers mostly to give to others and rarely for themselves. `` Europeans take flowers to their homes as much as they send them as gifts,'' <PERSON> Uribe </PERSON> said. `` Our studies demonstrate that West Germans, famous for their lavish preference for flowers, buy as much as eight times more flowers than Canadians and Americans.'' Colombian floriculturists joined the 28,000-member <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transworld </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delivery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to launch the advertising campaign, which begins in September. `` The future lies in convincing Americans and Canadians to change habits and persuade them to buy flowers for themselves, too,'' <PERSON> Uribe </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Aug. 11</NOTE>
