<HEAD>$adv 07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Aug. 7, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Postal Service Edges Into World of Marketing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Move over <ORGANIZATION> Topps </ORGANIZATION> _ you have new competition. But the baseball cards being marketed by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service to promote stamp sales wo n't have the trademark piece of bubble gum inside. The post office is easing into the card business with just four of the popular collectibles as part of a push to shift from the image of a neighborhood store into a modern marketing machine. Probably the most visible effort in this change will come in September, in a joint campaign promoting postage stamps featuring dinosaurs in conjunction with <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s home video release of the movie `` The Land Before Time.'' But this is n't the first tie-in between stamps and other businesses, and it wo n't be the last, said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morison </PERSON>, assistant postmaster general for philatelic and retail services. The baseball cards, for example, take advantage of previously issued stamps honoring popular ballplayers. The stamps featuring <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Gherig </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Babe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Clemente </PERSON> have been combined in a new albumn, with four matching baseball cards included. Last year a set of stamps featuring carousel animals got special promotions at several amusement parks around the country, <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. And the agency is interested in future arrangements, perhaps for planned stamps featuring lighthouses and marine mammals. And new stamps often receive special promotions when issued, often organized by local post offices. For example the Key West, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, office prepared a special 12 - by 16-inch print of the recent Hemingway stamp in the Literary Arts series Mounted on a backing with a copy of the stamp canceled on July 17, its first day of issue, the print is being offered for $ 25, by mail order, to collectors and <LOCATION> Hemingway </LOCATION> fans. But the arrangement with <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>'s film about dinosaurs is the most ambitious effort so far in the effort to boost sales of stamps to collectors. Buyers of the home video will receive a little brochure advertising the dinosaur stamps, offering for sale a T-shirt featuring one of the stamps, and also promoting holiday seals sold by the movie company and a special deal from Pizza Hut. The dinosaur stamps should appeal to youngsters, the T-shirts and posters to both youngsters and slightly older people, <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. With the movie going on sale in September, the promotion arrives just in time for Stamp Collecting Month, which the post office celebrates in October. The purpose of the effort is simple: getting people interested in collecting stamps, a hobby that means big bucks for an agency struggling to cover its ever increasing costs while avoiding raising postage rates. Those little piles of stamps `` collected'' in envelopes and desk drawers across the nation may seem like a small investment to their owners. But to the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service, collectors represent $ 150 million to $ 170 million in sales annually, <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. And the best part is, it's virtually all profit. A postage stamp is, after all, nothing more than a receipt for advance payment for a service _ the delivery of a letter or parcel. When people collect new stamps and save them, the post office gets its quarter but does n't have to perform any service for the money. That's the kind of business most companies would love to have, and one the post office is happy to encourage. It should please non-collectors, too, since the profits from stamps sold to collectors _ philatelists is the formal term _ helps subsidize the postal service and thus lowers the costs to people who use stamps to get letters delivered somewhere. Since stamps were first issued in the mid-1800s, the postal service has enjoyed the fact that people collect stamps, occasionally seeing a boost when some collector became famous, such as President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>. But only in recent years has it studied them and sought to increase the market. Who collects stamps? Well, 75 percent of youngsters have a collection of some type, said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, manager of philatelic services at the postal service. As youngsters enter their teens they find other interests, Ms. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said, and the stamp collection usually gets put aside until later in life when they marry, have families, and often get interested in stamps again. It was the nostalgic folks returning to collecting that made last year's carousel stamps big sellers, <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. This returning group is about half `` casual'' collectors, who buy stamps they like from time to time, but do n't make a big deal out of it. One-fourth are `` accumulators'' who have some stamps, often ripping used ones off envelopes. And the rest are serious collectors, buying whole sheets of stamps, subscribing to stamp publications and following the hobby closely. The serious collectors lobby the agency for stamps, but Ms. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said officials seek to please all types of collectors. One thing they have in common is that everybody likes pretty stamps, <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said, although serious collectors lean toward more formal engravings while casual collectors seem to prefer more colorful productions. Much of the recent marketing efforts is aimed at converting casual collectors to serious ones _ explaining how to mount stamps in albums, organize them by theme and so forth. To do this <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> has instituted a quarterly series of `` stamp packs'' including a brochure and all of the colorful commemorative stamps issued over three months. Previously, sets of stamps were issued just once a year, but the stamp packs four times annually help spread out the interest, <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. In addition, the agency has subscription services for stamp collectors to make sure they get all the new stamps that come out. There are 38,000 Benjamin Franklin Stamp Clubs for youngsters around the country, encouraged by the postal service as a means of getting youngsters interested in stamp collecting. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> has branched out postal marketing in other areas, too, promoting the sale of stamps in shopping malls and supermarkets, for example. Those sales have grown to $ 500 million, and `` the public just loves it,'' he said. People find it more convenient to buy stamps in supermarkets, he explained, and this also shortens the lines at post offices, improving service for people who need help from clerks. Shopping mall operations are being planned where people can `` shop and ship,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> added. Similar to the postal substations run by many small town stores, these operations would allow shoppers to buy something at a store, have it wrapped, and then take it to a counter in the mall for mailing to a friend or relative without having to make a special trip to a post office.
</TEXT>
