<HEAD>Historians on Nixon's Resignation: It Hurt, But Ultimately Helped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifteen years after <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> resigned as president to avoid the disgrace of removal from office, historians and political observers say the republic paid a price but ultimately benefited from the ordeal. And, they say, the impact of <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s crisis has been felt by every president who followed him; chief executives since <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> have been more cautious, candid and constrained. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchen </PERSON>, who served as an adviser to <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s successor, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, says that in retrospect <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s resignation was `` wholesome. Political scientist <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, author of `` Managing the Presidency,'' says the experience left <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s successors `` pretty skittish for a while.'' He thinks <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, for one, overreacted and was too weak. Historian <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkendall </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> says that while the event damaged the presidency, `` it would have left us with more serious problems if <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> had been able to get away with it.'' Political scientist <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> says the founding fathers `` pretty clearly expected that the impeachment process would be used more often than it has.'' He says <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` has been intruding on executive functions'' since it found the strength in 1974 to move toward the removal of a president. A dissent comes, however, from <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartmann </PERSON>, who served as White House counselor to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>. He says the near-impeachment of <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> was unforunate. `` There are other political remedies which are more routine and which can make presidents toe the mark and put the fear of God in them if they're over-reaching,'' <PERSON> Hartmann </PERSON> contends. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, can deny funds for presidential projects. `` Congress can so fix his clock that he ca n't do anything,'' <PERSON> Hartmann </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Buchen </PERSON>, however, says <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s continued tenure in office `` was having an adverse effect on the morale of the country and its status around the world. It could have led to a threatening international incident. We did not have a president who was actively governing.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, he says, was concerned solely with his own survival that summer 15 years ago. On the night of Aug. 8, 1974, a few days after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> had recommended impeachment, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> went on television to announce that he would resign, becoming the first and only president to have done so. He said he no longer had `` a strong enough political base in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>'' to carry out the duties of office. Three days earlier, he had surrendered the `` smoking gun'' Watergate tape. It revealed that within a week of the break-in at <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters at the Watergate in 1972, he had ordered an end to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation. Whatever remaining support <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> had in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> collapsed. The morning after <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s speech, he resigned in a letter to the secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION>, and Vice President <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> took the oath. `` Our Constitution works,'' the new president said. `` Our great republic is a government of laws and not of men.'' With the passage of time, a sampling of historians and political observers shows agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s assessment and these two points: _ Under the circumstances, <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s resignation was healthy for the country _ The impact on <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s successors has been to curtail presidential adventurism, to check the strong-president, weak-Congress trend that started with <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> and to promote presidential candor and accountability `` I think the initial effect was to make presidents much more sensitive to the concerns of the public,'' said <PERSON> Buchen </PERSON>, the ex-Ford adviser. `` That was true of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>. It began to slip at the end of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration or we would n't have had the Iran-Contra affair.'' But even in the Iran-Contra affair, noted <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, director of governmental studies at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, the record shows that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s people used the word `` impeachment'' when discussing the possible consequences of <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s secret Contra-funding activities. It is important that they were sensitive to the possibility of impeachment, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said, adding: `` The legacy of <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> assures us that some warning signals are present for successive presidents.'' `` Even a strong president like <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> found himself substantially constrained by an active <PERSON> Congres </PERSON> and a whole new set of statutes restricting presidential power,'' he said. Watergate resulted in laws in these areas _ freedom of information, limits on presidential war-making powers and a president's ability to impound funds appropriated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and limits on campaign contributions. <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> political scientist, said he finds it `` almost alarming that it came to the point that we almost had to do the same thing with <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>.'' He said the president's age, his popularity and his nearness to finishing his term saved <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> from an impeachment attempt, but he finds <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s escape worrisome, `` very seriously damaging to the fiber of the republic.'' <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranney </PERSON>, chairman of the political science department at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, said the difference between Watergate and Iran-Contra is that <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> knew what was happening while <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` always denied that he knew what was going on.'' As for whether the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> experience was good for the country, <PERSON> Ranney </PERSON> said it is never good to have a law-breaking president `` but it was a wonderful thing that our system of justice and separation of powers worked to remove a president without an assassination or violence of any kind.'' With the exception of <PERSON> Hartmann </PERSON> _ who said `` we will never know'' _ the experts interviewed agreed <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> could not have avoided removal from office had he not resigned. At the time he quit, every member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> had announced support for his impeachment by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and even such staunch supporters as Sen. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., had warned <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> he could not win in a trial by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` People had had it with <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and were finally ready to listen to the evidence,'' said <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>. `` There's no question he would have been impeached by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would have convicted him,'' said <PERSON> Ranney </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kirkendall </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s conduct in office shows that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has learned Watergate's lesson. He noted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> consults conspicuously with congressional leaders and allies before making major moves. `` He makes a big thing of it,'' he said. <PERSON> Ranney </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and others have learned `` that you ca n't get away with anything. Sooner or later, truth will out. And the truth shows that if you violated the law, you will take the consequences.''
</TEXT>
