<HEAD>Corbin Bernsen Stars in World War II Thriller</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON> was looking for a new acting experience when he accepted the lead role in the mind-bending thriller `` Breaking Point'' on cable television. He plays a World War II <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> intelligence officer whose capture just weeks before D-Day gives the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> an opportunity to pry out the invasion secrets in a most diabolical and deceptive manner. `` Breaking Point'' gets its first showing on <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> on Friday and will be repeated Saturday and Sunday. It's a remake of the 1964 film starring <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> `` I did it like an <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON> movie or something from the ` Twilight Zone,''' says <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON>, who stars regularly as lawyer <PERSON> Arnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` <LOCATION> L.A </LOCATION>. Law.'' `` That's what drew me to it. I've always wanted to do something in that genre. Since it's for cable we took risks. The wonderful thing is that after it's approved they leave the artists alone to do their work. It's not as pat as regular television. The experience was that of doing a feature film. I wanted to experience what my character feels, the pain, the torture, the freedom, and to be able to have the audience feel it, too.'' He plays Maj. <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>, who is abducted by the Germans, tortured briefly and wakes to find the war is over and he's in an American hospital. Or so he's led to believe. It's a plot to learn the secrets of D-Day. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON> is the `` American'' doctor and <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Pacula </PERSON> is the nurse he falls in love with after being told his wife has died. `` We filmed the exteriors at <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION>. There's a wonderful old school and a retreat that looks like an Alpine chalet. When I first read the script I said, ` Great, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. I can take my son to meet his grandparents,''' said <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON>, whose wife is English actress <PERSON> Amanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Pays </PERSON>. `` Well, we filmed <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Markle </PERSON> directed, and it has some interesting camera work. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON> and I had a great relationship and I think our scenes are well written and work well. <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>'s led to believe the war's over and he talks about the coming invasion of <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> Then he finds out he's been deceived and he hatches his own deception.'' <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON> did get to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, however. He and his wife spent a month traveling with their four-month-old son <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>. `` Breaking Point'' is <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON>'s first movie for cable. His feature film work in a busy schedule in the past few years included `` Major League,'' `` Disorganized Crime,'' `` <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rigby </PERSON>, You're a Fool'' and `` Hello, Again.'' <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON> said he would talk soon to the producers of `` <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> Law'' to see what would happen to <PERSON> Arnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> next season. `` I know what needs to be done,'' he said. `` He needs some re-evaluation. <PERSON> Arnie </PERSON> has n't quite figured it out. All life has to reproduce but <PERSON> Arnie </PERSON>'s caught in a cycle of refusing to commit himself. He has n't grown up enough to accept the moral conventions. The thing that I put into <PERSON> Arnie </PERSON> is that he senses something is missing. I do n't think I could play a character who does n't recognize it `` I think <PERSON> Arnie </PERSON> is terrified of marriage. As a divorce lawyer he knows all the built-in problems. I think he also sees it as a progression toward death. He's trying to hold onto his youth.'' He said one of the advantages of doing `` Breaking Point'' is that <PERSON> Pike </PERSON> is so different from <PERSON> Arnie </PERSON>. `` It's good to do a character who has his values and his loyalties straight,'' he said. `` After ` <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> Law,' I'd like to do more features. I'll have had seven years of a family and a house and a base. I think it'd be fun to live and work other places in the world. I'd like to base myself in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for a while. I could travel and spend time with my wife and son.'' <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON> grew up in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. His father, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernsen </PERSON> is a former agent and now a producer. His mother, actress <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, has been on the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> soap opera `` The Young and the Restless'' for the past 15 years. He said he occasionally works with his father in developing projects. `` I'm working on an idea for a stage musical and I have an idea for a series for <PERSON> Amanda </PERSON> and myself.''
