<TEXT>
 `` Crusoe'' -LRB- Virgin Vision. VHS-Beta, $ 89.95. Rated PG-13. -RRB- `` Crusoe,'' based on the tale of a shipwreck on a tropical island, is a lush and aesthetically pleasing movie, and as ripe with moral dilemmas as the burdened coconut trees swaying on the beach. In `` Crusoe,'' values come crashing down and savagely splinter the beliefs of the movie's star, <PERSON> Aidan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> plays a greedy young 19th-century slave trader who tempts fate by taking one final and risky expedition to round up more blacks from <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. But his ship becomes ensnared in a vicious autumn storm and all aboard perish, except for <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, who winds up sprawled on a desolate beach. <PERSON> Crusoe </PERSON> learns to endure the solitude and fashions a comfortable shelter for himself on the picturesque island. Before long his isolation is interrupted by visiting natives. He rescues one from a human sacrifice and decides to keep him as a slave. But the native later escapes and is killed. In a provocative twist, <PERSON> Crusoe </PERSON> becomes the hunted and is trapped by another islander. But the two men reach an accord and build something of a friendship. The film's ending is the final test of <PERSON> Crusoe </PERSON>'s new respect for the man he once wanted to enslave. Director <PERSON> Caleb </PERSON> <PERSON> Deschanel </PERSON> so effectively captures the panoramic beauty of the island setting _ with its creamy white sand beaches, dense verdant forests and crystal blue tide pools _ one can almost taste the salt spray in the breeze. There also is very little dialogue, but the engrossing visuals and the moral struggles make for compelling viewing. _ By <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Bibby </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Thrilled to Death'' -LRB- Republic. VHS-Beta, $ 79.95. Rated R -RRB- B-movie fans, beware. `` Thrilled to Death'' is an A, as in absolutely awful. The script is bad, the acting terrible and even the filming is poor with washed-out colors and fuzziness. It's a movie that uses the backdrop of a swingers' club to unravel a tale of murder and drug dealing. Along the way, there's some nudity, strong language and graphic violence Two couples meet and become friends. But one couple has set up the other to take a fall in a drug-and-murder doublecross. <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bahner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> play a mystery novelist and his wife; <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Maris </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> are the bad guys. _ By <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
