<HEAD>Kodak Blames Restructuring for Second Quarter, Half-Year Earnings
Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says its second-quarter profits fell 85 percent, mainly the result of a $ 225 million restructuring charge that was announced last week. Without the special charges, profits still would have dropped 26 percent in the second quarter. The company blames higher costs, including interest expenses and the impact of the strong dollar. Chairman <PERSON> Colby </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> vowed last week and again Tuesday that strong steps would be taken to deal with the slump in operating profits. Nevertheless, the stock fell Tuesday. It was off 62 -LCB- cents at $ 47.50 in late trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Net earnings were $ 60 million, or 18 cents a share, down from a record $ 390 million, or $ 1.20 a share, a year earlier. Sales rose to a record $ 4.5 billion from $ 4.13 billion for the second quarter last year. For the first half, profit fell 60 percent to $ 260 million, or 80 cents a share, from $ 650 million, or $ 2 a share, a year earlier. Sales rose to a record $ 8.4 billion from $ 7.46 billion in last year's first half. The one-time charges cover changes that `` have happened, are happening and will be happening,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. He said the changes could involve layoffs, sale of businesses and discontinuation of products. But the company has not released details about its specific plans. `` That's what we're waiting for. There's been nothing concrete so far,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>, stock analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said the company has already made it clear that the current restructuring is not going to be major by Wall Street proportions. `` It's going to be significant, but not gigantic,'' <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON> said. `` But that leaves the question of whether the company is going to tighten its belt by one notch, two notches or three.'' `` While volume gains so far this year have been gratifying, especially in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, our earnings have not kept pace,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. Some cost-cutting steps may be taken in the company's <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> business segment, which includes copiers, and microfilm and graphics equipment For the second quarter that segment posted a $ 144 million loss, as compared to a $ 92 million second-quarter profit last year. Even without restructuring charges, the segment would only have posted a profit of $ 6 million. `` There seems to be tremendous pressure there for something to happen,'' said <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>.
