<HEAD>House Votes to Increase National Debt Ceiling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House has voted to increase the national debt limit temporarily by $ 70 billion so the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> wo n't go into default while <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is on its summer recess. The bill, approved 231-185 Tuesday and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, adds to the debt ceiling of $ 2.8 trillion only through Oct. 31. By then, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> hopes to complete work on bill boosting the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s permanent borrowing authority to more than $ 3.1 trillion The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> is already bumping up against the $ 2.8 trillion limit and would be unable to meet its obligations by mid-August without additional power to issue debt. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government default would be unprecedented. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the short-term debt extension after blocking, 228-193, an attempt by Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dannemeyer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>., to make the increase contingent upon <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> consideration of an amendment to the Constitution requiring a balanced budget The House actually approved the permanent debt increase when it passed the fiscal 1990 budget last spring, but the legislation has been held up in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Several senators plan to use the must-pass legislation to carry amendments addressing pet priorities, and it could also become the vehicle for a new deficit-reduction effort by congressional leaders and the White House. The national debt has tripled since the beginning of the decade due to the huge budget deficits of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> has been forced to borrow more and more money to finance government spending that exceeds tax receipts. The annual deficits have gone down from their peak of over $ 200 billion a year, but nearly $ 150 billion in red ink will be added to the pool this fiscal year. The Gramm-Rudman budget law, itself passed as part of a 1985 debt bill that first put the limit above $ 2 trillion, mandates that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president reduce the deficit in fiscal 1990 to $ 100 billion. Fiscal 1990 begins Oct. 1. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> commences its four-week summer recess this Saturday. The short-term debt limit bill approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday also included a provision, requested by the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, to change the way the government accounts for its zero-coupon bonds when calculating the debt. The change will lessen the immediate impact the bonds have on the debt.
