<FIRST>r f PM-Route128Slowdown Bjt   08-02 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Route 128 Slowdown, Bjt,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>Route 128's Woes: A Matter of Style As Well As Substance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every morning, traffic moves at a crawl along Route 128, the high technology highway ringing <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Some insiders say the pace of business inside the sleek corporate headquarters along 128 is n't any faster. `` Tactical decisions that take six weeks in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> can take anywhere from six days to six nanoseconds in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> <PERSON> Hager </PERSON>, founder of a public relations firm that represents computer firms on both coasts. After a year of falling profits and employment, many companies along Route 128 are going through a period of painful retrenchment and self-examination, and a common conclusion is that they need to become more agile, less hierarchical and more willing to take risks. In the last week, three of the four largest computer makers in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ announced quarterly losses. Prime's troubles have made it a takeover target, and two other <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> high-tech companies _ <ORGANIZATION> Cullinet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Apollo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ already have been sold this year. Another former high flyer, <ORGANIZATION> Leading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is in bankruptcy. All told, high technology manufacturing companies in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> have eliminated 7,300 jobs in the past year and 36,100 since their peak in December 1984, the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> and Training says. Underlying Route 128's woes are the maturing of the computer industry, the slowdown in the national economy and the stiff competition that minicomputer makers face from workstations and ever more powerful personal computers. But those trends do not entirely explain why some <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> computer firms are still prospering, or why Route 128's <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> counterpart, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, is generally healthy. The substance of Route 128's problem, critics charge, is style: Boston-area executives in their button-down shirts and brown shoes are more cautious and slow-moving than their <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> rivals in polo shirts and Reeboks. `` In <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> companies, the hierarchy seems compressed,'' said <PERSON> Hager </PERSON>. `` An account executive in <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION> might be reporting directly to the president, the CEO or the founder. In <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, that person will speak to the communications manager, who works for the VP of you-name-it, who reports to the executive VP, who whispers to the Main Force.'' In part, <PERSON> Hager </PERSON> said, the different management styles reflect cultural or lifestyle differences. In part, they are a matter of age. `` The high-tech superstructure on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> is run and managed by people in their 30s, and the people who run the high-tech companies on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> are mainly in their 50s and 60s,'' he said. `` People in their 20s and 30s have no fear _ of anything.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Josselyn </PERSON>, a computer market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, agrees that decision-making is slower and product cycles longer along Route 128. `` It's just harder to get people to move on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>,'' he said. Examples abound: _ Wang, which pioneered the market for word processors, lost ground when it failed to move quickly into personal computers It is now making a big push into document imaging products, but it announced a $ 375 million quarterly loss Monday. Some analysts say the family-controlled company may have to find a substantial outside investor. _ <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the state's largest computer maker, also stuck with proprietary operating systems and failed to capitalize on the PC explosion Now it is moving into `` open,'' or non-proprietary, software. But <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings have slipped this year, and it has frozen salaries. _ Data General also is moving away from proprietary systems toward open software and reduced instruction set computing _ or `` risc'' _ technology, which simplifies the circuitry of a computer and allows cost savings In a two-year restructuring, it has cut its work force from 16,000 to 14,000, and posted a $ 23.1 million loss for the quarter ended June 24. Data General spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Klatman </PERSON> calls the critic's charges `` baloney. `` From the time management made the decision to commit to open systems, it took us just nine months to get our first products out the door,'' he said. `` That's something you never would have seen in this industry 10 years ago.'' <PERSON> Klatman </PERSON> and others point out that aside from sales of PCs and workstations, the entire <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computer market is slow. Minicomputer makers have been hit particularly hard, squeezed between mini-supercomputers on the high end and technical workstations on the low end, said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crook </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` It just so happens, it's an accident of nature, that there are more minicomputer makers based in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, and the traditional minicomputer is not growing at the rate of other areas,'' said <PERSON> Klatman </PERSON>.
