<FIRST>r f PM-Princeton-Newport     08-02 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton-Newport,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations On Forfeiture</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Princeton-Newport-RICO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The jury that convicted five former officials of <ORGANIZATION> Princeton-Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION> and a former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> trader of racketeering charges now must decide how much money they will have to forfeit to the government. The jurors began deliberations on the forfeiture issue Tuesday after hearing arguments from both sides. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said the defendants should relinquish salaries and other claims that could total more than $ 21 million. Defense attorneys, who have said they will appeal the conviction, argued that the forfeiture sought by the government was excessive and violated the constitutional ban on cruel and unusual punishment. On Monday, the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> federal court jury convicted the defendants of racketeering, racketeering conspiracy, conspiracy and numerous counts of mail and wire fraud. The case marked the first time securities professionals were accused of racketeering under a controversial federal law aimed at combating mobsters and drug pushers. The Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law provides for heavy fines and lengthy prison terms, in addition to forfeiture. The trial received widespread attention because it grew indirectly out of the <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> insider trading scandal that rocked Wall Street three years ago. The largest forfeiture was sought from former Princeton-Newport partner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>. His partnership interest was placed at $ 13.3 million and his salary at $ 1.75 million. From former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> trader <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON>, the government sought $ 2.5 million in salary. The prosecution asked the jury to require forfeiture for the other Princeton-Newport defendants as follows: former partner <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON>, $ 1.1 million partnership interest and $ 267,483 in salary; former partner <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabinowitz </PERSON>, $ 791,191 partnership interest and $ 454,507 in salary; former partner <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkman </PERSON>, $ 762,613 partnership interest and $ 558,328 in salary; and former controller <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smotrich </PERSON>, $ 124,583 in salary. `` Here's a man who has no money and the government wants him to forfeit millions and millions of dollars,'' said <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>. `` I submit to you that is cruel and unusual punishment.'' But <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> told the jury that the racketeering statute permitted the forfeiture of all interest from an illegal enterprise. `` As they chased the almighty dollar, they crossed far past the line of law,'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. `` You must decide whether the defendants should be stripped of some of their tainted wealth.'' The case involved a series of pre-arranged stock transactions from 1984 to 1986. The government alleged during the five-week trial that the defendants illegally bought and sold stocks to generate phony tax losses. <PERSON> Princeton-Newport </PERSON> went out of business after the indictment was brought last August. Defense lawyers said at the time that the charges alone, though unproven, destroyed the securities firm's ability to do business Besides forfeiture, the defendants face up to 20 years in prison on each of the two racketeering counts, jail terms ranging from five to three years for the other charges and fines. A sentencing date has not been scheduled. Before the lawyers presented their arguments to the jury, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> ruled that the prosecution could not tell the jury about a $ 650 million fine <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> paid to settle securities law charges in another case, which also stemmed from the <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> scandal. Defense attorneys had argued that telling jurors about the fine would prejudice them on the forfeiture question.
