<SECOND>PM-Family Leave,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Pushes for Passage of Unpaid Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Release at 10 a.m. EDT; time set by source. A version moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> families are losing at least $ 607 million a year because the government has n't passed legislation guaranteeing workers unpaid leave to care for young children or sick parents, a group backing such a law said today. `` Year after year, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> families are the big losers because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has failed to pass minimum family and medical leave policies,'' <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenhoff </PERSON> of the Women's Legal Defense Fund said in prepared remarks. `` Working parents should not have to choose between having a job and having a family.'' Legislation is awaiting debate on both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floors that would require employers to provide up to 10 weeks of unpaid leave over a two-year period to meet family needs during the birth or adoption of a child and for family medical emergencies. `` Unnecessary Losses,'' the report for the Family and Medical Leave Act Coalition, was based on a 1988 survey of 7,000 families conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The institute compiles data on a broad range of topics annually and it is then used by researchers who break out and interpret areas of particular interest to them. The analysis said the $ 607 million in family losses `` represents the additional earnings lost by new mothers who return to work, but are unable to return to their former jobs because their employers do n't have parental leave policies in place.'' `` When these new mothers without job-protected leaves return to work but are unable to return to their former jobs, they experience more unemployment and lower wages than those mothers who return after a period of protected leave,'' the report said. Moreover, the report said, taxpayers spend $ 108 million a year on government assistance programs that would n't be necessary if there was a nationwide family and medical leave program. `` Working mothers without job-protected leave receive $ 108 million more in assistance from such programs as unemployment insurance, supplemental security income and welfare than do mothers working for employers with parental leave policies,'' the report said. `` As <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> prepares to leave for their summer break, we wanted to remind our nation's lawmakers that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> families are suffering unnecessary losses due to their inaction on family policies,'' <PERSON> Lenhoff </PERSON> said.
