<HEAD>House Democrats Caucus on Split Over Capital Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with caucus. Picks up pvs 5th graf,
A Republican ... A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Badly divided <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats took their fight over a capital-gains tax cut behind closed doors today and apparently agreed only that opposition should not be a litmus test of party loyalty. Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., said the caucus indicated to him that most Democrats oppose a major cut in capital-gains tax rates, as is favored by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` I believe that is bad tax policy, bad fiscal policy, unwise, inequitable and ill-timed,'' <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said. But he added there has been no talk of retaliating against Democrats who side with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on the issue. `` We do n't have a guillotine around here,'' <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, D-Ga., a Ways and Means member who is chief sponsor of the proposed rate cut, said he has enough votes in committee and in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to pass the plan cutting the tax on profits realized from investments in securities or property Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the committee, said, `` I think there's a hopeful atmosphere of some kind of compromise,'' perhaps along lines of a new plan that he outlined Tuesday His proposal would protect investors from having to pay taxes on gains caused by inflation, but he declined to provide other details. He has said he could not support a reduction in the capital-gains tax rate. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said he planned to present the idea later today to the 13 Republican members of his committee who have joined six Democrats to produce a majority in favor of a rate cut. A Republican committee member, who spoke on condition that he not be identified by name, said there was no chance <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> can persuade Republicans to drop their support of a rate cut, an idea already rejected by the White House. However, the first task facing <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> is to win back at least one of the six Democrats. If he does that, he'll have an 18-18 tie in the committee, and wo n't have to face the caucus in the somewhat embarrassing position of being in a minority on his own committee. One of the six Democrats, Rep. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> called the proposal `` creative'' and said it probably could have drawn wide support if it had been presented earlier. `` It's a pretty sound concept, but six of us are still committed to Mr. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>' proposal,'' <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> referred to another of the six, Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, D-Ga., chief sponsor of a plan to cut the top capital gains tax rate to 19.6 percent for two years, and then raise it to 28 percent and exclude gains caused by inflation The top rate is identical with the top federal income tax rate on other income, 28 percent, or, for certain upper-income taxpayers, 33 percent. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has not formally endorsed <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>' plan, but administration officials have said there was a lot in it they could support. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal would set a top rate of 15 percent, but it would not apply to timber or commercial buildings. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s plan would exempt gains caused by inflation from taxation, but neither he nor <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> would give further details. The change would apply to profits from assets sold after Dec. 31, 1989. Capital gains are increased values of any asset _ stocks, homes, farms, stamp collections or almost anything that has value. All parties agree that a lower capital gains tax rate increases government revenue in the first year or so it is in effect as investors take advantage of the rate reduction to get rid of investments they no longer find of top appeal. The Democratic leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, including <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, has opposed a rate reduction on the grounds that most of the benefits would go to taxpayers making more than $ 100,000 a year. Supporters have argued that denial of rate cuts on those grounds is nonsensical because it hurts the economy and stifles job-creating new investments. The other four Democrats targeted by <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> are <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Flippo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, both of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.
