<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, halfway through another record year, today opened contract talks with union leaders who say they want a wage hike this time instead of the productivity bonuses of the past six years. Negotiations began in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, between <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and three districts of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, which represent 57,800 workers in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>. Representing the union are District 751 president <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Eldridge </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>'s District 70 and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>'s District 24. Aerospace industry analysts say the union is in a strong position to exact a favorable settlement because of a $ 67 billion backlog of commercial airplane orders, $ 346 million in profits in the first half of 1989 and a shortage of skilled workers that forced <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> to borrow <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> workers earlier this year. Union officials say they want an hourly wage increase, likely to be in the double-digits, to replace once-a-year productivity bonuses <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> has given the past six years. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> customers have been irritated by deliver delays for 747-400 model jets. With 44 due for delivery in the last quarter, a work stoppage would jeopardize <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s reputation for reliability. The company borrowed about 600 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> workers earlier this year as it rescheduled delivery dates for the 747-400, and union officials say those workers should be leaving <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> this month. `` I think they will get a wage increase ... I do n't think push is going to come to shove here,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Reich </PERSON>, aerospace analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The chance of a strike is small, say analysts, who believe <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> workers know they are better off riding the crest of record airplane orders than sitting out the good times on a picket line. `` I would not anticipate a prolonged labor disruption or strike,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Deatherage </PERSON>, aerospace analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Not many people at <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> are not aware of the cyclical nature of the business. This is the opportunity of a lifetime -LRB- for workers -RRB- to get all the overtime they can,'' he said. Other union contract requests will cover overtime rules, an improved cost-of-living index, better pension payments, on-site education programs and child care, union officers said. Wages will be the last item discussed. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, led by chief negotiator <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> McKean </PERSON>, vice president of human resources, has until Aug. 9 to make its first counterproposal, with further negotiations scheduled as needed. The union's current three-year contract expires Oct. 3. Before departing for <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION> on Monday, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the union would ask for a `` significant'' wage increase, adding he did not consider a single-digit increase significant. Except for welders, the people who make <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> planes currently earn $ 8.88 to $ 18.42 per hour depending on pay level and seniority. The average wage is $ 13.50 to $ 14 an hour. `` All the signals are that it looks good for us. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> can well afford to pay an increase in wages and increase benefits,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` Our relations have in general been very good with the union,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>. He declined to comment on the negotiations. Union officials want a wage increase to replace, either completely or partially, the bonuses that have ranged from 3 percent to 12 percent a year since 1983. Analysts said a reasonable increase would not affect <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s profitability, especially if it can pass part of the increase on to customers <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> also adjusts its prices as labor and commodity indexes rise. `` Customers may have to take a bite in the next three years'' if a wage hike is granted, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>, senior aerospace analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> He is not related to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrontz </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, has said that <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s goal is to hold down costs to improve profit margins and increase shareholders' return on equity. The union's bargaining position represents a complete turnaround from its position during the 1983 and 1986 negotiations. In 1983, about 12,000 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> workers had been laid off because of the industry slump, weakening the union's hand at the bargaining table.
