<HEAD>GTW Wins $100 Million Libel Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury awarded $ 100 million in libel damages today to <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> after rejecting <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shopping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>'s claim that the communications company was to blame for lost sales <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION> contended <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> did n't give it adequate equipment to handle a large volume of calls in 1986 and 1987 as the network expanded into 11 new markets. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> won the case on its counterclaim. The six-member jury reached its verdict after about five hours of deliberations in the complicated case following a six-week trial before Pinellas Circuit Judge <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rives </PERSON>. The award was to be split evenly by <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communciations </ORGANIZATION>. In a breakdown of each award, the jury said $ 10 million should by paid by <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION>, $ 20 million by board Chairman <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Speer </PERSON> and $ 20 million by President <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Paxon </PERSON>. In final arguments Monday, <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION> attorneys said <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> told `` little white lies'' to the network to cover up the communications company's failure to provide for the volume of calls. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reardon </PERSON> responded that a Dec. 2, 1986, letter placed in evidence documented that <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION> thought the telephone firm had been `` responsive to all our previous needs'' and was looking forward `` to continuing this highly successful relationship.'' Ten months after that, <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION> sued, claiming it lost millions of calls and about $ 500 million in potential sales because its <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> telephone network equipment was insufficient for the volume of calls. The parent company, based in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> subsidiary and <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> were named as defendants. In response, <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> filed a slander and libel counterclaim placing blame for <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION>'s decline in the electronics market and stock market on its own mismanagement there. <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION>'s 1986 purchase of 11 UHF stations in new markets, combined with its entrance into the cable television market, caused subscribers to soar from 9 million to 46.5 million in one year, <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Reardon </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> knew about the cable arrangements, he added. Cable companies were offered a $ 1 million stock option which enhanced their interest in <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION>, he said, and 70 cable outlets were obtained. But, even when <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION> made its initial public offering of stock on May 13, 1986, the company did n't mention its plans to purchase the broadcast stations as a second operational network, <PERSON> Reardon </PERSON> argued. He recalled that <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION> operations vice president <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLany </PERSON> warned in September 1986 the company did n't have enough personnel to handle the growing number of calls, but <PERSON> Speer </PERSON> `` did n't want to hear they needed more operators.'' Competition from similar retailers also has hurt <ORGANIZATION> HSN </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Reardon </PERSON> said.
