<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shares ended sharply higher Wednesday following a strong rally on Wall Street during the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> afternoon. A lack of selling pressure and strong rallies in the retaili and pharmaceutical sectors also combined to push the market higher. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share ended up 15.5 points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,307.8, the session high. At its lowest, the index touched 2,285.8, a fall of 6.5 points. Share prices opened lower but rallied on news of an agreement by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC and <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> with the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> government under which the British and West German electronics giants may resume their joint bid for <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> PLC., a British electronics company. Dealers said trading volume wilted during the afternoon, as the market tracked movements on Wall Street. `` It was a pretty volatile day but it seemed the market wanted to rally after its declines earlier in the week,'' one trader said. Volume was 424.8 million shares, compared with 413.5 million shares Tuesday.
