<HEAD>WPPSS To Re-enter Bond Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> announced plans Wednesday to re-enter the financial markets for the first time since defaulting on $ 2.25 billion in bonds for two nuclear plants in 1983. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> said it plans to sell $ 450 million in revenue bonds to refund higher interest bonds sold in 1981 and 1982. Pricing and sale of the bonds for <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> nuclear plants 1 and 3 are expected to take place the week of Aug. 21. The 1983 default on bonds for nuclear plants 4 and 5 was the largest in municipal bond market history. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> bond ratings were suspended in 1983, but <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> restablished its rating late last year. The refunding bonds are secured by net billing agreements that require the <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, a self-financed federal agency that markets electric power, to pay all costs connected with projects 1 and 3. The net billed bonds are the first step in a long-awaited refunding program to reduce debt service on about $ 2 billion of high interest bonds. The supply system also expects to refund aproximately $ 800 million of high-interest bonds issued for project 2 over the next several years. `` At current interest rates, the program will reduce the supply system's costs an average of $ 70 - $ 80 million a year over the next 30 years,'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazur </PERSON>, supply system managing director, and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jura </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> administrator, said in a statement Following the WPPSS default, an amendment to federal bankruptcy laws clarified that a bankruptcy would not impair protection of revenues, funds and other assets of projects 1, 2 and 3 from claims by projects 4 and 5 bondholders. In contrast to projects 4 and 5, bonds for projects 1 through 3 are secured by net billing agreements with <LOCATION> Bonneville </LOCATION>, which markets power from 30 federal hydroelectric projects, most in the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> basin. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> is a consortium of utilities that was formed in the early 1970s to build the five nuclear plants. Bonneville and participating utilities without interruption have provided funds for all obligations with respect to supply system bonds on projects 1 through 3 since the first bonds were issued in 1971. Project 2 has been in commercial operation since 1984. Projects 1 and 3 are in extended construction delay because the energy they would produce is n't needed presently.
</TEXT>
