<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An advertising agency said Wednesday it had dropped the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION>' $ 5 million-a-year account, saying proprietor <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> intruded too much and recently cut agency fees by 60 percent. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, who has been on trial in a tax evasion case in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, has been depicted in the advertising as the `` queen'' standing on guard making sure everything is perfect at the hotels. The ad agency <PERSON> Taylor-Gordon </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Aarons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> had handled the <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> account for the past three years Agency president <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor-Gordon </PERSON> said her company stands to lose $ 500,000 a year from its decision. `` All of us knew she was queen and we were there to serve her,'' <PERSON> Taylor-Gordon </PERSON> said. `` It was evident in her body language, her imperiousness and her arrogance.'' She described a typical business meeting with Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>: `` She was drinking martinis, and I was drinking <PERSON> Brioschi </PERSON>. There was a lot of tension ... She told me, ` Do n't get comfortable. You're not here for a social event.' Agency officials said she sealed her fate with <PERSON> Taylor-Gordon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aarons </PERSON> when she imposed an arbitrary 60 percent cut in agency fees for May and June. They said Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> was informed of the decision in a letter sent to her home. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> was approached by reporters at the courthouse about the agency's decision, but she said nothing. <PERSON> Taylor-Gordon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aarons </PERSON> was not the first agency to use Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> in ads for the hotel chain, or to dub her the `` queen.'' The approach was apparently effective: occupancy jumped from 24 percent before the ads to 87 percent afterwards, agency officials said.
