<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Soar on News of Big Export Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Cocoa futures snapped a slump and surged Wednesday on rumors that the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, the world's largest producer, had sold 500,000 tons to a major trading house. On other markets, sugar continued rallying in the face of growing demand and the fear of weak yields from Western Eurpoean crops; soybeans fell to a new low for the seventh time in eight days, depressed by wet weather and stuck there because many traders halted trading early to await indictments stemming for a 2 -LCB- - year investigation into commodities trading fraud Cocoa, traded on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Coffee, Sugar and <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, jumped at the opening bell after rumors surfaced that <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Houphet-Boigny </PERSON>, who had been in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in recent days, helped seal a huge export deal with trading company <ORGANIZATION> Philipp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The rumored deal suggested a heightened demand for cocoa, which has languished recently. The size of such a purchase, if confirmed, would also raise the possibility of short-term supply problems. `` As sleepy as the market had been, a lot of traders thought the market was at its technical bottom and as soon as it got a boost from the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> report, there were a lot of people jumping on the bandwagon,'' said <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Henig </PERSON>, who tracks commodities for <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Cocoa climbed $ 66 to $ 70 per ton higher, with the contract for delivery in September at $ 1,327 a ton. Sugar continued gaining because demand is outpacing supply. Early reports that a virus has cut substantially into crop yields in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> helped bolster prices. Sugar climbed .22 cent to .31 cent higher, with October at 14.43 cents a pound. Nervousness over commodity fraud indictments, announced after the close of business Wednesday, had sent some traders to the sidelines early at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat futures prices closed higher, but corn and soybeans were mostly lower. Wheat thrived in the wake of a 100,000-ton buy late Tuesday by the Chinese, and there were rumors they planned a second, equally large purchase. But November soybeans slipped 7 cents, establishing a contract low for the seventh time in eight days. The indictments `` probably kept people away,'' said one trader who asked not to be identified. `` But how much effect it actually had is debatable. A lot of this is already in the market. `` And besides,'' the trader added, `` bearish weather is killing the beans _ not indictments.'' Wheat was unchanged to 2 -RCB- cents higher, with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.90 \ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 1 -LCB- cents higher, with September at $ 2.21 -LCB- a bushel; oats were \ cent to -LCB- cent higher, with September at $ 1.33 \ a bushel; and soybeans were 1 -LCB- cents to 8 -LCB- cents lower, with August at $ 6.08 \ Livestock and pork futures were sharply higher at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle climbed .35 cent to 1.20 cents, with August at 73.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent to .60 cent higher, with August at 83.62 cents pound; live hogs were .23 cent to 1.23 cents higher, with August at 46.35 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to 1.10 cents highe