<HEAD>Sales of New Homes Climb, Possibly Averting Recession</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs to CORRECT factory orders to 0.4 percent sted
0.3 percent; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `Factory orders; Also on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of new homes climbed 5.5 percent in June, the third consecutive monthly increase, the government said Wednesday in a report that gave some economists hope that a rebound in housing will help keep the country out of a recession this year. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said sales of new single-family homes rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 670,000 units in June as sales continued to respond favorably to falling mortgage rates after skidding in March to their slowest pace in more than six years. Mortgage rates, which peaked at 11.22 percent for fixed-rate loans in March, have been falling since that time, helped along by credit easing on the part of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. Optimistic forecasters said they believed a rebound in housing and other credit-sensitive sectors of the economy would be enough to keep the record peacetime expansion chugging along, although at a more modest pace in the second half of the year. `` We are confident that we can avoid a recession,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawler </PERSON>, an economist at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` Housing is recovering from a slump earlier in the year as people respond to lower interest rates.'' But a second economic report Wednesday produced less enthusiasm. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said new orders for manufactured goods remained weak in June, edging up by only 0.4 percent after a steep 2.6 percent drop in May. Factory orders have fallen in three of the past six months, and the widespread view is that manufacturing will weaken further in coming months as businesses cut back their own investment plans. But many economists said they believed strong export sales and a rebound in housing would be enough to keep the economy moving forward. `` If exports continue fairly strong and housing comes back, that will help offset the weakness in other areas,'' said <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON>, an economist with <PERSON> DRI-McGraw </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>. `` We believe we will be able to skim by without a recession.'' Ms. <PERSON> Latta </PERSON> said her optimism was based in part on the fact that sales of both new and existing homes posted good gains in June, even before the biggest part of the drop in mortgage rates had occurred in July. Fixed rate mortgages are currently averaging 9.81 percent, their lowest level since early 1987. Economists are predicting further declines in the months ahead as the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> continues easing credit in an effort to prevent a recession. `` Buyers are taking advantage of falling interest rates to buy the most they can afford,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION>. `` The continued decline in rates is drawing buyers to new homes as well as existing homes.'' The 5.5 percent rise in new home sales in June followed a 4.3 percent May advance and a 9.7 percent rise in April. Altogether, the three months of increases have driven home sales 20.7 percent above their low point of the year, an annual rate of 555,000 sales in March, which was the weakest sales pace since December 1982 in the depths of the last recession. Home prices were up as well in June with the median price of a new home jumping 8.3 percent to $ 129,900. The median price means half the homes sold for more and half for less. The average price of a new home was up 8.4 percent to $ 159,100. Housing analysts said part of the increase reflects the fact that much of the market is composed of move-up buyers who can afford more expensive homes. The June increase in sales was powered by a 23.4 percent jump in sales in the West, which climbed to an annual rate of 232,000 units. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> real estate market is currently the strongest in the country. Sales in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> were up as well but by a smaller 3.1 percent to an annual rate of 99,000 units. Sales in the South edged up 1.9 percent to a rate of 267,000 units. The increases were enough to offset a giant 18.2 percent drop in new home sales in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, which fell to an annual rate of 72,000 units. Analysts said that the Northeast, until last year the hottest market in country, was suffering from a sharp run-up in prices. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Seiders </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION>, said he believed price declines were inevitable in this region, especially given the high inventory of unsold homes being carried by many developers.
</TEXT>
