<HEAD>World's Stock Markets Reach Record Levels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As Wall Street's rally resumed Wednesday, major stock market indexes set records in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>. The American stock exchanges are not the only ones that have rebounded from the world stock market crash of Oct. 19 and 20, 1987. In fact, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks trails other major indexes in its recovery. Stock prices rose Wednesday in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the world's biggest stock market, but remained below the record high set in Monday's session. The <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market was the first to climb back above the highs reached in 1987. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> shares remained below their 1987 peaks but set a post-crash high, influenced by the rally on Wall Street and rallies in retailing and pharmaceutical stocks. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 index rose to 2,307.8. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, share prices recovered from their early weakness to close slightly higher in thin trading. The CAC index of French shares reached a record high of 505.9. In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, foreign buying of blue-chip stocks kept a rally going on the <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> exchange. <ORGANIZATION> Daimler-Benz </ORGANIZATION>, maker of Mercedes cars, was again the strongest performer. The exchange's Dax index entered record territory during the session but slipped back. In <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> stock market index set a record 6,208.77, rising in harmony with other European exchanges. In the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, stock prices were mixed but there were enough gainers to push the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> main market index to a record for a third consecutive session. The CBS general shares index hit 201.6. In <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, the bull run in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> continued with an 18th record in 20 sessions. Forestry shares led the way. The Affaersvaerlden index closed at 1,317.2. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s news of a resurgence of inflation failed to hurt the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> stock market, where the main index jumped to a record 1,153. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> ended up 0.88 points at 34,899. It surpassed 35,000 for the first time at the end of morning trading but then retreated. So far this year the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stock market has risen 23.5 percent; the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> stock market is up 27 percent; the Japanese market is up 9.6 percent; and the West German market is up 19.3 percent, when measured in local currencies, according to statistics compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Perspective </ORGANIZATION>, a Geneva-based subsidiary of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment banking firm. In the very long term, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s stock prices are up nearly 1,600 percent since 1969, while American prices are up a relatively meager 320 percent.
