<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorneys are haggling over millions of dollars in the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' strike-bankruptcy case, but all <PERSON> Beatrice </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovinger </PERSON> wants is the $ 3,720 she spent on now-useless Eastern tickets for her family. `` I'm a grandmother,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lovinger </PERSON>, 57, told a public meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> creditors Wednesday. `` It's pretty horrible that big business can do this to me ... and I can be out this amount of money. I'm overwrought about it.'' Ms. <PERSON> Lovinger </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, says she purchased 13 tickets for her children and grandchildren in January so they could fly from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> for a family gathering in mid-April. Eastern's three unions struck March 4, grounding the Miami-based carrier and forcing it to seek the refuge of Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. Ms. <PERSON> Lovinger </PERSON> joined the thousands of other hapless ticketholders caught by the strike, hoping a federal bankruptcy court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> will make sure Eastern compensates them. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s sister carrier, has been honoring <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> tickets, but Ms. <PERSON> Lovinger </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> offered only to put her and relatives on standby status. She wants her money back or guaranteed seats. `` I need the tickets the way I bought them,' she told about 60 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> attorneys, creditors, shareholders and employees at Madison Square Garden's Felt Forum in midtown <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. On July 21, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> filed a proposed reorganization plan, which it said would provide for full repayment of the $ 3.3 billion owed to all creditors including ticketholders. Under the plan, people like Ms. <PERSON> Lovinger </PERSON> could exchange their tickets for cash with interest or more valuable tickets on the post-bankruptcy Eastern. But the plan must receive approval by the bankruptcy court and other creditors first, so Ms. <PERSON> Lovinger </PERSON> could be in for a long wait. `` This example is symptomatic of a problem we see coming up,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Flug </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said of the grandmother's case. <PERSON> Flug </PERSON>, who also attended the Eastern meeting, said <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> has heard of dozens of similar cases. Consumers Union, the non-profit consumer advocacy group that publishes Consumer Reports magazine, has asked the court to require Eastern to reimburse passengers before the company pays off other creditors.
