<HEAD>With AM-Commodities Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Exchanges Move To Bolster Confidence Following Indictments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials at the world's two largest commodities exchanges moved quickly Wednesday to bolster public confidence after a federal grand jury indicted 46 traders on charges of making illegal trades. But ordinary traders at bars near the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in the downtown <LOCATION> LaSalle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> financial district took a more low-key view of the indictments. Several traders refused to comment on the indictments, while others expressed mixed opinions about the federal probe that resulted in charges ranging from tax fraud to racketeering. Those traders willing to comment refused to identify themselves. `` If they're dirty, then they deserve it,'' one trader shouted over his shoulder as he walked out of The Trade Inn across from the Board of Trade building. But other traders questioned the validity of the indictments, which resulted from a 2 -LCB- - year undercover <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation at the two exchanges The charges involve such violations as pre-arranged trading, altering trading records and withholding customer orders from the market in order to dole them out to compatriots. From the indictments emerge a picture of several dozen traders, none of whom are considered especially influential, who allegedly conspired to skim profits from customers' accounts and hide the profits from the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Some traders at the Limit Up Bar in the <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> building portrayed several of those indicted as basically honest brokers who were not smart enough to cheat. `` There are things that look real dishonest that are done for the good of the customers,'' said one trader, who has been a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> for 10 years. He refused to elaborate on what practices he meant. The trader said he thought the federal investigation has focused so far on traders who had done little wrong. `` They're taking honest people and turning them into crooks,'' said the trader. `` If they're looking for something bigger, that's fine, great. The trader and two colleagues sitting at the bar denied ever breaking exchange rules and defended the record of most traders. `` That's very good if all they can find is 24 bad apples'' out of the 2,724 seats on the Mercantile exchange, he said. The government announced indictments of 22 traders at the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and 24 at the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>. The exchanges were not accused of wrongdoing and neither were any of the scores of brokerage firms whose customers were allegedly cheated. Officials at both exchanges said those traders under indictment would be barred from trading except for their own personal accounts. When asked about the number of indictments, <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> told a news conference that `` one was too many'' and vowed to protect the integrity of the exchange. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> had launched its own investigation of traders before reports about the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> probe surfaced in January, but was asked by federal authorities to hold off while the government investigation continued. CBOT President <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> said the exchange has since moved to improve its computer surveillance system so that it will be able to audit all transactions within one business day and stiffen its maximum fines for violations from $ 75,000 to $ 250,000. <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> said the board would conduct its own investigation into the practices of the indicted traders and revoke the trading privileges of anyone who pleads guilty or is convicted on charges stemming from the probe. `` Without integrity being a major part of the way we do business, we can not exist,'' <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> told the news conference. At the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, chairman of the executive committee, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Geldermann </PERSON>, chairman of the board of governors, issued a statement promising to deal `` severely'' with any member found guilty of the federal charges. They said the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> had commissioned a special committee to review all trading practices.
